<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catfish Hunter Regains Consciousness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter regained  
consciousness today and responded to commands, but the Hall of Fame 
pitcher still was in critical condition after injuring his head in 
a fall at his home. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is conscious and responding to commands -- wiggle your toes  
and that sort of thing,'' said Doug Boyd, a Pitt County Memorial 
Hospital spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The 53-year-old Hunter, who suffers from amyothrophic lateral  
sclerosis -- an irreversible deterioration of the muscles -- fell 
Sunday while negotiating concrete steps outside his home in 
Hertford, a friend said. 
</P>
<P>
	Family spokesman Keith Vaughan, pastor of the Hertford Baptist  
Church, said today that Hunter's condition showed ``slight 
improvement overnight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boyd said the Hunter family wasn't talking to the media. ``The  
family is very private right now,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter's wife Helen, however, issued a statement expressing  
gratitude for the solicitude of friends and fans of Hunter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The outpouring of love and support for us and for Jimmy is a  
tremendous encouragement to us,'' she said. ``Over the last year, 
we have been constantly encouraged by the calls, letters and phone 
calls from all over the world expressing their love and 
appreciation for Jimmy. Many people have asked what they can do. 
The greatest thing you can do for us at this time is to pray for 
Jimmy and all the thousands who suffer from ALS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he was injured, Hunter was taken to an Edenton hospital and  
then was transferred early Monday to the Greenville hospital, which 
serves the East Carolina University medical school and is a 
high-level trauma center for eastern North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Harrell, who lives next door to the Hunters, spent much of  
Tuesday on the phone with several of Hunter's former teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrell wasn't optimistic about his friend's condition.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's had some bad knocks before, but this is the worst,'' said  
Harrell. ``The only thing people can do right now is pray for 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Harrell said Mrs. Hunter is handling the latest setback  
well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Helen's tough,'' Harrell said. ``She's got a strength that a  
whole lot of people don't have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Childhood friend Charles Woodard said Hunter fell around 5:30  
p.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was outside seeing off a friend and was going back up the  
steps to his house when his feet got tangled,'' said Woodard. ``He 
just fell backward and hit his head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former major league pitcher was diagnosed in September with  
ALS, or Lou Gehrig's disease, a neurological disease that 
interferes with the signals the brain sends to the muscles. Over 
time, the muscles degenerate. The cause is unknown, and there is no 
cure. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter pitched for 15 years, winning 224 games, including a  
perfect game. He received five World Series rings while playing for 
the Kansas City and Oakland Athletics and the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Boyd said Hunter hasn't undergone surgery since he was admitted  
to the hospital. However, his head injuries caused blood clots on 
his brain, and he was undergoing a series of tests, The Pilot and 
Ledger Star of Norfolk, Va., reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors in Greenville are consulting with others at The Johns  
Hopkins University School of Medicine in Baltimore, who are 
treating Hunter's ALS. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
