<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Questions Gore on Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES (AP) -- Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, seeking  
to capitalize on what an aide to Vice President Al Gore now says 
was a miscue, questioned Gore's commitment to abortion rights 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I respect a woman's right to choose, and that includes women  
who are poor,'' Bradley said, referring to a story in last Sunday's 
editions of The Des Moines Register about Gore's position on 
abortion. The two men are vying against each other for the 
Democratic Party's presidential nomination next year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Gore spokesman Roger Salazar said the vice  
president did not believe that federal money should be used to pay 
for abortions, except to save the life of the mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Salazar, reached Wednesday night to comment on Bradley's  
statement, said he gave the newspaper bad information. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did not do my research.'' Salazar said. ``The vice president  
opposes any attempt to restrict Medicaid funding for abortions. He 
has fought to guarantee that Medicaid recipients who are victims of 
rape or incest should have access to abortion, in addition to those 
whose lives are endangered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, federal law has prohibited the use of federal funds,  
including Medicaid, to pay for abortions except in cases of rape, 
incest or instances where the mother's life is endangered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
