<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Mayor Gets House Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The ex-mayor of Camden on Wednesday avoided  
prison for illegally receiving $20,833 in salary from his former 
post as school superintendent after he became mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Arnold W. Webster, 68, could have faced up to 16 months in  
prison, but the federal judge granted a request for no 
incarceration from Webster's lawyer, who noted that the former 
mayor is blind and suffers from a heart condition and diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Webster was sentenced to six months' house arrest and  
three years of probation. U.S. District Judge Alfred M. Wolin also 
ordered him to repay all the money and assessed a $1,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster was sworn in as mayor earlier than scheduled and a  
school computer kept sending him checks because it didn't have the 
new date in its system, Webster's lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Webster is the second official of the Camden school district,  
which has 20,000 students, to admit wrongdoing in less than two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Former school board president Elaine A. Bey served five months  
in prison after pleading guilty to embezzling more than $24,000 in 
school funds for personal use, including liquor and adult movie 
rentals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
