<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisco Report Pushes Dow Higher / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher today as a battered market  
revived, due in part to a better-than-expected earnings report from 
networking company Cisco Systems. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 44.00 points at 10,699.15. This morning's gains followed through 
on a rebound that began Tuesday afternoon, when the Dow and other 
indicators regained some of the ground lost in early steep 
selloffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher today. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 9.10 at 1,290.53, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was up 22.54 at 2,512.65. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the market was ripe for a modest rally following a  
slump that has left every major market index well below the lofty 
records reached in mid-July. But most Wall Street players expect 
market jitters to endure through Aug. 24, when Federal Reserve 
policy-makers hold their next meeting to set interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed is widely expected to raise short-term interest rates  
for the second time this year, hoping to prevent inflation from 
creeping into the robust U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	That possibility and growing fears of a third rate hike this  
fall are hurting stocks and bonds alike. Plummeting bond prices 
have pushed up the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to nearly 
two-year highs approaching 6.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	For some investors, rising bond yields have presented an  
attractive alternative to returns on volatile stocks. Other stock 
investors are unsettled that an uptrend in interest rates will cut 
into corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco helped spark buying today, rising 1 7/16 to 60 3/16. Late  
Tuesday, the company reported fourth-quarter earnings that beat 
analysts' estimates, rounding out a fiscal year in which revenues 
grew 43 percent and operating profits improved 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 98.3 million shares, 
well ahead of Tuesday's early pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 3.19 at 606.56, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.95 at 772.72. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.05 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.6 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.0 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 
0.9 percent. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
