<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Want Seat Belt Warning Labels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators want a warning label that  
says young children should not use seat and shoulder belt 
positioning devices in cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration  
proposed requiring the warning label so that seat belt adjusters 
are not used on children under age 6 out of concern they would 
suffer greater injuries in crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This proposal, if adopted, would help parents provide for the  
safety of children,'' Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of after-market, seat-belt-positioning devices have  
been sold in the United States in the last decade. The devices 
often use cloth or clips to lower the shoulder belt for children or 
small adults so the belt does not ride up on their necks. 
</P>
<P>
	However, unlike child seats, they are not regulated by any  
federal motor vehicle safety standard. 
</P>
<P>
	In particular, agency officials are worried that  
belt-positioning devices may cause the lap belt to rise up in a 
crash and rest above the child's hips, increasing the potential for 
abdominal injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency is seeking public comment on the proposed label and  
also whether it should alter federal safety standards to include 
regulation of belt positioners. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Capps, chief executive officer of Blue Ridge  
International Products Co., the largest manufacturer of seat belt 
adjusters in the United States, welcomed the idea of warning 
labels. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue Ridge makes and sells SafeFit, a triangle-shaped nylon  
pouch that fits over the shoulder and lap belts near the buckle. 
</P>
<P>
	Capps said SafeFit has always recommended using the product for  
children over 50 pounds, or age 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1990, Blue Ridge has sold more than 4 million of the  
devices in the United States and 23 other countries, Capps said. 
About a half-dozen other companies sell seat belt adjusters. 
</P>
<P>
	Testing done in 1994 by NHTSA, the federal safety agency,  
indicated the belt-positioning devices generally performed 
adequately in restraining a 6-year-old dummy, but the 3-year-old 
dummy registered increased risk of head injuries in a variety of 
tests. In many tests, the seat belts were generally more effective 
in restraining the dummies without the adjuster than with it. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency recommends that children weighing 20 pounds to 40  
pounds, or are roughly 1 to 4 years old, should be in child seats. 
Once they outgrow child seats, the agency recommends that children 
ride in booster seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``The data show that a 6-year-old child restrained in a  
belt-positioning booster seat is provided a greater level of safety 
protection than when using a seat belt positioning device,'' a 
32-page agency document on the issue said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Capps noted most children do not use booster seats after  
they have outgrown child seats. They are instead transferred to the 
ill-fitting adult shoulder belts that ride up on their necks. 
</P>
<P>
	``These children would have injuries (in crashes) without the  
shoulder belt adjuster because they're going to put the shoulder 
belts behind their back,'' Capps argued. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
