<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Renewal Pioneer Dead at 82 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- William L. Slayton, an urban renewal pioneer  
who headed a federal agency charged with renewing American cities, 
is dead at age 82. 
</P>
<P>
	He died Saturday at Georgetown University Hospital after  
suffering a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Slayton was commissioner of the Urban Renewal Administration in  
the Housing and Home Finance Agency under Presidents Kennedy and 
Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Department of Housing and Urban Development was formed  
in 1966, Slayton left government service and became executive vice 
president or Urban American, creator of the National Urban 
Coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his government assignments, at the State Department,  
Slayton was responsible for overseeing the design and construction 
of a number of embassies and other federal facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	His career also included a stint as executive vice president of  
the American Institute of Architects. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
