<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 18:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Anderson, Falcons Agree to Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson, who  
missed the first two weeks of training camp because of a contract 
dispute, agreed to a five-year, $32 million deal with the Atlanta 
Falcons after nearly four hours of talks Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and his agent, Jim Sims, reached the accord after  
meeting at a Greenville hotel with Falcons coach Dan Reeves and 
general manager Harold Richardson. The running back will get a 
signing bonus of $7.5 million, becoming the highest-paid player in 
Atlanta history. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who set a franchise record with 1,846 yards rushing  
and an NFL mark with 410 carries as the Falcons advanced to the 
Super Bowl last season, will join the team for a light practice 
Thursday afternoon. He won't play in Friday night's first 
exhibition game against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's missed some time, but we know he can make it up because  
he's a veteran and the system hasn't changed,'' Reeves said. 
``He'll be ready for the season opener against the Vikings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said he wanted to complete a deal by Friday, knowing  
that marks a month to go until the Sept. 12 contest against 
Minnesota, a rematch of last year's NFC championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	``A month is plenty of time to get ready,'' he said. ``Most guys  
will tell you that you really don't need to be in training camp for 
five or six weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson made an early-morning appearance on an Atlanta radio  
station before joining Sims in a stretch limousine for the 2 1/2-hour 
drive to Greenville. The player looked tired and frazzled after the 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a bit shellshocked,'' Sims said.  
</P>
<P>
	Still, Anderson managed to display a bit of the wit that made  
him one of Atlanta's most popular athletes. He promised to unveil a 
new version of his ``Dirty Bird'' dance and joked that Reeves 
agreed to the deal when challenged to a boxing match. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately for Hollywood, I won't be able to do any feature  
films during the football season,'' the 26-year-old Anderson said. 
``But I'm happy it's over with. I want to play and it's great to 
see my teammates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sides basically agreed on the length and value of the  
contract but stumbled over the signing bonus, guaranteed money and 
structure of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson will become one of the highest-paid running backs in  
the NFL, according to his agent. He still trails Denver's Terrell 
Davis, who has a nine-year, $59 million deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves initially scoffed at Sims' request for a face-to-face  
meeting, hinting that it was a publicity stunt. But the coach 
conceded afterward that it was a good idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is better when you sit down face to face,'' Reeves said.  
``With the four of us there, we were able to get a lot of things 
cleared up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after Anderson and Sims arrived at the hotel in their  
limo, Reeves and Richardson pulled up in a green Buick. Reeves, who 
has final say in contract matters, sat in on the talks for over an 
hour before leaving the hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a good meeting, but I've got to go to practice,''  
the coach said. ``I'm late.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Falcons held training camp at nearby Furman  
University, Richardson remained behind to continue the talks with 
Anderson and Sims. Finally, shortly after 5 p.m., the weary-looking 
Anderson emerged from the meeting room, saying he was hopeful of a 
deal getting done. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, the only thing that remained was getting the approval  
of Reeves and Falcons owner Taylor Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and Sims crawled back into their limo and followed  
Richardson's car to the Furman campus through rush-hour traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson emerged from the vehicle at the player dormitories and  
pumped his arms in the air just as three of his offensive linemen -- 
Ephraim Salaam, Calvin Collins and Bob Whitfield -- pulled into the 
parking lot on a golf cart. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, big money!'' Collins yelled.  
</P>
<P>
	Anderson embraced all three before jumping on the golf cart and  
riding away with them to their dorm room. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I saw him today, it was a great sight for sore eyes,''  
linebacker Jessie Tuggle said. ``To get in here now, it's still 
early, and I think the days he missed won't hurt him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons tried to carry on normally during Anderson's  
two-week-long holdout, but it was clearly a distraction for a team 
trying to follow up its first NFC championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't agree with what he did, and he knows that. He had a  
contract and I thought he should honor it,'' Reeves said. ``But 
that's part of the business. If you let it become personal ... it 
can get in the way of getting something done. We want to put it 
behind us and move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, set to make $2.6 million in the final year of his  
current contract, refused to report for the start of training camp 
July 29 without a new deal. He has since accumulated $70,000 in 
fines, but Reeves would not say if he still planned to collect the 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims had raised the possibility of asking for a trade if  
Wednesday's talks didn't produce an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we don't get it done, I think from that point on we'll  
really have to push the trade option,'' Sims said Tuesday night. 
``He's not retiring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves flatly rejected the idea of trading Anderson to another  
team, and the sides finally worked out their differences. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
