<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bucks Coach Doesn't Want GM Duties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Milwaukee Bucks coach George Karl says he does  
not want to take on the additional duties of general manager now 
that the team has decided not to renew Bob Weinhauer's contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to do both jobs. I have never said I'd do both  
jobs,'' Karl said Wednesday after throwing out the first pitch at 
the Milwaukee Brewers game with the Colorado Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Karl has taken added responsibility for roster and personnel  
decisions over the last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think right now we're looking to improve a little more.  
I think we're just trying to make this the best situation in 
basketball,'' Karl said. '' But I don't have time to do both 
jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karl said he wanted to work closely with Weinhauer's  
replacement. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, I want a good working relationship. I want an  
opportunity to have a say in what goes on. And we all battle 
together, fight together,'' Karl said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Karl's first season as coach, the Bucks returned to the  
playoffs for the first time since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Karl said Weinhauer also was responsible for the success because  
of deals he had made to acquire key players. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Bob did a great job in helping us get back in the  
playoffs. And I wish him the best,'' Karl said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bucks recently lost Michael Curry and Dell Curry, free  
agents who signed with other clubs after playing key roles as 
reserves. Karl said their loss bothered him but he did not 
criticize what the team did to retain them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't deny that I'm disappointed,'' Karl said. ``I thought  
last year one thing we developed was our bench. And that now has 
changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I also think our organization did what they were supposed  
to do with the offers that were made. We did everything possible to 
get those players back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
