<HEADLINE> Calif. Poster Protest Man Gets Jail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTMINSTER, Calif. (AP) -- A shopkeeper who sparked weeks of  
demonstrations by hanging a picture of Ho Chi Minh in his store in 
Little Saigon has been sentenced to 90 days in jail for video 
piracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Truong Van Tran, 37, was found guilty on the felony charge  
Tuesday during a non-jury trial. He also was sentenced to three 
years probation and 80 hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
	Police raided Tran's HiTek video shop in March, seizing about  
15,000 allegedly pirated videos, mostly of Asian soap operas. 
</P>
<P>
	Tran had faced up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine.  
</P>
<P>
	His attorney, Ron Talmo, said Tran will appeal. He said Tran did  
nothing wrong by renting and copying the tapes. 
</P>
<P>
	Tran had said he put up the Ho Chi Minh display to encourage his  
Vietnamese neighbors to see their homeland in a new light. The 
displays attracted protests for 53 days, with crowds of up to 
10,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the neighborhood's 200,000 residents are former  
political prisoners or refugees who despise Vietnam's communist 
government. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
