<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Track Athlete Going for Jackpot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- A leading contender for a gold medal  
at the World Championships relied on his powers of persuasion to 
stay in the running for a Grand Prix track bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Barmasai, world record-holder in the 3,000-meter  
steeplechase, told speeding Kenyan compatriot Christopher Koskei to 
drop back just before the end of the race Wednesday in the 
Weltklasse meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said `Leave it for me' and that's why he slowed down,''  
Barmasai told stunned journalists shortly after clocking a winning 
time of 8 minutes, 5.16 seconds -- a fraction ahead of Koskei. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris could have won, but because he is my friend and we have  
to live together, he let me win,'' said Barmasai, who has posted 
the season's four best times in the steeplechase and is the only 
athlete to run under 8 minutes this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Barmasai is one of four athletes with a chance for the Golden  
League jackpot of $1 million awarded to any athlete unbeaten after 
the seven biggest Grand Prix meets. There are now just two meets 
left. 
</P>
<P>
	He indicated that -- if successful -- he would share the spoils  
with his friends -- presumably including Koskei. 
</P>
<P>
	In track, the use of runners who set a fast pace at the start  
and drop out later to help set up records is common. But Barmasai's 
confession of collusion at the end of the race was surprising. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethiopia's Haile Gebrselassie, the 5,000-meter world  
record-holder and winner his race Wednesday, said Barmasai had no 
need to cut deals with rivals or compatriots. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barmasai is a top athlete. He has sprint and distance power,''  
Gebrselassie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Denmark's Wilson Kipketer, another Golden League jackpot  
contender, stressed that running was an individual rather than team 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	``The jackpot is important. But the main thing is to run the  
race,'' Kipketer said. ``You can't get paid until you do the job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Kipketer said a dangerous bout of malaria following training  
last winter in his native Kenya gave him other values apart from 
money and glory. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I had malaria, I was fighting life and death,'' Kipketer  
said. ``I'm lucky to be running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American Marion Jones kept up her claim to the Golden League  
jackpot by winning the 200 in 22.10 seconds, extending her unbeaten 
streak in the event to 21 races. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I felt the tailwind on the straight, I was flying home,''  
said Jones, the only woman to run under 22 seconds this summer. ``I 
hope I'll do as well in Seville. That's what I'm training for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unbeaten in the event since 1997, the 23-year-old American is a  
strong favorite heading into the World Championships in Seville, 
Spain, later this month. She has a chance for four world titles. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth Golden League jackpot contender is Romania's  
3,000-meter specialist Gabriela Szabo, who set a meet record of 
8:25.03. She said that her main priority was not the Seville 
championships or the Grand Prix payout, but next year's Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	In an intriguing men's 1,500, world record-holder Hicham El  
Guerrouj of Morocco bested a strong field that included Kenyan 
sensation Noah Ngeny and Olympic champion Noureddine Morceli. 
</P>
<P>
	El Guerrouj finished in 3:28.57 -- almost three seconds slower  
than his own world record. Ngeny finished second, while Morceli 
finished seventh, 3.62 back. 
</P>
<P>
	American Maurice Greene, who broke the world 100-meter record  
earlier this year, won the last major 100 before the World 
Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Fighting a slight headwind, Greene finished in 9.99 seconds to  
collect his fifth straight victory. Obadele Thompson of Barbados 
finished second, 0.03 seconds behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his string of successes, Greene said he still had not  
accomplished a perfect race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, it will come out in a meet sometime,'' Greene said.  
</P>
<P>
	He said he was unaffected by the withdrawal due to injury of his  
rival, friend and training partner, Ato Boldon of Trinidad, and the 
absence of Olympic champion Donovan Bailey of Canada. The American 
said he preferred to concentrate on his own performance rather than 
other racers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
