<HEADLINE> Miller Tries a Comeback With Broncos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREELEY, Colo. (AP) -- Anyone who wanted to know if Chris Miller  
could still play football just needed to watch the former all-pro 
quarterback last weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing with second and third-string players, Miller, 34,  
completed 11 of 13 passes for 136 yards Saturday and directed the 
Broncos to the tying and winning field goals over the San Diego 
Chargers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have gone over everything and I am just getting familiar  
with the system,'' Miller said Wednesday at training camp. ``Once 
you know what you are doing and had enough reps, you can do less 
thinking and let things happen more naturally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller left the game in 1995 after a series of concussions, but  
joined the Broncos again because he knew he could play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Physically I felt great, my arm felt good and mentally I feel  
sharp,'' he said. ``That is the big reason why I came back. If I 
couldn't throw the ball like this I wouldn't have thought about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive coordinator Gary Kubiak concurred: ``There is nothing  
wrong with Chris Miller. ``The guy can play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before retiring, Miller had thrown for 18,793 yards and 121  
touchdowns in nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	The only difference Miller has discovered between his former  
teams and the Broncos is the terminology. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to get used to it if you hadn't been familiar with  
the West Coast offense because there is a lot of memorization,'' 
Miller said. ``Some of our play calls are 15 to 16 words long and 
that takes some getting used to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller offers Shanahan the luxury of an experienced backup to  
Bubby Brister and Brian Griese as well as a veteran player who 
accepts his role. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the third-string quarterback. Bubby is the starter and  
Brian is No. 2,'' Miller said. ``The plan of Gary Kubiak is just to 
get me to where I am familiar with everything, where when I go in 
there I'm not hurting us, slowing things down and I am not making 
mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller suffered a minor setback when a sore elbow forced him out  
of workouts on Tuesday and Wednesday. Doctors ruled the injury 
insignificant enough to keep him in the game plan for Saturday's 
game with the Arizona Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``His elbow is sore. All it is tendinitis,'' Shanahan said. ``So  
we gave him a couple of days off. Hopefully, it will be back to 
normal.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
