<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Rep Visits Barry Sanders' Dad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIVERSITY CENTER, Mich. (AP) -- A representative from the  
Detroit Lions is in Wichita, Kan., visiting with the father of 
recently retired running back Barry Sanders. But the elder Sanders 
today said his son wasn't a big topic of conversation. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Hughes, director of security for the Lions, has been at  
William Sanders' home for two days. The Detroit News said today 
that Hughes is visiting apparently in hopes of setting up further 
talks between Sanders, his family and the team's front office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it's the start of something good,'' Sanders' father  
told the News. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by the newspaper if any talks will be a drawn-out affair,  
the elder Sanders said: ``I hope with all my heart it's not 
time-consuming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But today, Sanders said Hughes just came down to spend some time  
with him. He said the two are friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``We discuss Barry once in a while,'' Sanders said. But he said  
he didn't think the Lions had sent Hughes specifically to discuss 
his son's football future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't discuss my son's future because I don't know what my  
son's intentions are,'' he said. He said he hasn't talked with his 
son since before Barry Sanders announced his retirement last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Lions spokesmen with knowledge of the Sanders situation were not  
immediately available for comment this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, who retired from the Detroit Police Department as an  
inspector, has headed the Lions' security department for four 
years. He is a former member of the Harlem Globetrotters. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders announced his retirement July 28, the day before the  
team reported to training camp at Saginaw Valley State University. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Sanders said his desire to quit football outweighed  
his desire to play. When camp opened July 29, Sanders was in London 
on a European vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said it was believed he will return this week.  
Sanders has a home in Rochester Hills. He also spends considerable 
time at his parents' home in Wichita, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	His father earlier said Hughes was sent to Wichita by Lions vice  
chairman William Clay Ford Jr., son of owner William Clay Ford. The 
younger Ford talked to Sanders' father by telephone July 29 and 
told him he would do what he could to talk to Sanders and get him 
back in uniform with the Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think (Hughes) represents Bill Ford,'' William Sanders told  
the News. ``He (Ford) impressed me as being a fine gentleman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But today, Sanders downplayed the Lions' role in Hughes' visit.  
He said Hughes will stay ``as long as my wife will feed him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lions have not made a significant move to replace Sanders.  
Only one back, Jerris McPhail, has been signed who was not on the 
roster at the time Sanders announced his retirement. McPhail was 
with the Lions last year but did not carry the ball or catch a 
pass. He was picked by the Browns in the expansion draft, but was 
cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Rivers, Sanders' backup the last four years, is No. 1 on the  
depth chart. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders has avoided all contact with the Lions' front office and  
coaching staff since the final game of the 1998 season. Coach Bobby 
Ross attempted to contact him through a total of 13 telephone calls 
or handwritten letters, but Sanders did not respond to any of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
