<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> INS: Legal Immigration Rate Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Recording the lowest level of legal  
immigration in a decade, the United States last year granted legal 
permanent residence to 660,477 foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	The green card figures for fiscal 1998, announced Wednesday by  
the Immigration and Naturalization Service, marked a 17 percent 
decrease from 1997 and a 28 percent drop from the year before that. 
</P>
<P>
	The decrease wasn't a reflection of reduced demand, however.  
Rather, it was a sign of the agency's continued difficulty in 
dealing with a rising backlog of applications. INS estimated it 
would have granted legal permanent residence to as many as 140,000 
additional people last year had it been able to keep pace with its 
caseload. 
</P>
<P>
	The backlog currently stands at 890,000 -- a sharp increase from  
the backlog of 121,000 applications in fiscal 1994. With the rising 
caseload, processing times have soared from an average of four 
months in 1994 to as much as three years now. 
</P>
<P>
	``The `S' in INS does stand for service. They may want to  
remember that occasionally,'' said Matt Tallmer, spokesman for the 
American Immigration Lawyers Association. ``Their backlog is just 
atrocious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the backlog owes to Congress' decision in the mid-1990s  
to allow illegal immigrants eligible for legal permanent residency 
to pay a fine and file their paperwork at INS offices within the 
United States. Before, they had to leave the country and apply at 
U.S. consulates abroad, which are operated by the State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The since-ended program, known as 245(i), ``appears to be the  
chief reason for INS' inability to issue green cards expeditiously 
enough,'' said Mark Krikorian, executive director of the Center for 
Immigration Studies, a think tank that favors reduced legal 
immigration rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress placed an enormous burden on the INS at the same time  
as citizenship applications increased dramatically,'' Krikorian 
added. ``Some people are going to point to this as another sign of 
the INS' dysfunction but in fact this is really a consequence of 
Congress' decision, not INS'.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly three-quarters of the green cards granted last year went  
to relatives of U.S. citizens, as expected under a federal 
immigration policy that places highest priority on the 
reunification of families. Another 77,517 green cards were granted 
for business reasons, while refugees and asylees accounted for 
nearly 55,000 cases. 
</P>
<P>
	One-fifth of the legal immigrants admitted last year came from  
Mexico. Immigrants from North America accounted for 38 percent of 
the total - one-fifth of which came from Mexico. Thirty-three 
percent of the total came from Asia and 14 percent came from 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	California, New York, Florida, Texas, New Jersey and Illinois  
were the top destinations for the new immigrants -- as has been the 
case since 1971, INS said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 18:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Test May Improve Syndrome Detection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Researchers seeking a safer way to detect Down syndrome in a  
fetus say combining blood and ultrasound tests from the first and 
second trimesters would be more accurate than standard screenings 
and reduce the need for riskier testing. 
</P>
<P>
	The method would spare many women the need for a definitive test  
called amniocentesis, in which a needle withdraws fluid from the 
amniotic sac. That triggers miscarriage about 1 percent of the 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Compared with the testing that is standard in the United States,  
the new system would prevent the miscarriages of about 1,400 
healthy fetuses each year and detect about 800 more fetuses with 
the chromosomal abnormality, said Dr. Nicholas Wald, the lead 
researcher. He said the new system would reduce by 80 percent the 
number of women for whom amniocentesis would be recommended. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got an improvement in detection, but the real gain is  
the reduction in the number of women who have to have an amnio,'' 
said Wald, chairman of the Wolfson Institute of Preventive Medicine 
in London. 
</P>
<P>
	The screening also could reassure expectant parents their baby  
doesn't have Down syndrome, a condition in which an extra 
chromosome causes mental retardation and physical abnormalities. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1 in 700 babies has Down syndrome, which is marked by a  
broad, flat face with slanting eyes -- and an early death. Older 
women have a higher risk of delivering a baby with Down syndrome -- 
for example, for a woman who is 40, the rate is 1 in 106. 
</P>
<P>
	Wald's research is reported in Thursday's edition of The New  
England Journal of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	``For women who don't want an invasive procedure, this offers  
them a very viable choice,'' said Dr. Anne Summers, director of the 
Maternal Serum Screening Program at North York General Hospital in 
Toronto, which will begin using the system soon. ``This has great 
potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wald and colleagues developed a complicated computer program  
that integrates results of tests in both trimesters. First, a woman 
is given an ultrasound and a blood test for a protein linked to 
Down syndrome, both done 10 to 14 weeks into the pregnancy. A month 
later, she has blood tests for abnormal levels of four substances 
associated with a high risk of Down syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	American women generally get only second-trimester screenings  
for three of those substances -- two hormones and a protein. 
</P>
<P>
	Wald's computer program can be set to allow only a 1 percent  
chance of a false positive result that would lead a doctor to 
suggest the invasive amniocentesis test. With that setting, the 
program correctly identified 85 percent of Down syndrome cases. 
Standard screening detects 46 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Summers' hospital plans to use Wald's system, she said  
more research is needed to confirm the accuracy of his research. 
That's because his calculations were done by piecing together data 
from three other studies, each involving different women receiving 
only some of the tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Another expert who agreed, Dr. Fergal Malone, director of  
perinatal research at New York Presbyterian Hospital, said Wald's 
system probably is accurate, ``but it should not lead to a change 
in clinical practice'' until another, larger trial is performed 
using all of the tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone and Wald are now running studies of the tests on tens of  
thousands of expectant mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	In an editorial in the journal, Dr. Joshua Copel and Dr. Ray  
Bahado-Singh of Yale University argue that Wald's method won't gain 
wide acceptance because it requires withholding results of 
first-trimester tests until they are combined with the later data. 
Women might prefer an earlier warning so they could terminate the 
pregnancy safely, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 20:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore To Outline Ag Advances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA FALLS, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore on Thursday will  
outline how new biotechnology targets by the Clinton administration 
that Gore claims could eventually boost farm income in Iowa by up 
to $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was scheduled to sign an executive order Thursday,  
according to aides speaking on the condition of anonymity, to 
establish as a national goal a tripling in the use of biomass 
products and technologies by the year 2010. 
</P>
<P>
	Details on how the government would encourage that growth were  
unavailable. But Gore will argue that achieving the goal will cut 
sharply into greenhouse gas emissions in addition to bolstering 
farmers' income, according to aides. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is set to announce the goals at an Iowa campaign stop and  
tout the impact of them to farmers suffering from sagging commodity 
prices that threaten to drive thousands from the land. 
</P>
<P>
	The goals, aides said, recognize recent advances in farming and  
biological technologies allowing for a far more diverse use of 
trees and other crops for a variety of purposes. Those range from 
distilling of ethanol to blend with gasoline to make it burn 
cleaner to bio-based textiles and furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	While backers of biomass technology say it's environmentally  
friendly and can cut greenhouse gases blamed for global warming, a 
study in May by the National Academy of Sciences on corn-based 
ethanol found ``little air-quality impact in terms of ozone 
reduction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plants used in biomass technology -- such as trees -- absorb  
carbons during their growth, and Gore contends that their use in 
energy and other applications can also cut into ozone-producing 
carbon emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the plants are largely deep-rooted varieties which  
are helpful in controlling erosion and filtering chemicals from 
groundwater. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Gore and his rival for the Democratic presidential  
nomination next year, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, are both 
campaigning in Iowa this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening the gate for the production of new and nontraditional  
commodities could hold out hope for farmers, and could provide the 
fodder for new research at places like Iowa State University on 
seeking even more new uses for biomass technology. 
</P>
<P>
	While not well known in many parts of the country, ethanol and  
biomass have been hot topics for years in Iowa, with nearly $600 
million in annual tax subsidies for ethanol helping prop up prices 
for corn in a state that is the largest grower of it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sanders' Dad Hopes He Will Come Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- Barry Sanders' father played down  
speculation that his son might return to the NFL but vowed to try 
to persuade him to come back. 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said Wednesday that the running back didn't even  
ask his advice when he retired from the Detroit Lions at age 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, 1,458 yards short of Walter Payton's career rushing  
record, walked away from the game on July 28, the day before the 
Lions began training camp at Saginaw Valley State University. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Sanders said his desire to quit football outweighed  
his desire to play. 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said he told his son not to retire three years  
ago when he was considering it. ``This time he didn't ask me, he 
just quit,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Hughes, director of security for the Lions, has been  
staying at the elder Sanders' home in Wichita since Monday, 
generating speculation that the running back might be rethinking 
his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, a family friend, said Wednesday he came in response to a  
long-standing invitation -- and not at the urging of the Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not down here to try to convince anyone,'' he told The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes said he told only one coach that he was coming so he  
wouldn't be considered absent without leave. He said he decided to 
take a few days off during training camp and planned to stay in 
Wichita another day or more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came here to relax and have a good time,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Lions spokesman Bill Keenist said Hughes was visiting Sanders as  
a Lions official, but would not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Conspicuously absent was Barry Sanders, who was traveling in  
Europe. His father said he hasn't heard from him recently, and 
didn't even know exactly where he was now. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only time Barry called me often was when he was at  
Oklahoma State and he needed money,'' he said. ``He only calls me 
every once in a while now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said he expected to see his son when he comes  
back from Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said his son called to tell him about his decision to  
retire only so that he heard it from him rather than the news 
media. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was disenchanted with the direction the team was going. He  
was tired of losing,'' Sanders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said he would do everything he could to get his son to  
come back to the team and had promised the Lions before Hughes' 
visit that he would try. 
</P>
<P>
	``It stung me a little bit, but it didn't disappoint me,'' he  
said of the retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lions have not made a significant move to replace Sanders.  
Only one back, Jerris McPhail, was not on the roster at the time 
Sanders announced his retirement. McPhail was with the Lions last 
year but did not carry the ball or catch a pass. He was picked by 
the Browns in the expansion draft, but was cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Rivers, Sanders' backup the last four years, is No. 1 on the  
depth chart. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders has avoided all contact with the Lions' front office and  
coaching staff since the final game of the 1998 season. Coach Bobby 
Ross attempted to contact him through a total of 13 telephone calls 
or handwritten letters, but Sanders did not respond to any of them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
