<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spice Girls Founder Dies in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Bob Herbert, the man who formed the Spice Girls  
and who lately had managed the teen pop group Five, has been killed 
in a car accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert, 57, was killed Monday when he lost control of his car  
in heavy rain and collided with another car in Windsor, west of 
London, according to RCA, Five's record company. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert's management of the Spice Girls capitalized on the trend  
of pop groups manufactured to target teen-aged record buyers. 
Earlier, Herbert created Bros, the brother act of Luke and Matt 
Goss. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert and his son, Chris, sought candidates for the Spice  
Girls through an ad in a trade magazine in 1996, seeking 
``streetwise, ambitious and dedicated'' young women. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 women answered the ad. The Herberts chose five for  
the band, initially called Touch, and then spent a year teaching 
them to sing and dance. 
</P>
<P>
	They later fired him in favor of another manager, and their  
number was reduced to four when Ginger Spice -- Geri Halliwell -- 
quit the group last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were all shocked and saddened to hear the news,'' the Spice  
Girls said in a statement Tuesday. ``Our deepest sympathy goes out 
to his family. We know he will be sadly missed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that without that little advert in 'The Stage' I  
wouldn't be where I am today,'' said Halliwell, who has come out 
with a solo album and is a goodwill ambassador for the U.N. 
Population Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will always remember him for the fact that he never gave up  
his dream of managing a great band, which he found in Five,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Five was on a promotional trip in South America and was  
unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the Spice Girls, we thought we could teach them enough to  
get by because we didn't consider talent to be the most important 
thing,'' Herbert was quoted as saying in a 1997 story in The 
Independent newspaper. ``This time we've got a band that's 
talented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert, who lived in Camberley, south of London, is survived by  
his wife, Ann, daughter Nicky, and son Chris, who is co-manager of 
Five. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral arrangements were not announced.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
