<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sears Drops `Orchard' Name Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Sears Roebuck &AMP; Co. has decided against  
converting its 250 hardware stores nationwide to Orchard Hardware &AMP; 
Garden outlets after a test run in Ohio flopped. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers of Sears' 10 Columbus-area hardware stores preferred  
the Sears name and product line, company spokesman Chuck Merydith 
said Tuesday. The name was changed two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbus was Sears' only test market for the concept, which  
downplayed Sears' trademark tools and appliances in favor of 
Orchard's broader line of home-and-garden products. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives hoped the Orchard format would bring more female  
shoppers through the doors. 
</P>
<P>
	But Merydith said that didn't happen.  
</P>
<P>
	``In our research, we asked customers where they liked to shop  
and they said Sears Hardware, and they preferred it not only to 
Orchard but also to the competition,'' he said. ``They told us that 
they wanted Sears Hardware back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sears replaced the Orchard signs last weekend and plans to hold  
a grand reopening for its stores Sept. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears bought Orchard in 1996, attracted by the California  
chain's broad selection of housewares, nursery supplies and 
hardware. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears renamed its Columbus stores after Orchard and changed the  
stores' merchandise mix a year later, spending an estimated $10 
million on the overhaul. 
</P>
<P>
	To accommodate the added merchandise in the same  
20,000-square-foot stores, the company eliminated its line of large 
stationary power tools, most of them bearing Sears' Craftsman 
trademark. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
