<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	1 Dead, 100 Injured in Utah Tornado  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The tornado that ripped through downtown  
Salt Lake City this afternoon killed an exhibitor at an outdoor 
retailers convention that was being set up at the Salt Palace 
Convention Center. Allen Crandy, 38, of Las Vegas, was killed when 
he was struck in the head with flying debris, authorities said. 
Crandy worked for Renaissance Management. A spokeswoman for the 
Utah Comprehensive Emergency Management, said 50 people were 
hospitalized, 12 with moderate injuries and two in critical 
condition. Between 100 and 150 more treated for minor injuries at 
the scene. 

</P>
<P>
	L.A. Shooting Suspect Charged  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Buford O'Neal Furrow, who allegedly confessed  
to the shooting of five people at a Los Angeles Jewish community 
center, was charged by federal prosecutors today with killing a 
postal worker. Furrow was also charged with illegal possession of a 
firearm in the slaying of Joseph Ileto, 39, who was killed when he 
returned to his mail truck about an hour after the center shootings 
yesterday. Furrow turned himself in to the FBI in Las Vegas, saying 
he wanted his attack to be ``a wake-up call to American to kill 
Jews.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Jackson Intervenes in Puerto Rico  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson arrived in  
Puerto Rico today to take the island's side in an escalating feud 
with the U.S. Navy over use of a military training ground. Jackson 
said he wanted to show support for Gov. Pedro Rossello, who is 
urging the Navy to leave the training ground on the outlying island 
of Vieques after recent accidents at a bombing range there. Jackson 
was to meet Rossello tomorrow and then visit the bombing range, 
where protesters have set up camp amid unexploded ordnance to 
thwart further exercises. 

</P>
<P>
	Better Down Syndrome Testing Found  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Researchers seeking a safer way to detect Down  
syndrome in a fetus say combining blood and ultrasound tests from 
the first and second trimesters would be more accurate than 
standard screenings and reduce the need for riskier testing. The 
method would spare many women the need for a definitive test called 
amniocentesis, in which a needle withdraws fluid from the amniotic 
sac. That triggers miscarriage about 1 percent of the time. 
Compared with the testing that is standard in the United States, 
the new system would prevent the miscarriages of about 1,400 
healthy fetuses each year and detect about 800 more fetuses with 
the chromosomal abnormality, said Dr. Nicholas Wald, the lead 
researcher. 

</P>
<P>
	Navajo Nation Sues Tobacco Industry  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Mirroring successful claims made by numerous  
states, the nation's largest Indian tribe sued the tobacco industry 
today to recover the cost of caring for sick smokers. The complaint 
filed in Navajo court alleges tobacco companies deceived Navajo 
Nation consumers, illegally targeted minors and burdened their 
healthcare system. The claim seeks unspecified damages from eight 
tobacco companies, including Phillip Morris and R.J. Reynolds. 
Twice as many American Indians smoke in comparison to other groups, 
according to the surgeon general. The figures are worse for the 
Navajo. 

</P>
<P>
	Fed Says Economy Growing Strongly  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The economy is growing strongly with even the  
beleaguered manufacturing sector showing signs of a rebound, the 
Federal Reserve said today in a new survey of business conditions 
around the nation. While nearly every region of the country faced 
labor shortages, the Fed said wage pressures did not seem to be 
accelerating or causing widespread pressures on inflation. 
Financial markets took heart from the Fed's lack of alarm about 
inflation. But private economists said the Fed report did not 
change their view the central bank is getting ready to raise 
interest rates for a second time this year when policy-makers meet 
Aug. 24. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose moderately Thursday as  
investor sentiment was buoyed by rises in New York and Chicago. The 
Nikkei Stock Average rose 130.27 points to 17,341.43 in early 
trading. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average 
closed up 132.65 points at 10,787.80. 

</P>
<P>
	Orioles Beat Devil Rays 4-2  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Mike Mussina stopped his three-game  
losing streak and B.J. Surhoff and Albert Belle hit back-to-back 
homers as the Baltimore Orioles beat the Tampa Bay Devil Rays 4-2 
tonight. Mussina (14-7) rebounded from losing three consecutive 
starts for the first time in his career. Mussina gave up two runs 
and nine hits in 7 2-3 innings, striking out seven and walking one. 
Surhoff and Belle hit solo homers in the fifth inning. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
