<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jamal Anderson To Meet With Falcons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Jamal Anderson could return to the  
practice field today for the Atlanta Falcons. Then again, he might 
be requesting a trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and his agent, Jim Sims, were planning to hold their  
first face-to-face meeting with coach Dan Reeves and general 
manager Harold Richardson since training camp began July 29 at 
Furman University. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims portrayed the gathering as a chance to break the impasse  
that has kept the All-Pro running back out of camp -- or cause 
irreparable damage to the negotiating process. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said today he was confident a deal could be worked out.  
``I think a deal could be done today,'' he said in an interview 
with WHTA-FM in Atlanta. ``I'm trying to remain here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By this afternoon, he said, ``me and Dan will be dancing and  
smiling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If a deal can't be reached today, Sims said he would ask the  
Falcons to trade Anderson, who set a franchise rushing record with 
1,846 yards and an NFL mark with 410 carries. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims first raised the trade possibility a couple of weeks ago  
when his client refused to report to training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I we don't get it done, I think from that point on we'll  
really have to push the trade option,'' the agent said. ``He's not 
retiring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As he did several weeks ago, Reeves flatly rejected the idea of  
dealing Anderson to another team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll meet with them and he won't get traded,'' the coach  
vowed. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, dozens of reporters converged on the sleepy campus  
at the edge of the Appalachians, expecting a meeting between 
Anderson and the Falcons. The running back arrived in Atlanta on 
Monday morning, putting him within a 2 1/2-hour drive of Greenville. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sims, based in Oakland, Calif., said he had trouble getting  
a flight out of the Bay Area, so the meeting was pushed back 24 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves seemed perturbed by all the attention devoted to the star  
running back, who is refusing to play out the final year of his 
current contract for $2.6 million. Anderson wants a long-term deal 
that's in line with the NFL's other top runners. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just want more publicity and y'all are doing a great job  
of giving it to them,'' Reeves groused to reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The coach, who has final say on contract matters, continued to  
draw a line in the sand at Anderson's demands. He said the running 
back should accept the Falcons' offer or live up to his contract 
and become a free agent at the end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see anything being different just because we're  
meeting face to face ... instead of talking on the phone,'' Reeves 
said. ``We've stated our stance and that's not going to change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did concede a willingness to shift some money to earlier  
years in the contract. While the two sides have basically agreed on 
a new five-year deal worth $28 million to $30 million, Anderson is 
seeking around $13 million in the first three years and the Falcons 
have offered $11 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the Falcons have offered a $7 million signing bonus, while  
Anderson is seeking at least $7.5 million after initially asking 
for $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	If a deal is reached today, Sims said his client could take part  
in practice this afternoon or Thursday morning. The Falcons play 
their first exhibition game Friday night against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves seemed somewhat heartened that Anderson was at least  
making the effort to be at training camp, even if didn't plan on 
being in uniform right away. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's better than nothing,'' Reeves said. ``We'll sit down  
and talk and see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sims sparked the first face-to-face talks by cutting short a  
European vacation and sending a new proposal to Richardson on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There can't be a bigger commitment than going to training camp  
ready to go to work,'' Sims said. ``Hopefully, we'll get it done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, facing fines of $65,000 for skipping 13 workouts as of  
Tuesday, has been unwilling to take the field without a new 
contract since the Falcons can still retain his rights next season 
by designating him a franchise player. 
</P>
<P>
	Even in that situation, he would be assured of making at least  
the average salary of the top five players at his position. 
</P>
<P>
	While Anderson can't force the Falcons to trade him, Sims said  
it would be foolish to keep the player if negotiations reach a 
point where he no longer wants to play for the NFC champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's only vindictive for a team not to go forward and try to  
entertain the trade option,'' Sims said, pointing out that the 
Falcons would be stuck with a $3.6 million salary cap cost whether 
Anderson plays or not. ``Then where we are going to be next year? 
Starting off at square one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Falcons went through another day of practice on a  
scorching 95-degree day, their thoughts far away from Anderson's 
contract impasse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think about Jamal until you asked me,'' linebacker  
Jessie Tuggle told a reporter. ``That's the truth. I want him out 
here as quick as possible, but I'll promise you I'm not losing any 
sleep over him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
                             *Broncos    	
</P>
<P>
	Denver coach Mike Shanahan dispelled rumors of a developing  
quarterback controversy with one word: ridiculous. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though Bubby Brister's first pass was intercepted and he  
went 2-for-7 for 13 yards in the exhibition opener, Shanahan said 
Brister is the Broncos' first-string quarterback. Period. 
</P>
<P>
	While Brister's performance in Saturday's 20-17 victory over San  
Diego was disappointing, third-string quarterback Chris Miller 
played brilliantly. In his first game since concussions forced him 
out of the NFL in December 1995, the 10-year veteran was 11-of-13 
for 137 yards. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Chargers    	
</P>
<P>
	Although the medical prognosis suggests otherwise, injured  
quarterback Ryan Leaf said he hopes to return to play by midseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaf, the second overall pick in the 1998 draft, was back at the  
Chargers' UC San Diego training camp for a second day as he 
recovers from the shoulder injury that was expected to sideline him 
for the entire season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope because I'm younger and maybe will heal a little  
faster, maybe by Week 8 or Week 9,'' the 23-year-old Leaf said. 
``There's a possibility that I can be back out there and play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leaf, who lost his starting job last season because of  
disappointing play, rejoined the Chargers on Monday without wearing 
the sling that he had worn since he underwent surgery two weeks 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Colts    	
</P>
<P>
	Indianapolis practiced again without their top draft pick.  
</P>
<P>
	Running back Edgerrin James has already missed more than two  
weeks of camp and Saturday's exhibition game at Chicago, and there 
was no word of progress in his stalled contract talks with the 
Colts. 
</P>
<P>
	Agent Leigh Steinberg checked out of his hotel and did not  
immediately respond to a telephone message left at his California 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Club president Bill Polian said Monday he had no intention of  
calling Steinberg and did not respond Tuesday to phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	Running back LeShon Johnson's comeback from cancer was put on  
hold when he had surgery to reattach a torn ligament in his right 
thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	During a procedure at the Hospital for Special Surgery-Cornell  
Medical Center in New York City, the ligament and a piece of bone 
still attached to it were anchored back in place by Dr. Andrew 
Weiland, a hand specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, sidelined last season after a tumor was found in his  
chest, was expected back at training camp at the University at 
Albany by Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Giants coach Jim Fassel said Johnson might return to practice  
next week. He will miss the team's exhibition opener at Minnesota 
on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
                            *Cardinals    	
</P>
<P>
	Chris Dishman's injured right elbow and neck injuries to Aeneas  
Williams and Zack Walz were the biggest concerns among a long list 
of players who were hurting at training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Dishman, the starting left guard, might undergo arthroscopic  
surgery to remove bone fragments from the elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, a Pro Bowl starter at cornerback the last four  
seasons, has soreness in his neck, a condition that also bothered 
him last year. 
  	   	
</P>
