<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Wages Frugal Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- George W. Bush is sitting on a massive  
war chest but his campaign is still pinching pennies, directing 
employees nationwide to lay off the 411 calls and use free 
directory-assistance Internet sites instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential front-runner's campaign sent an  
e-mail memo on the matter to staffers across the country Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been informed that there are Internet sites that allow  
you to look up a person's phone number or address FOR FREE,'' 
stated the memo, written by campaign office manager Julie Thomas. 
``Please try to use them rather than spending money on directory 
assistance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush's fund raising dwarfs that of all other presidential  
candidates, the Texas governor has earned a reputation for thrift. 
Many presidential candidates serve lavish meals at donor 
gatherings, but Bush, who raised $37 million in the first half of 
the year, often hands out peanuts and pretzels. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas, who sent the memo from the campaign's Austin, Texas  
headquarters, declined to comment on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a suggestion to save the campaign money,''  
campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said. ``We try to run an 
efficient operation here at the campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's campaign collected $31 for every $1 it spent on fund  
raising in the first half of the year. The Gore campaign took in $6 
for every $1 it spent to raise money. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Former Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole  
said she's not distracted by Texas Gov. George W. Bush's huge 
financial edge as she seeks to counter his financial muscle with 
brand-new voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at history,'' Mrs. Dole said Tuesday, while arguing that  
money can't be the sole basis for a bid for the nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The former head of the American Red Cross slogged through four  
Des Moines campaign stops seeking to lure new voters to the polls, 
and to a big straw poll on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are coming to the events, it's not a matter of having to  
pull them in. They are there,'' Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	At campaign stops, Mrs. Dole carefully positions herself at the  
door after speaking, shaking hands and speaking with all who 
attend. At the same time, aides are busily scurrying around with 
pledge cards, seeking to sign up backers for the Saturday straw 
poll. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowds are heavily female and young, and Mrs. Dole said  
that's who she is targeting as she seeks to broaden the Republican 
base. While she claimed progress, the success rate of aides was 
well under 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a tough task, because straw polls and precinct caucuses are  
new to many who attend her events. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. Dole doesn't focus her campaign strictly on her  
gender, she points to a series of firsts she's had that appeal to 
women voters. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	GRUNDY CENTER, Iowa (AP) -- Steve Forbes says the tax-cut plan  
approved by the GOP-controlled Congress last week was better than 
nothing but would not significantly help Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes to a little more than 3 cents on the dollar over 10  
years,'' the GOP presidential hopeful told people Tuesday who 
turned out to greet him during campaign stops across north-central 
Iowa. ``And yet to hear all the hoopla in Washington, you would 
think it was the most radical and revolutionary thing since 1776. 
It's pennies to the people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New Jersey publisher has campaigned as a political outsider.  
</P>
<P>
	In Iowa for Saturday's straw poll, he repeatedly poked fun at  
Washington politics, calling the 10-year, $792 billion package 
approved by Congress a ``supposed, great-big tax cut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, who advocates a flat-tax plan, said the tax-cut proposal  
would do nothing to alleviate people's concerns over the 
complicated U.S. tax system. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Forbes' campaign, which asked audience members at  
each stop to turn out and support him Saturday at the GOP straw 
poll in Ames, announced new help from another Republican campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Kasich of Ohio dropped out of the Republican  
presidential race in July and threw his support behind Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush. But three of Kasich's top Iowa campaign staffers, 
including former state director Karen Slifka, said Tuesday they had 
joined the Forbes campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
