<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Partnerships Plan Uncertain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The American Bar Association is putting on hold a  
proposal to let lawyers join with accountants and other 
professionals to offer clients one-stop shopping for legal, 
financial and other services. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest lawyers' group decided Tuesday to delay the  
issue for more study after many members raised objections. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is the longstanding ban on lawyers forming partnerships  
with other professionals such as accountants, psychologists and 
social workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers face increasing competition from huge, multi-service  
international firms. Outgoing ABA President Philip Anderson said 
lawyers cannot ignore the fact that the practice of law is 
changing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The response of `I don't like it' is not going to make it go  
away,'' Anderson said. ``I don't like it either but it's here and 
it's going to stay here, and the question is what are we going to 
do about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone will write the rules,'' Anderson said. ``The lawyers  
should write the rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some ABA members said forming partnerships with non-lawyers  
would harm lawyers' professional standards and their ability to 
promise confidentiality and undivided loyalty to their clients. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a nightmare,'' said Philadelphia lawyer Lawrence J. Fox.  
He said he dreamed he was attending a conference of 
multi-profession partnerships and an award was being given to Rep. 
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, for his ``bringing together of extermination 
and legal services.'' DeLay formerly ran a Houston pest 
extermination company. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABA's policy-making House of Delegates decided on a majority  
vote to delay the issue. Even if the proposal had passed, the 
ethics rule changes would have taken effect only after an 
additional ABA vote at a future meeting and then by authorities who 
regulate lawyers' ethics in each state. 
</P>
<P>
	Sherwin P. Simmons of Miami, who chaired the ABA panel that made  
the proposal, said he hopes the issue will be raised again when the 
lawyers' group meets in New York next July. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed ethics changes would allow people to get legal help  
and accounting or financial planning advice all in one place. Or 
lawyers who practice family law could form partnerships with 
psychologists or social workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban on lawyers' partnerships with non-lawyers is intended to  
protect attorneys' independent judgment, protect confidential 
client information and ensure awyers' loyalty to their clients by 
avoiding conflicts of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would specify that legal ethics rules apply to all  
lawyers no matter where they work. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox said about 5,000 lawyers already work for other companies on  
such matters as taxes or mergers and acquisitions. He said they are 
making the ``disingenuous argument that they are not practicing 
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox said another lawyer accused him of ``defending the buggy  
whip in the age of the automobile.'' But he said he wanted to 
``circle the wagons around loyalty to clients, confidentiality, 
client accountability and legal independence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons said consumer groups' members want to get legal help  
through non-traditional means, such as at accounting firms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can we do this in a way which will protect the public? So  
they'll know who's giving them advice and what to expect?'' Simmons 
said. ``We want to have another shot at this. We want to have more 
input from you,'' he told the delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on Tuesday, ABA delegates passed a resolution calling on  
federal, state and local legislators to require police to keep 
statistics to help determine whether traffic stops and searches are 
being conducted for racially discriminatory reasons. A number of 
motorists say they have been stopped for no apparent reason other 
than ``driving while black.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, the delegates defeated a proposed ethics rule that would  
restrict lawyers from making political contributions aimed at 
getting government work, a practice known as ``pay to play.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 14:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
