<DOCNO> APW19990811.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 18:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schilling Suffers Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Phillies ace Curt Schilling suffered another  
setback Wednesday when he was unable to throw off the mound as 
scheduled due to muscle spasms. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, who had a cortisone shot this week to ease the  
effects of tendinitis and mild rotator cuff swelling, will try to 
throw again Thursday. If he experiences pain again, team doctor 
Michael Ciccotti said he will consider shutting him down 
indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's not able to throw the way he normally would two days  
before a start, then that's enough,'' Ciccotti said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, whose string of 117 consecutive starts ended July 28  
due to biceps tendinitis, was supposed to pitch off the mound 
Wednesday. But he experienced spasms in his neck and behind his 
shoulder blades while playing catch and cut the session short. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciccotti said if he has similar discomfort Thursday, an MRI  
might be prescribed -- although the doctor believes Schilling's 
shoulder is structurally sound. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the results of his throwing session Thursday might go a  
long way toward deciding if Schilling is sidelined indefinitely, 
Ciccotti said, ``Yes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Schilling might not make the team's trip to Cincinnati  
this weekend if things don't go well Thursday, Ciccotti said, 
``That's a consideration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was another dose of bad news for Schilling, who had been on  
schedule to start Friday against the Reds. But even before 
Wednesday's setback, the Phillies had already pushed him back to 
Saturday -- a nationally televised matchup against Pete Harnisch, 
another pitcher who has battled tobacco addiction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Schill doesn't especially like to pitch in the day  
sometimes, but I think it's better if we give him the extra day,'' 
Francona said before Schilling's bullpen session. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling will come to Veterans Stadium to test his shoulder on  
Thursday, an off-day for the Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, who started for the National League in the All-Star  
game, led the league with 300 strikeouts, 268 2-3 innings and 15 
complete games last season. He's dropped to fifth in the NL in 
strikeouts this season, fading in his bid to join Nolan Ryan as the 
only pitchers to strike out 300 batters in three consecutive 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old right-hander is second in the majors to Randy  
Johnson with eight complete games, throwing five straight early in 
the season. But the Phillies have stopped short of saying 
Schilling's shoulder problem is due to overwork. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling had major shoulder surgery to repair a torn labrum and  
remove a bone spur in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I'd call it overwork,'' Ciccotti said. ``Yes,  
he throws a lot and he throws very hard. ... The style of pitcher 
he is and his competitiveness unquestionably puts tremendous stress 
on the whole shoulder girdle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling said through a Phillies spokesman that he was  
unavailable to comment before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's appropriately distressed,'' Ciccotti said. ``But he's  
very willing to do the things we're suggesting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want him to pitch, and we want him to pitch pain-free. We  
don't want him to put himself at risk, not only for the rest of the 
season, but for the rest of what will be a very long career.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
