<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians 4, Angels 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Manny Ramirez hit his 30th homer and  
Roberto Alomar hit his 20th as the Cleveland Indians beat Anaheim 
4-3 Wednesday night to complete a three-game sweep and send the 
Angels to their sixth straight loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, who hit 45 homers last year, connected off Lou Pote in  
the eighth for his second homer in two nights and raised his major 
league-leading RBIs total to 116. 
</P>
<P>
	Dave Burba (9-7) allowed one run and seven hits in six innings  
to win for the first time in four road starts since June 13. He 
escaped a bases-loaded jam in the first inning by retiring Garret 
Anderson on a weak tapper back to the mound and stranded eight 
runners in the first five innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Jackson got three outs for his 26th save in 29 chances,  
allowing a two-out, two-run homer to Todd Greene, the first home 
run by an Angels' pinch hitter in 51 at-bats this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Mo Vaughn then singled, but Jackson struck out Tim Salmon to end  
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Sparks (5-9), who retired 13 of his first 14 batters, lost  
for the fifth time in his last six decisions, giving up three runs 
and seven hits in five-plus innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Last-place Anaheim has lost 22 of 26 to fall to 46-67, dropping  
22 games back in the AL West. 
</P>
<P>
	Indians designated hitter Jim Thome sat out after complaining of  
flu-like symptoms. Alex Ramirez was inserted as the DH and broke a 
scoreless tie with an RBI double in the fifth following a double by 
Richie Sexson. 
</P>
<P>
	Omar Vizquel opened the sixth with a single and Alomar followed  
with a two-run homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Huson's opposite-field RBI single in sixth was the only run  
allowed by Burba. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Sparks' wild pitch in the fourth was his first in 64 1-3  
innings and only his second in 103 2-3 innings. He threw five wild 
pitches in his first 18 innings this season. ... Tim Salmon's 
first-inning double was his 969th career hit, moving him past Rod 
Carew for fifth place on the Angels' career list. Carew had 
additional 2,085 hits for the Minnesota Twins. ... Darin Erstad sat 
out after sprained right knee Tuesday night. ... Angels two-time 
Gold Glove center fielder Jim Edmonds played first base for the 
first time since June 26, 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
