<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Geneva Conventions Turn 50 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Olga Villarrubia smiles at the memory.  
</P>
<P>
	The Red Cross delegate was visiting Croatians captured by Serbs  
in their 1991 war when one man, overjoyed at the friendly face, 
gave her one of his most precious possessions: dice made from his 
bread ration. 
</P>
<P>
	Months later, the released prisoner found his way to her office  
in Zagreb, the Croatian capital, just to thank her. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Villarrubia's smile fades. She's recalling the despair of a  
detainee in Sierra Leone who wept at news Villarrubia was leaving. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you spend hours with a person. You say you will come  
back, but the person looks at you and they don't believe it,'' she 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Villarrubia's stories show the Geneva Conventions at work.  
</P>
<P>
	Fifty years old Thursday, the conventions lay out humane and  
dignified treatment of prisoners and civilians in wartime. 
Compliance visits by the International Committee of the Red Cross 
have given hope to decades of detainees struggling against 
isolation and, frequently, abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	But with a ceremony planned at Geneva's town hall and special  
events around the world, the conventions today are perhaps better 
known for the violations against them than the respect for them. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, the conventions ban torture, hostage-taking, mass  
extermination, summary executions, deportations and the wanton 
destruction of civilian property, all of which were commonplace in 
the recent wars in Sierra Leone and Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The conventions boast the signatures of 188 nations, more than  
the U.N. membership of 185. A big problem, however, as some see it, 
is that individual signatory states are left to police themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the problem is in the texts,'' says Isabelle  
Scherer, a local representative for Amnesty International, the 
human rights organization. ``The texts are excellent, but there is 
no mechanism to measure their respect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Claudio Cordone, director of Amnesty's main policy unit in  
London, says many states don't realize that signing the conventions 
gave them the responsibility to apprehend and prosecute war 
criminals in their own courts. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a growing recognition that impunity is linked to  
violations of both human rights law and the law of war,'' he says. 
``There are often very good judges that don't actually know that 
they have this authority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The four conventions were drawn up in the aftermath of World War  
II's horrors to establish minimum conditions for prisoners of war, 
civilians and the sick and wounded during international armed 
conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	They replaced several earlier, more limited agreements, also  
known as Geneva conventions, that covered battlefield wounded, 
signed in 1864; sailors wounded or captured at sea, 1906; and 
prisoners of war, 1929. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1949 conventions designated the International Red Cross as  
observers. Last year, the ICRC visited 212,000 detainees in 59 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The conventions stipulate that a nation treat captured or  
injured ``enemy'' troops and civilians the same way as its own 
soldiers and release them when war ends. They make special 
provision for medics, clergy and journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	The modern treaties were updated with two additional protocols  
in 1977 that strengthened protection for civilians in civil wars as 
well as international conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	George Moose, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations in Geneva,  
says the conventions ``will rank high among the list of noble 
accomplishments this century bequeaths to the next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``To assess their importance we need only contemplate the  
suffering that has occurred where they haven't been respected,'' 
Moose says. 
</P>
<P>
	But the changing nature of warfare has limited the good the  
conventions -- and the Red Cross -- can do. 
</P>
<P>
	As written, the conventions envisage a traditional war between  
law-abiding armies -- where troops from one nation attack troops 
from the other until one is victorious. 
</P>
<P>
	But most modern conflicts involve internal strife or armed  
rebellions, neither addressed in detail by the conventions. 
Although the 1977 protocols strengthened the rights of civilians 
caught up in civil war, state sovereignty is still held paramount. 
</P>
<P>
	In internal conflicts, the Red Cross has to seek a government's  
permission to send in a delegate. China still forbids access, for 
instance, and visits to Myanmar and Algeria are beginning only now, 
after years of negotiation. 
</P>
<P>
	Even in an ``international'' war such as the bombing of  
Yugoslavia by NATO, the Red Cross had to wait weeks before it was 
allowed to visit three U.S. soldiers captured by Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	The ICRC is the first to concede the conventions are far from  
perfect. But it isn't urging reform. 
</P>
<P>
	Villarrubia, who coordinates ICRC visits from the Geneva  
headquarters, says enforcement should be the priority of the 
international community, rather than rewriting the conventions. 
``If we had to renegotiate the Geneva Conventions, we would never 
reach what we reached in 1949,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't stop the war. We can't go into a country and say this  
is right and this is wrong,'' she says. ``But we are convinced we 
have a role in calming down, even if only by checking the 
conditions of detention, by assisting the population, by being 
present.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
