S&AMP;P 500:         1299.96 + 18.53
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          777.37  + 6.60
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2,564.98  + 74.87
Gold(final) -    $260.20    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Fed Finds Strong U.S. Economy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy is still growing strongly  
with labor shortages reported nationwide, the Federal Reserve said 
today. The Fed's ``beige book'' survey of economic conditions, 
compiled from reports from its 12 regional banks, found only 
scattered signs of mounting wage pressures and little evidence of 
rising inflation in general. But the Fed survey did note 
developments that could lead to increased inflationary pressures, 
including scattered higher prices. 

</P>
<P>
	Alcoa Offers To Buy Rival Reynolds  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa Inc., the world's largest aluminum  
company, went public with an offer to buy No. 3 Reynolds Metals Co. 
for $5.6 billion in cash and stock just hours after three foreign 
aluminum rivals announced a deal that would catapult them to the 
No. 1 ranking. Alcoa and Reynolds would have a combined revenue of 
about $21 billion, rivaling the new marriage of Alusuisse-Lonza 
(Algroup) of Switzerland, Pechiney of France and Alcan Aluminium of 
Canada, which have combined revenue of $21.6 billion. Alcoa shares 
closed up 2 15/16 at 69 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Hat Shares Soar in IPO  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Red Hat Inc. shares nearly quadrupled in their  
first day of trading today, underscoring investor confidence in the 
upstart Linux operating software and shunning rampant market 
pessimism toward initial public offerings. The warm investor 
reception toward Durham, N.C.-based Red Hat, the first Linux-only 
company to go public, is expected to trigger more IPOs by companies 
promoting the operating system as an alternative to Unix and 
Windows NT for running business computers. Red Hat closed at 
$52.06 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market after being initially priced at 
$14 and opening at $46. 

</P>
<P>
	Cisco Systems' Revenues Soar  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Internet gold rush is alive and well at  
Cisco Systems where the online communications company posted a 
strong fourth-quarter and capped a stunning fiscal year. The San 
Jose, Calif.-based company saw its revenues grow 43 percent and 
operating profits improve 35 percent for the fiscal year. Cisco's 
fourth-quarter revenues totaled $3.55 billion, a 48 percent 
increase from last year. Cisco earned $727 million or 21 cents per 
share, in the quarter, excluding one-time charges totaling $97 
million for acquisition-related expenses. Cisco shares closed up 4 
3/16 at 62 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	UPS Ordered To Pay Back Taxes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service won a rare  
victory in its campaign to curb offshore corporate tax shelters 
when a federal judge ruled that the United Parcel Service set up a 
Bermuda company to avoid paying income taxes. UPS officials said 
today they disagree and are likely to appeal this week's ruling by 
a U.S. Tax Court judge, which could cost the Atlanta-based package 
carrier hundreds of millions of dollars in back taxes, penalties 
and interest. 

</P>
<P>
	Cos. To Bankroll Family-Friendly TV  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Disgusted by sex-soaked and violent television  
programs, 11 major advertisers said today they will pay to have 
writers develop family-friendly shows for consideration by the WB 
network. The advertisers, including Procter &AMP; Gamble, General 
Motors, IBM and Sears, say they are taking the steps after finding 
fewer prime-time programs during which they feel comfortable 
selling their products. The advertisers agreed to bankroll at least 
eight scripts that can cost as much as $90,000 each. WB will 
supervise the development and decide which scripts, if any, will go 
into production. 

</P>
<P>
	Procter &AMP; Gamble Buying Pet Food Co.  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. is jumping into the  
lucrative pet nutrition business by buying pet food maker Iams Co. 
for $2.05 billion in cash, P&AMP;G's biggest purchase ever. P&AMP;G 
officials said today they intend to expand Iams' pet food sales in 
foreign markets. Iams' international sales now represent about 30 
percent of the company's total revenues, even though two-thirds of 
the global pet nutrition market exists outside of North America. 
The global pet food market is estimated at $25 billion. P&AMP;G stock 
fell 1/2 at 93 1/4. 

