</P>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Struggling manufactured-home builder  
Oakwood Homes Corp. said today its longtime chief executive, 
Nicholas St. George, will retire and that the company is no longer 
looking for a suitor. President and chief operating officer William 
G. Edwards will be his successor. The company, which is the 
nation's largest retailer of manufactured homes, also said it had 
halted efforts to look for a buyer after a succession of poor 
earnings reports. Oakwood also said that recent layoffs, attrition 
and three plant closings have eliminated about 1,000 jobs since 
April. Oakwood stock fell 1 9/16 at 7 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Helps Airlines With E-Tickets  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A collaboration between IBM and the airline  
industry could make ticketless air travel much more convenient for 
passengers and air carriers. At some domestic airlines, up to half 
of all passengers now use electronic tickets. But unlike paper 
tickets, airlines cannot honor each other's electronic tickets 
unless they establish costly links between their e-ticket systems. 
IBM and the International Air Transport Association announced today 
that they are developing a computer system that would link all 
airlines that offer ticketless travel beginning next year. IBM 
shares closed up 3 15/16 at 123 1/4. 

