<DOCNO> APW19990811.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 10:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Warns Deutsche Telekom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration raised the  
potential of another bruising trade fight with Europe on Wednesday 
when it warned that it was prepared to file a complaint if German 
telephone giant Deutsche Telekom imposes unfair connection charges 
to limit foreign competition. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said she was  
taking action after U.S. telecommunications companies complained 
that the former German monopoly telephone service was trying to 
impose high interconnection fees and other roadblocks in their 
efforts to offer services in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``German regulatory authorities must take concrete steps to  
ensure that Deutsche Telekom provides timely interconnection at 
fair rates, terms and conditions for prospective entrants,'' 
Barshefsky said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the U.S. trade office would be closely monitoring  
upcoming decisions by German regulators and would not hesitate to 
bring a case before the World Trade Organization if those decisions 
are not consistent with a global agreement opening up 
telecommunications services to greater competition. 
</P>
<P>
	In issuing the warning, Barshefsky said U.S. officials welcomed  
recent rulings in which German regulators decided to ``reject most 
of the unreasonable rates, terms and conditions that Deutsche 
Telekom has sought to impose immediately on new entrants to the 
telecommunications market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But she said the concern now was upcoming rules to be issued in  
the fall that will set the conditions for foreign competition 
beginning in the year 2000 and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	``Further action by the regulator is essential to secure market  
access for U.S. industry in the newly liberalized German 
telecommunications services market,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, the United States is involved in two high-profile  
trade fights with the 15-nation European Union in which it has 
imposed punitive tariffs on more than $300 million of European 
products in retaliation for the EU's refusal to abide by WTO 
decisions involving American beef and bananas. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
