<HEADLINE> Red Hat Shares Soar in IPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Red Hat Inc. shares nearly quadrupled in their  
first day of trading Wednesday, underscoring investor confidence in 
the upstart Linux operating software and shunning rampant market 
pessimism toward initial public offerings. 
</P>
<P>
	The warm investor reception toward Durham, N.C.-based Red Hat,  
the first Linux-only company to go public, is expected to trigger 
more IPOs by companies promoting the operating system as an 
alternative to Unix and Windows NT for running business computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Hat closed at $52.06 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market after being  
initially priced at $14 and opening at $46. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the biggest price leap in at least two weeks among IPOs,  
which recently have hit a wall of investor nervousness about small, 
money-losing companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Its share price Wednesday gives Red Hat a staggering market  
value of $3.8 billion -- even though Red Hat had sales of just $11 
million and lost money last year -- a seeming return to the gigantic 
valuations investors showered on Internet stocks before the recent 
slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Hat sold 6 million shares to raise $84 million for spending  
on its Web site, software development and other expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a phenomenal opening, just given the current market  
conditions,'' said Paul Bard, an analyst with Renaissance Capital 
Corp., a Greenwich, Conn., IPO research firm that also operates a 
mutual fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Bard said demand appeared to be heightened by scores of  
volunteer Linux programmers who got the word out about the IPO over 
the Internet and who comprised some of the investors as well. In 
addition, investors generally are willing to pay a premium for 
companies that are first to market in their industry sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Linux-only company expected to come to market is VA  
Linux Systems Inc., a maker of business computers that come 
pre-loaded with Linux software. 
</P>
<P>
	More typical of this week's IPO market was Blockbuster Inc., the  
big video-rental chain, whose shares barely budged from their 
offering price Wednesday amid investor concern that new media will 
doom the video-rental business over the next few years. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Blockbuster, which priced at $15, closed at $15 after  
hitting a high of $15.06 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	While many IPOs issued earlier this year enjoyed heady gains in  
their first day of trading, more recent IPOs have risen only 
slightly -- or even dropped in price. The last time an IPO had a 
similar jump to Red Hat was back on July 28, when shares of 
drugstore.com nearly tripled. 
</P>
<P>
	Linux was created in the early 1990s by Linus Torvalds, a  
Finnish student who released his blueprints over the Internet so 
programmers around the world could contribute improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Linux can be downloaded for free off the Web or bought in  
packages with technical support for as little as $30. A growing 
minority of corporate technology workers are embracing Linux as an 
adjunct -- if not an alternative -- to the Unix and Windows NT 
computers at the hub of networks of business machines, and on 
computers that run Web sites. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
