<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: L.A. Tragedy Disturbing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Wednesday it is  
``deeply disturbing'' to think that the shootings at the Los 
Angeles Jewish center were motivated by religious hatred. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton did not offer specifics but alluded to reports linking  
the suspected gunman, Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., and the white 
supremacist group The Order. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have heard about the suspect and his motives is deeply  
disturbing. Nothing could be further from the values we honor here 
today,'' Clinton said during a ceremony to bestow the Presidential 
Medal of Freedom on former President Gerald Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that Furrow had turned himself in, Clinton thanked law  
enforcement officials who ``quickly responded to the crime, 
identified the suspect and kept the pressure on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I can only hope that this latest incident will intensify our  
resolve to make America a safer place, and a place of healing 
across the lines that divide us,'' Clinton said. He also again 
expressed sympathies for the victims and their families. 
</P>
<P>
	First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton said she was concerned about  
the five people wounded in the shooting -- four of whom were 
children ages 5 to 16. 
</P>
<P>
	``When children are the victims of gun violence, it shocks the  
conscience of our nation,'' she said. ``There is no place for 
violence or intolerance in our country and it is urgent we address 
these issues now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton last week reiterated his appeal to Congress to pass a  
hate crimes bill that would make it easier for the Justice 
Department to investigate and prosecute such offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate approved the measure last month and added it to a  
still pending spending bill. The House Judiciary Committee held a 
hearing on the measure last week. Critics say a federal law is 
unnecessary since states prosecute hate crimes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
