<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest Airlines CEO Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Herb Kelleher, the flamboyant chief executive of  
Southwest Airlines, said Wednesday that he has prostate cancer, 
which his doctor said was caught in the early stages. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher, 68, who pioneered no-frills, low-cost air service and  
built Southwest into one of the country's top airlines, began 
radiation treatment Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts were reassured by an upbeat prognosis from doctors,  
though they remain concerned about who will succeed the colorful, 
68-year-old executive. Kelleher relishes his image as a 
heavy-smoking workaholic with a penchant for Wild Turkey bourbon 
and an evangelical zeal for a friendly workplace. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as he can hold a shot glass, I want him running this  
airline, and so does every Southwest shareholder,'' said Glenn 
Engel, an analyst with Goldman Sachs. ``The day when it appears 
Herb is mortal, then Southwest's stock will go down more than it 
did today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas-based Southwest's stock dropped 12 1/2 cents to $16.37 1/2 in  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange after dropping as much as 
$1.06 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher displayed his characteristic humor and loud, cackling  
laugh during a half-hour conference call with reporters in which he 
said his ``mundane, routine'' case of prostate cancer would not 
interfere with his ability to run the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher said cancer was suspected after a routine physical exam  
about a month ago and subsequently confirmed by an antigen test and 
biopsy. 
</P>
<P>
	He will undergo radiation therapy every weekday at M.D. Anderson  
Cancer Center in Houston -- commuting from his office in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Andrew C. von Eschenbach, director of the prostate cancer  
program at the hospital, said the cancer was discovered early and 
is in a mild stage of development. He said Kelleher is expected 
``to lead a fully active and productive life, just as if he had 
never had prostate cancer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prostate cancer is the second most common cancer among American  
men, after skin cancer. The American Cancer Society estimates 
179,300 new cases of prostate cancer will be diagnosed in the 
United States this year, and about 37,000 men will die of this 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher said he received an otherwise clean bill of health from  
doctors and doesn't plan to make any changes in his lifestyle, 
although doctors urged him to quit smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told them, 'Well, that's something I'll consider after these  
treatments are concluded,' '' Kelleher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some stockholders have complained about Kelleher's smoking and  
questioned whether the company has an adequate succession plan for 
the man who helped found the airline in 1971. Kelleher dismissed 
the criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no need to update any succession plan because our  
board discusses that issue on a regular basis,'' said Kelleher, 
whose contract runs through 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	James Higgins, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,  
said Southwestern has ``a deep bench'' of executives capable of 
replacing Kelleher. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether they have his personality and his visceral  
understanding of labor relations is another question,'' Higgins 
added. ``He is an impossible act to follow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Candace Browning of Merrill Lynch praised Kelleher for not  
anointing an heir apparent, saying that other talented executives 
who were not tapped might have left the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelleher, a lawyer from San Antonio who started the airline with  
one of his clients, was named chairman in 1978 and assumed titles 
of president and CEO in 1981. His spirited leadership -- including 
dressing up as Elvis, a leprechaun and a cross-dressing male nurse 
-- are part of the fabric at a company known for high customer 
satisfaction. Fortune magazine named it the country's most admired 
airline, and, this year, the best place to work in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest is the nation's seventh largest airline in terms of  
revenue, though the fourth-largest carrier in terms of number of 
passengers. It operates more than 2,450 flights a day, many of them 
less than 500 miles, and has more than 28,000 employees. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
