<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins: Webb May Miss NFL Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Seven-time Pro Bowl tackle Richmond Webb may  
miss the start of the Miami Dolphins season because of a contract 
stalemate. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson predicted that Webb will wait until  
just before the season to sign, meaning backup Brent Smith would 
start the opener Sept. 13 at Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are totally prepared to go with Brent Smith,'' Johnson said  
Tuesday. ``I would guess Richmond won't come in until the week 
before the start of the season because he doesn't want to miss his 
paychecks. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that happens, he won't be ready. It would take him a few  
weeks at least to get ready to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Veterans such as Webb earn $800 per week during the preseason  
and don't begin collecting their salaries until the first week of 
the season. The Dolphins have offered Webb a one-year, $3.4 million 
deal, meaning each game missed would cost him more than $200,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb has missed 12 days of training camp and two scrimmages. His  
agent, Steve Zucker, declined to comment Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
