<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 10  
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Oklahoman, Oklahoma City, on double standards:  
</P>
<P>
	Ethics and professional standards aren't what they used to be.  
</P>
<P>
	Contrast the American Bar Association's response to cases of  
presidential misconduct involving Richard Nixon and Bill Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1973, a year before Nixon left office under threat of  
impeachment, the bar association adopted a resolution condemning 
him and his colleagues for their role in the Watergate scandal and 
called for swift disciplinary action. 
</P>
<P>
	Fast forward to just a couple weeks ago. U.S. District Judge  
Susan Webber Wright orders Clinton to pay more than $90,000 in 
contempt-of-court sanctions for lying under oath during his 
deposition in the Paula Jones case. The bar's response: Come 
address our annual convention. 
</P>
<P>
	So the question is, have the legal profession's standards  
plummeted that much, or are there two set of standards -- one for 
liberals and one for all the rest? 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 6  
</P>
<P>
	Houston Chronicle, on paying down national debt:  
</P>
<P>
	The hyperbole and gamesmanship in the debate over tax cuts and  
the supposed federal budget surplus have been rampant. 
</P>
<P>
	We have argued, long and repeatedly, that a more productive  
approach would be to apply some of the speculative ``surplus'' to 
saving Medicare and Social Security and using the rest to pay down 
the monstrous $3.6 trillion federal debt, which requires hundreds 
of millions of dollars each year just to service. 
</P>
<P>
	Some prefer spending the excess money. Others are stuck on the  
argument that the tax money should be returned to the taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	The truth is, we all ran up the national debt together. We all  
continue to pay interest on it. And we are in danger of just 
passing it on to our children and grandchildren. Shame on us. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, we should consider it largely the cost of  
waging a war -- the Cold War -- that we fortunately won and now must 
pay for. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 6  
</P>
<P>
	The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer, on KKK rally:  
</P>
<P>
	The Cleveland Police Patrolman's Association has won an  
at-least-temporary legal victory in its effort to keep the Ku Klux 
Klan from using the Justice Center garage as a staging area for its 
Aug. 21 rally. But that victory is not one against racism or 
intolerance. It is merely a tactical political triumph over Mayor 
Michael R. White. And if the court ruling is not reversed, the 
likely result is to heighten the danger of violence during the 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	White has proposed using the garage as a dressing area not  
because he wants to promote the Klan's message, as police 
protesters ridiculously allege, but because it is the best way for 
authorities to keep the hate group under control during its short 
visit to Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	We once again appeal to all parties in this issue to stop  
tossing matches in streets already knee-deep in racial tinder. The 
evidently irresistible urge to play politics with the Klan's visit 
already has put everyone on edge and threatens to turn what ought 
to be a community celebration of the Browns' return into an ugly 
confrontation. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 5.  
</P>
<P>
	The Post and Courier, Charleston, S.C., on Zapruder film:  
</P>
<P>
	The federal arbitration panel's decision on the value of the  
famed Zapruder film showing the assassination of President John F. 
Kennedy is a stunner: $16 million for a 26-second segment of 
celluloid that is too fragile to run through a projector. The panel 
appears to have confused the importance of the event with the 
importance of an artifact that already has been duplicated a 
multitude of times. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, the panel's 2-1 vote can't be appealed since the  
arbitration process was agreed upon as a way to settle its value 
after the film was declared a permanent possession of the 
government by the federal Assassination Records Review Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The Zapruder family had sold the film previously to Life  
Magazine following the assassination in 1963 and then bought it 
back 12 years later for $1, according to the Houston Chronicle. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Auction house experts who testified before the panel estimated  
the value of the film between $1 million and $25 million. The 
Zapruders wanted $30 million; the government offered $1 million. 
The arbitration panel split the difference, more or less. Too bad 
the government couldn't have given it back and kept a copy. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 5  
</P>
<P>
	The Stuart (Fla.) News, on toddlers and television:  
</P>
<P>
	Even if the American Academy of Pediatrics had never uttered a  
syllable on the subject, many parents would have figured out for 
themselves that too much TV is bad for their children. But many 
might not have concluded that children under 2 should be kept from 
the tube entirely. 
</P>
<P>
	The pediatricians say so, however, and while they cannot  
demonstrate definitively that damage is done by such early viewing, 
they do make the interesting case that a blaring, nearby TV could 
keep these infants and toddlers from what counts far more in their 
development -- face-to-face interaction with their parents and other 
caring adults. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Television can affect attitudes and breed habits of passivity.  
It clearly can have psychological, physical and societal 
consequences, as the pediatricians claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Television is a fact of life in our times, and in some families,  
its regulation obviously can be difficult. ... But aiming to 
control the watching of TV by children is a good idea for parents, 
and the American Academy of Pediatrics deserves credit for saying 
so. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 7  
</P>
<P>
	The Intelligencer, Wheeling, W.Va., on playgrounds:  
</P>
<P>
	Playgrounds today feature a lot of really neat structures for  
kids, with all manner of things to climb, slide on and crawl 
through. Some of it is fun enough to make an adult want to elbow a 
6-year-old to one side and get at it. But amid all this updating of 
playgrounds, you may not have noticed that some old childhood 
favorites have disappeared. Teeter-totters, for example, are 
particularly hard to find, the Associated Press reports. ... 
</P>
<P>
	It seems that kids sometimes fall off teeter-totters and get  
hurt, or -- not that we ever did such things -- some dirty rotten 
kids will play tricks like jumping of the teeter-totter when the 
other kid is raised up high. 
</P>
<P>
	Modern every-complaint-deserves-a-lawsuit America being what it  
is, what used to cause a few tears and -- okay, we'll admit it -- 
perhaps some cruel laughter, now generates lawsuits and fat 
contingent fees for lawsuit lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Safety advocates of the sort who believe in their hearts that  
all risk should be removed no matter the expense say this is a good 
thing. Playgrounds undoubtedly are safer. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet something of the fun and adventure of childhood has been  
lost. Kids, after all, want -- whether it really makes sense at the 
moment or not -- to test their limits and see what they can do at 
play. They'll always want to climb higher, run faster and whatnot -- 
and some number of kids always will get hurt. Hard lessons are part 
of the way we learn. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 9  
</P>
<P>
	Daily Freeman, Kingston, N.Y., on late state budget:  
</P>
<P>
	When it comes to state government, words occasionally fail us.  
</P>
<P>
	We scratch our heads and stroke our chins looking for just the  
right one to describe in polite company what passes as public 
service in Albany. The well nearly runs dry. 
</P>
<P>
	For today, ``shameless'' will have to do. ...  
</P>
<P>
	Last week, after finally putting the finishing touches on a  
budget, nearly the latest adopted in state history, the Capitol's 
Big Three -- Gov. George Pataki, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, 
D-Manhattan, and Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, R-Brunswick -- 
virtually tripped over each other to declare how well they'd done. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, in the hours just before and after legislative  
approval of the spending plan, fax machines in newsrooms all over 
the state were humming with press releases from local assemblymen 
and senators, all eager to brag about money they'd helped steer to 
various hometown district projects. ... 
</P>
<P>
	All this for a four-month-tardy budget that is the product of  
one of the most politically charged systems in the country, a 
budget that again set back the state's credit rating and a budget 
that caused uncertainty and fear among countless constituencies, 
particularly non-profits and the education community. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 10  
</P>
<P>
	Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal, on new rules governing private  
mailboxes: 
</P>
<P>
	Because the U.S. Postal Service has received more than 600  
complaints and questions since its revised private mailbox rules 
were announced in April, it is putting off their effective date 
from this fall to next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a wise move that will not only give private mailbox  
renters a chance to use up their old stationery, but may give the 
public time to see that the rules make sense for consumers and 
businesses alike. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules require an identifier in the address for private  
boxes, verification of renter identity and, importantly, also give 
the Postal Service time to make sure privacy is maintained for 
private box holders. 
</P>
<P>
	Most needed is the rule that vendors require photo  
identification of applicants. If a customer can't comply, the 
commercial mailer cannot rent that person a box. U.S. Post Offices 
already do this with box applicants. 
</P>
<P>
	The other contentious issue is the requirement that ``PMB'' (for  
``private mailbox'') be affixed to the address of everyone using 
such a box. Critics claim ``PMB'' carries a stigma, mainly because 
the rules were first announced in tandem with a call for curbing 
mail fraud. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Unclear, however, is who will have access to the box renter's  
application information, including the renter's home address. This 
is a critical question the Postal Service says it will clear up 
between now and next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The USPS says it will appoint a task force to ensure only law  
enforcement agencies and those with a court order can get that 
personal information. This must be done. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 11  
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Shimbun, Tokyo, on Russian President Boris Yeltsin:  
</P>
<P>
	Russia's President Boris Yeltsin must enjoy starting a week with  
draconian personnel change. This week, he fired his prime minister, 
Sergei Stepashin, who had just been appointed in May. Stepashin's 
tenure lasted only three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander Lebed, governor of Krasnoyarsk, made the glib  
observation that the reason Yeltsin's subordinates are so bad that 
they have to be removed from office one after another is because 
their boss himself is so bad. It is indeed extraordinary to go 
through five prime ministers in just a year and a half. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin named Vladmir Putin, director of the Federal Security  
Service and secretary of the Security Council, as prime minister. 
... Yeltsin has thus surrounded himself with men who have made 
their careers in security or political police administration. If 
they are respected not for their political and managerial prowess, 
but for their inclination to take control of government machinery 
as the president wants, there cannot be much hope of their 
injecting new vigor into the Russian government. Yeltsin, in poor 
health, seems to presume that the decisive power of his authority 
comes from the way he demonstrates it by shuffling personnel. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 10  
</P>
<P>
	La Stampa, Turin, Italy, on Boris Yeltsin:  
</P>
<P>
	Boris Yeltsin's imagination seems boundless. Less than three  
months after dismissing Yevgeny Primakov and nominating Sergei 
Stepashin, Yeltsin is now replacing Stepashin with the even 
less-known Vladimir Putin whom he has touted as future president. 
It seems farcical that the Russian people -- only two percent of 
whom opinion polls show support the President -- have no choice 
other than to accept Yeltsin's protege. 
</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin's objective seems to avoid elections altogether, and in  
spite of this strategy's inherent dangers, the Kremlin seems to 
think that it's less dangerous than losing an election. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet now an even greater danger lurks. Moscow's governor, Yuri  
Luzhkov, has formed an alliance with powerful regional leaders. 
This cartel can expect the support of the most popular man in 
Russia, Yevgeny Primakov. Boris Yeltsin has nobody to stand with 
him in opposition to this party, besides himself and Vladimir 
Putin. It seems that that won't be enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Granted, Russia has many problems, but its most pressing one is  
an inability to free itself peacefully from Czar Boris and his 
``Family.'' Yet the White House still assures, ``For us, this 
changes nothing.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 11  
</P>
<P>
	The Mirror, London, on Prince Philip:  
</P>
<P>
	Other families have daft old men who are a constant source of  
embarrassment. But the Windsors' one is turning into a particularly 
unsavory example of the breed. 
</P>
<P>
	We have tolerated Prince Philip's countless gaffes over the  
years because he is the queen's husband. But his more recent antics 
go beyond a laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	He has insulted the Scots, Chinese and Hungarians, the grieving  
parents of Dunblane and the deaf. Yesterday he surpassed himself 
with an outrageous slur on Indians, insinuating they can only make 
poor quality fuse boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	It was so offensive even by Philip's standards that he had to  
issue a rare apology. But that is not good enough. Philip has been 
dropping the queen in it for too long and dragging down the 
reputation of the royal family as he does so. ... 
</P>
<P>
	He may well have been a loyal and trusty consort to her majesty,  
and he may well have performed many selfless acts of charity. But 
the truth is his behavior has become a liability at a time when the 
monarchy needs to modernize and move with the times. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 11  
</P>
<P>
	The Express, London, on Prince Philip:  
</P>
<P>
	We are used to the Duke of Edinburgh's (Prince Philip's)  
tactless, off-the-cuff remarks, But his latest, that a fuse box in 
a hi-tech electronics company looked as if it had been ``put in by 
an Indian,'' is a gaffe too far. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he has left it to a Buckingham Palace spokesman to do his  
dirty work and apologize on his behalf. If the duke was made to eat 
humble pie in person, it might drive home the offense his comments 
cause. 

</P>
