<P>
	Aug. 6  
</P>
<P>
	El Pais, Madrid, on Pinochet extradition to Spain:  
</P>
<P>
	The Chilean government proposal presented to the Spanish  
government for (resolving the Pinochet extradition case through) 
friendly arbitration would avoid the handing over of the dictator 
(to Spain) to face charges. ... 
</P>
<P>
	... Any negotiated way out (of the Pinochet case) that is not  
based in the courts would have incalculable consequences for the 
defense of human rights. Apart from mocking the memory of the 
victims, a hypothetical settlement between governments would open 
an uncontrollable escape route for present or future perpetrators 
of torture or genocide, sheltered by the highest levels of the 
state and protected in their respective countries by laws that give 
them immunity. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Many countries have the means to pressure others and Chile,  
undoubtedly, can pressure Spain. But higher values must also be 
weighed, the most important being the principle that those 
responsible for committing crimes against humanity should face 
justice. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 10  
</P>
<P>
	The Straits Times, Singapore, on rebuilding Balkans:  
</P>
<P>
	The Sarajevo postscript to the destruction of Yugoslavia has a  
rich irony not lost on fair-minded people. In a meeting in the 
Bosnian capital on July 30, the United States and its allies in the 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization resolved that, having bombed 
part of the Balkans to near oblivion, they will spend billions to 
rebuild the region. Do not even ask where the money is to come 
from. 
</P>
<P>
	What should be asked is whether, in humanitarian terms, this is  
not a grotesque distortion. Speaking of the genocide and famine in 
Africa which have displaced four million people compared with 
Kosovo's 850,000, the United Nations' two principals for refugees 
and human rights, Mrs. Sadako Ogata and Mrs. Mary Robinson, have on 
accasion decried the inattention paid that continent. To little 
avail. The Balkans are just the newest edition of selective 
recompense. Why? Is this Judeo-Christian triumphalism? 
Afro-compassion is out of vogue? Political expediency? Sadly, 
nobody wants to know. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 9  
</P>
<P>
	Der Bund, Bern, Switzerland, on crisis in Belgium:  
</P>
<P>
	Belgium's new prime minister, Guy Verhofstadt, is really not to  
be envied. He had barely taken office before he had to struggle 
with the unpleasant traces of dioxin which the cabinet of his 
predecessor Jean-Luc Dehaene had left behind. 
</P>
<P>
	The domestic farming industry is complaining of a dramatic loss  
of sales and is demanding, in spite of empty state coffers, 
financial assistance and the relaxation of expensive regulations on 
meat. Conversely, skepticism is increasing in other countries 
towards Belgium's meat production: its EU partners are only 
prepared to import Belgian food with strict controls. 
</P>
<P>
	Maneuvering between the demands of the domestic cattle industry  
and the legitimate concerns of the neighboring countries, the new 
government is skidding hopelessly out of control. Brussels has 
apparently learnt nothing from the mistakes of the past: with its 
muddling, amateurish information policy, the coalition has 
increased the mistrust in other countries even more. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Hope for an improvement in the Belgian patient has evaporated  
for the moment. With his inconsistent crisis management, 
Verhofstadt is muddling his way through the dioxin scandal in the 
same manner that led to the downfall of his predecessor Dehaene. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 9  
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney (Australia) Morning Herald, on Aboriginal  
Australians: 
</P>
<P>
	When world attention focuses on Australia before and during the  
Sydney Olympics next year, international interest in the position 
of Aboriginal Australians will intensify. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the story almost every foreign newspaper, magazine or  
television network will want to explore, raising the specter of 
possible Aborigine-inspired boycott action. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, barely a year away, Aboriginal leaders are talking not of  
boycott but a more subtle strategy -- that of shaming Australian 
governments in the eyes of the world for their mistreatment and 
neglect of Aborigines. 
</P>
<P>
	This strategy will anger many Australians but such anger is not  
only futile but misdirected. 
</P>
<P>
	If international scrutiny shames white Australia into necessary  
reappraisal of flawed policies, well and good. If it also sharpens 
Aboriginal leaders' understanding of the need for greater efforts 
on their part, even better. 
  	   	
</P>
