<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 00:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Glitz Winning in Iowa Straw Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMES, Iowa (AP) -- It's glitz thinly disguised as politics, where  
NBA star Karl Malone is as big a draw as those who would be the 
next leader of the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	For those not attracted to sports, how about a concert with the  
likes of crooner Vic Damone or pianist Roger Williams? Outdoor 
enthusiasts can choose between skeet shooting and bass fishing. 
</P>
<P>
	It's all happening, appropriately enough, under giant circus  
tents. Glitz and politics, it seems, have collided in the Iowa 
Straw Poll -- and glitz has taken an early lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has taken on a life of its own,'' sighed Sara Miller,  
Finance Director of the Iowa Republican Party and an organizer of 
Saturday's doings. 
</P>
<P>
	Straw polls have been a staple of Iowa politics for the better  
part of 25 years, but none have approached this year's edition. 
There isn't a bus to be had anywhere in the state, and the same 
thing holds true for golf carts. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't even think about renting a tent.  
</P>
<P>
	``The party rental places are pretty well cleaned out,'' Miller  
said. Caterers will make out about as well as Republicans, who will 
collect $25 for every vote cast. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine contenders for the Republican presidential nomination are  
headed for Ames, and most are throwing lavish parties for backers, 
organizing legions of buses to truck backers into town for the day 
and fighting for attention from the 600 or so journalists signed up 
to chronicle the event. That's three times the number of reporters 
who accompanied the president and first lady to Africa in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa event picked up additional steam when Texas Gov. George  
W. Bush, the overwhelming front-runner, said he'd not only compete 
but play to win. ``The Bush people really raised the bar on this 
thing,'' said Bob Haus, an organizer for publisher Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	With that, things spun happily out of control.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's been hyped to the point where you'd think the election  
was this Saturday,'' said former Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not a party without some entertainment, and the Iowa State  
Center at Iowa State University will be as much concert as 
convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander is bringing in country  
star Crystal Gayle to croon for backers munching on barbecue. 
``We've got baby back ribs,'' said aide David Kochel. Pork, of 
course. There's a hog industry crisis going on. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch promises the Osmond Brothers, Williams and  
Damone, in a concert clearly designed with baby boomers in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush is leaning toward the athletic, with a touch of salsa, a  
natural for a candidate courting Hispanics. Former pro football 
star Roger Staubach and pro basketball star Sean Elliot will be on 
hand, but the big local draw is retired University of Iowa football 
coach Hayden Fry, a very popular transplanted Texan. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to be outdone, Hatch is bringing in Malone, the Utah Jazz  
star. 
</P>
<P>
	A string of salsa bands will enliven the Bush tent. Politicians  
will be heading for the Bush tent in a motorcycle parade headed by 
Colorado Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell and Wisconsin Gov. Tommy 
Thompson. 
</P>
<P>
	Ames is a mid-sized college town of 47,000 with all the usual  
amenities, but forget about renting a hotel room there. Folks are 
being shipped 30 miles away to Des Moines to find a room. 
</P>
<P>
	Some resources are getting strained. The various campaigns  
really have rented all the available buses in Iowa, and there are 
no golf carts available because the 300 or so volunteers will be 
buzzing around the grounds on their electric wheels. 
</P>
<P>
	The best guess is about 15,000 activists will be on hand, and  
there'll be plenty of politicos mingling with the entertainers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole aide Monte Shaw insisted that they're playing things  
low-key. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not bringing in any quote, unquote stars,'' he said.  
``We've got real people showing up to help a real candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All of the candidates are being tight-lipped about their  
spending, but it's huge. Rumor has it Bush has leased more than 100 
buses and the phone banks in most of the campaigns have been 
humming for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	There is time for perspective, however.  
</P>
<P>
	Just down the road in Des Moines, the Iowa State Fair opens this  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're talking a million people and 400 acres and 15,000  
vehicles,'' said marketing director Kathie Swift. ``I think it 
would be somewhat bigger than those concerns, not to demean those 
concerns.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
