<HEADLINE> Browns' RB Still Has His Playbook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEREA, Ohio (AP) -- Running back Terry Kirby had some personal  
belongings stolen. Not the Cleveland Browns' secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby's sports utility vehicle was broken into Monday night  
outside Fawcett Stadium in Canton, Ohio, while the Browns were 
playing the Dallas Cowboys in the Hall of Fame Game. 
</P>
<P>
	When a police report was filed, among the items listed as  
missing was the Browns' playbook, a thick, spiraled notebook which 
is about the size of the Cleveland phone directory. 
</P>
<P>
	But, as it turns out, the report was incorrect. A smaller  
notebook, containing some of the notes Kirby takes during team 
meetings was stolen, along with a DVD player, some clothes and a 
pair of Kirby's shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't his playbook, it was his notebook,'' Browns coach  
Chris Palmer said. ``No, they didn't get the key to the castle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer said his players are required to leave their playbooks at  
the Browns' training facility to guard against them getting lost or 
stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyway,'' Palmer said. ``It's so heavy, I don't think a lot of  
players would carry it with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer said he wasn't concerned about what the thieves might  
have in their possession, and that Kirby would not be fined. 
</P>
<P>
	The vehicle showed no sign of forced entry, according to a  
police report. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't nothing major,'' Kirby said. ``It was just broken  
into. Shoot, I was more upset my DVD player was taken.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
