<HEADLINE> Rain Pulls Grains, Soybeans Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures retreated Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as beneficial showers moved into Midwest 
growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	While rains across key growing states were expected to do little  
to reverse damaged caused by hot, dry weather over the past few 
weeks, some market participants believed the precipitation will 
slow the deterioration in crop conditions that has occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers were expected in Illinois and Indiana, two key growing  
states that hold the most potential for yield loss, but forecasters 
predict rainfall totals will amount to less than an inch. Still, 
the moisture gave investors a chance to take a breather after a 
sharp rally in the past few sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices also fell as investors squared their positions in  
advance on Thursday's early morning release of the U.S. Agriculture 
Department's latest production estimate and demand reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery fell 7 1/2 cents to $2.89 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 5 1/2 cents to $2.35 1/4 a bushel; December oats fell 
1/4 cent to $1.19 a bushel; November soybeans fell 7 1/4 cents to $4.86 1/4 
a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle futures were mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while feeder cattle were mixed. Pork futures were mostly 
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .37 cent to 65.72 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .45 cent to 77.12 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .62 cent to 54.37 cents a pound; February pork bellies 
fell .70 cent to 57.75 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
