<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McDonald's Criticized in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- McDonald's Corp. has raised the eyebrows of  
Hong Kong government censors with a television ad that shows a 
woman loudly slapping her boyfriend in the crotch for stealing her 
French fries. 
</P>
<P>
	After being struck with a shopping bag, the man collapses in  
agony, clutching his groin. Some Hong Kong viewers were not amused. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the commercial was aired Aug. 1, eight people complained  
to the territory's censorship board, the Television and 
Entertainment Licensing Board, that ``the commercial has a bad 
theme and has bad influence on young people,'' said Mandy Au Yeung, 
the board's spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	The board is investigating and could warn or fine the two  
television stations that had broadcast the commercial, Au Yeung 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayee Tang, a McDonald's spokeswoman in Hong Kong, said the  
commercial was intended to show ``the kind of craving people could 
have for McDonald's French fries.'' The commercial targeted 
teen-agers, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. fast food chain had not received any formal complaints,  
but was aware of public concerns after a viewer phoned the company, 
Tang said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The concerns were around the slap. We had some big sound  
effects. Some thought that maybe it was too violent,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's started airing a new version Tuesday, which was  
edited to tone down the sound effect and cut some of the shots, 
Tang said. 
</P>
<P>
	The spot now only has one shot of a pained expression on the  
man's face and ends with the woman showing a ``cheeky but warm and 
sweet expression,'' Tang said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
