<HEADLINE> Clinton Discusses Peace With Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton discussed prospects for  
Mideast peacemaking today with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel 
amid signs the United States may have to help fix a timetable for 
an Israeli pullback on the West Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak telephoned Clinton and they spoke for about 20 minutes  
about ways to make Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's upcoming 
trip to the region productive, White House spokesman Barry Toiv 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Before going, Albright intends to meet here with the senior  
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and with Yasser Arafat's deputy, 
Mahmoud Abbas, widely known also as Abu Mazen. Arafat has been 
quoted as saying he wanted Abbas to succeed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright is due in Jerusalem on Sept. 2, tentatively planning to  
stop first in Morocco and Egypt. She also will hold talks with 
Israeli officials in Jerusalem, with Palestinians in Gaza and the 
West Bank and with Syrians in Damascus. 
</P>
<P>
	If a timetable for a phased pullback by Israel from another 11  
percent of the West Bank is not settled by then, Albright could 
intervene to prod Israel and the Palestinians into an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	While Israel prefers handling its negotiations with the  
Palestinians with minimum U.S. mediation, Albright has said she 
would ``calibrate'' her diplomacy to any need to keep the parties 
on track to an accord. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's conversation with Barak and Albright's planned meeting  
here with Palestinian officials are ``designed to see how we can be 
as helpful as possible, both in insuring the implementation of the 
Wye River agreement as well as assisting the parties in pursuing a 
permanent peace accord,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those two objectives are what Albright will be working on,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Barak envoy, Gilead Sher, is due to meet Erekat in Jerusalem  
later today to work on the timetable for Israel's pullback under 
the Wye accords that were negotiated last October in Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel agreed to relinquish 13 percent of the land in exchange  
for stronger action by the Palestinians against terrorism. After 
yielding 2 percent, former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu called 
a halt, saying the Palestinian Authority's efforts were not 
sufficient. 
</P>
<P>
	With Barak pledging to implement the Wye accords, Israel and the  
Palestinians have agreed the pullback would resume in September. 
However, they are in disagreement on when the two phases should be 
completed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
