<HEADLINE> NY's Lazio Puts Senate Run on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAY SHORE, N.Y. (AP) -- Rep. Rick Lazio may not agree with Gov.  
George Pataki that New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is the better 
Senate candidate, but he bowed to the governor's wishes Wednesday 
and put his own Senate hopes on hold -- at least temporarily. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me be clear about this, I am not leaving the race,'' Lazio  
said at a Long Island news conference. ``We are keeping our powder 
dry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio said he would wait until Aug. 31 to see if Giuliani  
decides to face likely Democratic candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton 
in the November 2000 race. If not, he said he would ask Pataki to 
``re-evaluate his position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki had asked Lazio to put off an announcement of his  
candidacy planned next week until Giuliani decides whether he will 
seek the Senate seat. 
</P>
<P>
	At an upstate appearance Wednesday, Giuliani was asked about  
Lazio's Aug. 31 deadline and replied: ``I think the most graceful 
thing for me to do is not say anything about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reminded that GOP Chairman William Powers also had suggested  
that date, Giuliani said, ``I'm great at resisting pressure.'' And 
when asked by an audience member whether or not he would run, he 
replied only: ``It looks that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican governor said Giuliani had earned the right to be  
the GOP candidate. Lazio, who represents Suffolk County on Long 
Island, said he disagreed, but is a team player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the better candidate. I am ready to get into this race,  
but I am doing right now what is in the best interests of the 
Republican Party. I don't agree with Governor Pataki here but I am 
doing this out of respect for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki, at odds with Giuliani since the mayor endorsed  
then-Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1994, had been under pressure 
from some GOP leaders to keep Lazio out of the race to avoid a 
divisive primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio acknowledged that unity is key if the Republicans want to  
secure the Senate seat now held by retiring Democratic Sen. Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	His loyalty won him praise from both the governor and state GOP  
Chairman William Powers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rick Lazio has done the right thing for himself, for his party  
and for New York state,'' Pataki said. ``As I said last week, he is 
a rising star with a bright future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Mrs. Clinton nor Giuliani has formally entered the race  
but Lazio, like Powers, urged Giuliani to make the decision soon. 
</P>
<P>
	The congressman has already raised $3.1 million for the race,  
compared to Giuliani's $2.6 million. A third potential GOP 
candidate, Rep. Peter King of neighboring Nassau County, has raised 
$487,596. The Democrats have set a fund-raising target of $25 
million for the Senate race. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
