<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Gets Rare Victory in UPS Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service won a rare  
victory in its campaign to curb offshore corporate tax shelters 
when a federal judge ruled that the United Parcel Service set up a 
Bermuda company to avoid paying income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	UPS officials said Wednesday they strongly disagree and are  
likely to appeal this week's ruling by a U.S. Tax Court judge, 
which could cost the Atlanta-based package carrier hundreds of 
millions of dollars in back taxes, penalties and interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision runs counter to other recent Tax Court cases  
involving similar arrangements by companies including Gulf Oil and 
U-Haul. At the same time, the Treasury Department is urging 
Congress to approve tougher penalties on corporate tax shelters 
that are estimated to cost taxpayers some $10 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Provisions which provide certain incentives and confer certain  
benefits on taxpayers will always be debatable,'' Treasury 
Secretary Lawrence Summers said in a recent speech. ``But there 
should be little doubt about transactions whose only objective is 
to reduce tax liabilities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although there is major disagreement on how to define a tax  
shelter, leading Republicans in Congress say legislation aimed at 
blocking many of them could move later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``High rollers are cheating and gaming our tax system, and  
honest taxpayers have to make up the difference,'' said Rep. Lloyd 
Doggett, D-Texas, sponsor of one bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The intricate nature of these tax shelters is apparent in the  
UPS case, which illustrates the how difficult it is for the IRS to 
prove they are improper. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1983, UPS created a subsidiary in Bermuda that was later  
called Overseas Partners Ltd., which was subsequently spun off but 
remains owned by UPS employee-shareholders. Its purpose was to 
provide reinsurance -- a way of spreading risk -- for UPS packages 
insured for over $100, according to court documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to that, UPS had handled this ``excess value'' package  
insurance itself and reported the revenue as income for tax 
purposes. After Overseas Partners was set up -- such companies are 
called ``captives'' -- the profit from the insurance was funneled to 
the Bermuda company not liable for U.S. income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	UPS insists that Overseas Partners was a legitimate operation  
and that a key reason for its creation was to avoid possible state 
regulations that could hamper its insurance activities. In 
addition, UPS argued that the Bermuda company was always intended 
to become a full-service insuror. 
</P>
<P>
	``UPS made a legitimate decision to get out of the insurance  
business,'' said company spokesman Norman Black. ``OPL is its own 
separate business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are good reasons to create an offshore captive insurer,  
said Timothy McCormally of the Tax Executives Institute. For 
example, an oil company might not be able to find unrelated 
insurers willing to cover costs of environmental cleanups at an 
affordable price. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real key in the tax shelter area is, do the companies have  
a business purpose for entering into the transactions?'' said 
McCormally, whose group represents tax officials at major 
corporations. ``If you don't have a legitimate non-tax business 
purpose, it's going to be overturned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the UPS case, Tax Court Judge Robert P. Ruwe said there was  
no evidence in company documents that UPS researched any pending 
state insurance problems. He also said the insurance rates were 
much higher than they should have been. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruwe said the company was ``motivated by the reduction of  
federal income tax'' in what the judge called a ``sham 
transaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The question of who should be taxed depends on which person or  
entity in fact controls the earning of the income rather than who 
ultimately receives the income,'' Ruwe wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS issued a notice of tax deficiency in 1995 for the tax  
years 1983 and 1984, which totals $67 million in taxes plus 
penalties and interest. UPS has continued the practice, however, 
and could owe some $259 million for 1985 through 1990 -- IRS is 
seeking taxes for those years as well -- and potentially millions 
more for years after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said UPS believes it is complying with all laws and is  
likely to appeal the ruling to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of 
Appeals in Atlanta. ``There are more than sufficient grounds for an 
appeal,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 09:20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court: UPS Avoided Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United Parcel Service owes hundreds of  
millions of dollars in back federal taxes that the package carrier 
avoided by creating a subsidiary located in Bermuda, a federal 
court has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision by the U.S. Tax Court held that Atlanta-based UPS  
is liable for taxes, penalties and interest for deductions it took 
related to the income of Overseas Partners Ltd., now an independent 
company that provides ``excess value'' insurance for certain 
packages. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling directly covers penalties and interest on $67 million  
in taxes from 1983 and 1984, a total estimated at $300 million. The 
company could owe some $259 million more in taxes alone to the 
Internal Revenue Service for tax years through 1990 and, because it 
has continued a similar practice since then, could be liable for 
millions more. 
</P>
<P>
	UPS spokesman Norman Black said today that UPS believes it is  
complying with all laws and is likely to appeal the ruling to the 
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are more than sufficient grounds for appeal,'' Black  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision, however, marks a victory for the IRS in its effort  
to stop practices by large companies to shield income from taxes 
through creation of overseas subsidiaries that have no real 
economic purpose. 
</P>
<P>
	In the strongly-worded ruling, released Monday, Tax Court Judge  
Robert P. Ruwe called creation of the subsidiary a ``sham 
transaction'' and dismissed UPS's contention that a key reason for 
doing so was to avoid possible state regulations against the 
insurance activities it was performing. 
</P>
<P>
	Trial testimony, Ruwe noted, provided no evidence that UPS  
officials had actually researched whether such state regulations 
were pending and little evidence that the Bermuda subsidiary was 
ever exposed to an insurance loss. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the ruling states, the ``extra value'' insurance was  
mainly a way of transferring profit from corporate headquarters to 
avoid federal income taxes by taking large deductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Company documents, Ruwe said show that UPS ``seriously  
considered and was motivated by the reduction of federal income tax 
that would occur'' by making the transactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Judge Rules on Sex Offenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The state's highest court has dealt a blow to the  
state's sex offender registry law, issuing a ruling that could 
entitle all sex offenders to a hearing before they're listed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pleased with the ruling and I think the courts are again  
reaffirming that not all sex offenders are the same,'' said Larni 
Levy, an attorney at the Committee for Public Counsel Services, the 
state's public defender agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Levy said the impact of the Supreme Judicial Court ruling issued  
Wednesday would be a ``complete shutdown'' of the registry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sex Offender Registry Board will ``have to cease -- and  
police departments will have to cease -- giving out any names to the 
public for any offenders,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The registry law became effective on Oct. 1, 1996. The idea was  
to protect the public from sex offenders living in their midst and 
to aid police in catching them. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the law, people convicted of certain offenses were  
required to register with their local police departments. Their 
names could be made available to people inquiring at the department 
and, for more dangerous offenders, police were to take steps to 
actively notify people in the community. 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge to the law was brought by a man who was found  
delinquent as a juvenile in 1993 because of a child rape 
conviction. The man, referred to in the opinion only as ``John 
Doe,'' challenged attempts to require him to register as a sex 
offender. 
</P>
<P>
	The court decreed that the man was not required to register  
until a hearing was held. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the attorney general's office and the public defenders  
interpreted the ruling to mean that hearings were required for 
people convicted of all of the various crimes for which the law 
requires registration. 
</P>
<P>
	Alice Moore, chief of the government bureau in Attorney General  
Thomas Reilly's office, said she was disappointed in the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``It further delays bringing information about sex offenders to  
parents who may want that information to take necessary steps to 
protect their children,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will work with the Legislature to craft a bill that  
complies with the SJC's decision today to require a hearing for 
every sex offender.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
