<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American League Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It's been a wild four days for Wade Boggs. After becoming the  
23rd player with 3,000 hits, Boggs joined Ty Cobb as the only 
members of that club to take the pitcher's mound. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on their way to a 17-1 loss  
Tuesday night to the Baltimore Orioles, manager Larry Rothschild 
turned to his future Hall of Fame third baseman to get the final 
four outs. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't much of a choice. It was going to be a position  
player, and Wade had done it before,'' Rothschild said. ``He throws 
a knuckleball, so I don't worry as much about him hurting his 
arm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The highlight for the 17,848 fans at Tropicana Field came with  
two outs in the eighth inning when Boggs entered with the bases 
loaded. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a hell of a week,'' said Boggs, who became the first  
player to homer for his 3,000th on Saturday night. ``I was dead 
serious about getting them out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After receiving a standing ovation, Boggs retired Charles  
Johnson on a fly ball to right field. He got the first two batters 
out in the ninth, including a strikeout of Delino DeShields. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys that made outs off of Wade Boggs, they came back and  
I said, `A Hall of Famer got you out,''' Baltimore manager Ray 
Miller said. ```Don't let it bother you. Just don't tell anybody it 
was a hitter.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs allowed one run on three hits, including an RBI single by  
Mike Bordick, before retiring Albert Belle on a soft fly ball to 
center to finish the inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was exciting, but weird. After seeing him get his 3,000th  
hit and now he's out there trying to strike you out,'' Johnson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boggs also threw a scoreless inning for the New York Yankees at  
Anaheim on Aug. 19, 1997. Cobb, who pitched in two games in 1918 
before getting his 3,000th hit, pitched one shutout inning in 1925 
for Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	In other AL games, it was Toronto 10, Minnesota 6; Boston 9,  
Kansas City 6; Oakland 6, New York 1; Texas 4, Detroit 3; Seattle 
4, Chicago 3; and Cleveland 2, Anaheim 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Sidney Ponson threw his league-leading sixth complete game for  
Baltimore. Ponson (11-7) allowed one run and six hits in recording 
his third complete game in his past six starts. The right-hander 
struck out five and walked two. 
</P>
<P>
	Bordick tied his career-high with five RBIs. The Orioles, who  
won for just the fifth time in their past 15 games, had dropped six 
straight to Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Devil Rays starter Dave Eiland (2-7) allowed six runs and six  
hits in 1 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Blue Jays 10, Twins 6    	
</P>
<P>
	Carlos Delgado hit two of Toronto's five home runs and the Blue  
Jays had 15 hits, giving them 40 in two nights at Texas and 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Shannon Stewart, Darrin Fletcher and Homer Bush also homered off  
Brad Radke (8-11) as Toronto maintained a one-game lead over Boston 
in the AL wild-card race. Delgado has seven homers in his last five 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelvim Escobar (10-8) allowed three runs and four hits in five  
innings. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Red Sox 9, Royals 6    	
</P>
<P>
	At Kansas City, Brian Daubach's double capped a four-run 10th  
inning after Tim Wakefield (4-8) struck out four in the ninth, but 
still blew the save. 
</P>
<P>
	Darren Lewis and Jose Offerman had RBI singles in the 10th off  
Matt Whisenant (4-4), and Daubach hit a two-run double off Mac 
Suzuki. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich Garces earned his first save.  
</P>
<P>
                       *Athletics 6, Yankees 1    	
</P>
<P>
	Scott Spiezio's two-run double in the sixth broke up a scoreless  
duel, and Ben Grieve followed with a two-run homer off Roger 
Clemens (10-5). 
</P>
<P>
	Omar Olivares (10-9) allowed one run in six innings to win his  
second game since he was traded to Oakland from Anaheim on July 29. 
Doug Jones earned his sixth save. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's, 10-2 on a homestand that ends Wednesday, improved their  
home record to a major league best 41-18 and stopped the Yankees' 
six-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Rangers 4, Tigers 3    	
</P>
<P>
	Royce Clayton hit a game-winning single off Nelson Cruz (2-4) in  
the bottom of the 12th, Texas' first hit since the sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Danny Patterson (2-0) pitched the 12th for the win. Rangers  
relievers Tim Crabtree, Jeff Zimmerman and Patterson did not allow 
a hit in the final 5 1-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Mariners 4, White Sox 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Seattle, Ken Griffey Jr. hit his AL-leading 36th homer and  
pinch-hitter Tom Lampkin's two-run double off Bob Howry (2-3) in 
the ninth inning gave the Mariners the win. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Moyer (11-6) pitched an eight-hitter for his first  
complete game of the season and 17th in his career. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Indians 2, Angels 1    	
</P>
<P>
	At Anaheim, Manny Ramirez hit a tiebreaking sacrifice fly for  
his major league-leading 115th RBI as Cleveland won for the 10th 
time in 14 games. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was the Angels' 21st in 25 games and fifth in a row,  
dropping them a season-worst 21 games out of first place in the AL 
West and 20 games under .500. 
</P>
<P>
	Longtime Angels teammates Chuck Finley and Mark Langston pitched  
to a draw before the Indians got to Mark Petkovsek (9-4) in the 
10th. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricardo Rincon (1-2) got four outs for the win and Mike Jackson  
earned his 25th save. 
  	   	
</P>
