<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US, Senate in Confirmation Squabble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Judges in waiting, ambassadors on hold, a top  
Justice Department job still in dispute -- President Clinton is 
prodding the Senate again to get going on confirmation of his 
nominees next month. 
</P>
<P>
	He complains of a political slowdown, but that's only part of  
his problem. The balky confirmation system reflects the strains 
between any White House and any Senate, heightened when they are of 
opposing parties. A nominee a president wants confirmed can be 
hostage to something a senator wants done, or undone. 
</P>
<P>
	That accounted for the final stall before Richard Holbrooke was  
confirmed, 81-16, as U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, to take 
a job that will have been vacant for a year by the time he gets 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	The Holbrooke holdup was over the complaint of one Republican  
senator at the job transfer -- he says demotion -- of a U.N. 
whistleblower, and the demand of two others that Clinton appoint 
their candidate to a GOP vacancy on the Federal Election 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	They didn't get their man. Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa said  
he'd made progress on the whistleblower case, but he's not 
satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	So when he lifted his hold -- the practice by which any senator  
can block action -- on Holbrooke, Grassley substituted a new one, to 
block three other ambassador nominees. He said that would increase 
his leverage, because he didn't think Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright was concerned enough to be ``out of sorts with the hold up 
of the Holbrooke nomination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of them is A. Peter Burleigh, a career diplomat who stood in  
at the U.N. during the long wait for Holbrooke, and has been 
nominated ambassador to the Philippines. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton didn't send Holbrooke's nomination to the Senate until  
Feb. 10, after eight months of background checks and ethics 
investigations involving his contacts with former government 
colleagues as a private businessman. He agreed to pay a $5,000 
civil fine, while denying he'd done anything wrong. Then the 
ponderous Senate system took over, and when the Foreign Relations 
Committee finally approved the nomination on June 30, Grassley and 
the others put it on hold. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the general public is somewhat perplexed about the  
procedures of the Senate,'' Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said, as the 
impasse yielded to confirmation on Aug. 5 after a 35-minute debate 
with no arguments; it was spent largely on praising Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton weighed in on the judges before the American Bar  
Association in Atlanta on Monday, complaining that political 
considerations are stalling confirmations needed to deal with a 
``mounting vacancy crisis'' in the federal courts. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary Committee,  
tried to preempt him on Sunday with a letter saying that handling 
has been balanced and thorough. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said only 11 of his 61 federal judge nominees this year  
have been confirmed, 13 have been approved by Hatch's committee, 
and ``37 are still stuck there.'' Hatch said the administration has 
been slow to send up background material the committee needs to 
assess the nominees. 
</P>
<P>
	No mention of the power play involved in that process. Hatch had  
stopped holding hearings on judicial nominees last winter because 
Clinton didn't name his candidate to a Utah court opening. He 
reopened the process in June after getting Clinton's assurance that 
Ted Stewart, a former Hatch aide, would be nominated. He was, on 
July 27. No delay on that one. The Judiciary Committee approved it 
three days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the unyielding Republican stall on the nomination  
of Bill Lann Lee, Clinton's choice to be assistant attorney general 
for civil rights. That one has been blocked in the Judiciary 
Committee; Hatch and other opponents say Lee pushed racial hiring 
quotas when he was a lawyer for the NAACP. He was named to the 
Justice Department's top civil rights job late in 1997, but there's 
never even been a hearing on a nomination Clinton has submitted 
twice. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told the ABA he is going to ask the Senate to ``do the  
right thing'' and approve Lee. That isn't going to happen. Nor is 
it going to make much difference. When Lee's nomination was 
blocked, Clinton installed him as acting assistant attorney general 
for civil rights, so he's been on the job since, despite the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 16:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Judge Rules on Sex Offenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The state's highest court dealt a crushing blow  
Wednesday to the state's sex offender registry law, issuing a 
ruling that could entitle all sex offenders to a hearing before 
they're listed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pleased with the ruling and I think the courts are again  
reaffirming that not all sex offenders are the same,'' said Larni 
Levy, an attorney at the Committee for Public Counsel Services, the 
state's public defender agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Levy said the impact of the Supreme Judicial Court ruling would  
be a ``complete shutdown'' of the registry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sex Offender Registry Board will ``have to cease -- and  
police departments will have to cease -- giving out any names to the 
public for any offenders,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alice Moore, chief of the government bureau in Attorney General  
Thomas Reilly's office, said she was disappointed in the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``It further delays bringing information about sex offenders to  
parents who may want that information to take necessary steps to 
protect their children,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will work with the Legislature to craft a bill that  
complies with the SJC's decision today to require a hearing for 
every sex offender.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The challenge to the sex offender registry law was brought by a  
man who was found delinquent as a juvenile in 1993 because of a 
child rape conviction. The man, referred to in the opinion only as 
``John Doe,'' challenged attempts to require him to register as a 
sex offender. 
</P>
<P>
	The SJC decreed that the man was not required to register until  
a hearing was held. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the attorney general's office and the public defenders  
interpreted the ruling to mean that hearings were required for 
people convicted of all of the various crimes for which the law 
requires registration. 
</P>
<P>
	The sex offender registry law became effective on Oct. 1, 1996.  
The idea was to protect the public from sex offenders living in 
their midst and to aid police in catching them. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the law, people convicted of certain offenses were  
required to register with their local police departments. Their 
names could be made available to people inquiring at the department 
and, for more dangerous offenders, police were to take steps to 
actively notify people in the community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
