<DOCNO> APW19990811.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 01:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton and Gore Campaign Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The good, the bad. The wins, the losses.  
Whatever legacy history bestows upon Bill Clinton's White House 
also belongs to Al Gore. Or so goes the president's endorsement of 
his vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``The record of this administration is his record,'' Clinton  
told Democratic fund-raising bigwigs Tuesday night after an 
unusually joined-at-the-hip day with Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really is a record of achievement,'' Gore replied. ``But  
the question is where we go from here.'' Gore, who wants to go from 
No. 2 to No. 1, called Clinton ``a true friend ... a partner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, they toured a mop factory together and conducted a  
roundtable with workers to highlight Gore's agenda for small 
business. They shared a limo back to the White House, lunched 
together in private, then ate not one, but two dinners together. 
The two supper shifts allowed Clinton and Gore to schmooze campaign 
financiers -- including Seagram Chairman Edgar Bronfman Jr. and New 
Jersey Nets basketball star Jayson Williams -- in more intimate 
groups of 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans seized on all the togetherness and issued a public  
reminder of Clinton's impeachment scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been together under all kinds of circumstances,''  
Clinton said before his first dinner -- of chicken and rice. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were times of great elation, times of great triumphs,  
times of defeat, times of frustration, times of intense 
difficulty,'' the president said. ``But we've also been together in 
personal ways. I talk to him about everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, Clinton and Gore paired up for the first time on  
the Campaign 2000 trail, picking up more than $300,000 in Arkansas 
and trying to put to rest lingering reports of dissension between 
them. More joint fund-raisers are planned. 
</P>
<P>
	But no money changed hands Tuesday night. Instead, said Gore  
campaign spokesman Roger Salazar, the reception and two dinners 
were intended to energize the people organizing future 
fund-raisers, thank those who already have and recruit new blood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need your help,'' Gore said. ``The decision will be  
contested because change always is resisted and we have been 
bringing change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, Republican National Committee Chairman Jim  
Nicholson put out a mock Gore 2000 campaign poster with the caption 
``Bosom Buddies'' under a photo of Gore hugging Clinton with both 
arms. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release, Nicholson recalled Gore's statement in June,  
as he launched his presidential campaign, that Clinton's Oval 
Office affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky was 
``inexcusable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now Gore and Clinton are back on the prowl, as a fund-raising  
tag team, working to shake down Democrat fat cats,'' Nicholson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Begala, a veteran of the 1992 Clinton-Gore campaign and a  
former White House political strategist, said Gore is smart to 
exploit the president's ``unmatched ability to raise issues and 
money'' and to rally Democrats. Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley 
is challenging Gore for the party's presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	But, added Begala, a Gore booster, ``You don't want them joined  
at the hip. Gore has to stand up and define himself with some 
force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their identical Tuesday schedules, Clinton and Gore kept  
distinctly different paces. Gore was the man with things to do, 
places to go. He kept the president and his motorcade waiting at 
the White House before dinner then dashed from dinner with a cell 
phone to his ear. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton acted the part of a man with time on his hands,  
lingering at the Hay Adams Hotel for a full 32 minutes after Gore 
and many dinner guests already filtered out. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 16:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medinah Country Club a Unique Place  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEDINAH, Ill. (AP) -- If the mosque-like clubhouse can't convince  
you, with its Egyptian murals, hand-painted rotunda and patios that 
look like something from ``Casablanca,'' then the hand-carved sign 
on the way out will. 
</P>
<P>
	``Allah Be With You,'' it reads.  
</P>
<P>
	As players and fans at the 81st PGA Championship are discovering  
this week, there's something special about Medinah Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing like it anywhere in the United States,'' said  
Don Larson, a Medinah member since 1975 and general chairman of 
this week's tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	No offense, Augusta. Pardon us, Pebble Beach. But Medinah  
combines challenging golf with impressive architecture, gorgeous 
scenery and a history that seems better suited to Hollywood than 
the PGA. 
</P>
<P>
	A bear once lived here. A camel used to visit. And all because  
in the early 1920s, some members of the Ancient Order of Nobles of 
the Mystic Shrine -- yes, that really was the name of their 
philanthropic group -- wanted a country retreat for their families. 
</P>
<P>
	As members of the Medinah Temple -- named for the Muslim holy  
city of Medina -- they wanted the club to reflect that history in 
everything from its name to its architecture. So before he drew his 
blueprints for the clubhouse, designer Richard Schmid spent two 
years traveling the Middle East and Europe in search of 
inspiration. 
</P>
<P>
	The result is a clubhouse that looks like a smaller version of  
the Hagia Sophia in Istanbul. The brown- and orange-brick building 
is three stories high and 104,000 square feet, with towers on the 
left and right sides. There used to be a minaret, too, but the top 
was knocked off by lightning and never restored. 
</P>
<P>
	The centerpiece of the building is the 60-foot rotunda. While  
the ceiling looks like a mosaic of cream, blue, orange, black and 
red tiles, it's actually hand-painted. The walls of the rotunda 
also are hand-painted, giving them a Byzantine flavor. 
</P>
<P>
	``There isn't anybody who walks in there for the first time that  
doesn't just gasp,'' Larson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first of Medinah's three courses opened in September 1925,  
and its first tournament, the Medinah Open, was held in 1930. It 
has played host to three other major championships, the 1949, 1975 
and 1990 U.S. Opens. 
</P>
<P>
	There is more to Medinah than golf. There's a gun club and a  
pool. In the early years, members could boat and fish on Lake 
Kadijah or go skating in the winter. There also was a ski jump and 
toboggan runs. 
</P>
<P>
	There were different events and parties, including the one to  
which a camel, Miss Medinah, was brought in to entertain members. 
There also was a bear that lived in a cage on the grounds for a 
brief time. But it bit a little girl's finger and members found it 
a new home. 
</P>
<P>
	Medinah currently has almost 1,000 members, though only about  
500 people have golf memberships, and there is a waiting list of 
more than six years. The most famous member is Michael Jordan, who 
joined in April and created a stir last month when he played with 
buddy Tiger Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a wonderful time,'' Woods said.  
</P>
<P>
	Despite its luxury now, Medinah has known hard times. Members  
had to bail the club out during the Depression, and Course No. 2 
was shut down during World War II, said Wally Hund, the club 
historian. A herd of sheep grazed on the other two courses to keep 
them in shape. 
</P>
<P>
	And when club officials asked the members to approve a  
renovation in 1995, it barely passed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Times were tough from the time this club started,'' Hund said.  
``What makes this club so special is the blue-collar people. Most 
of us are first-generation money. We're just a bunch of 
blue-collars who make this thing go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $10 million renovation closed the clubhouse for more than a  
year. The plumbing, heating and air conditioning were redone. The 
original murals and painting were restored. Rooms that once housed 
employees were turned into office space. 
</P>
<P>
	A golf lobby was created outside the locker rooms to display  
pieces of the club's history, including Hale Irwin's clubs from the 
1990 U.S. Open and the clubhouse's original blueprints. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17th hole on Course No. 3, the PGA Championship's host  
course, also was rebuilt. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Medinah is back to its original glory, Hund said.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty special,'' agreed David Steele, a Medinah member  
since 1979. ``Every time I play golf, I sit on the bench and look 
at the clubhouse. You sit there and think, `We're pretty lucky to 
be here.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 15:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sanders' Dad Hopes He Will Come Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- Barry Sanders' father played down  
speculation that his son might return to the NFL but vowed to try 
to persuade him to come back. 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said Wednesday that the running back didn't even  
ask his advice when he retired from the Detroit Lions at age 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, 1,458 yards short of Walter Payton's career rushing  
record, walked away from the game on July 28, the day before the 
Lions began training camp at Saginaw Valley State University. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Sanders said his desire to quit football outweighed  
his desire to play. 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said he told his son not to retire three years  
ago when he was considering it. ``This time he didn't ask me, he 
just quit,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Hughes, director of security for the Lions, has been  
staying at the elder Sanders' home in Wichita since Monday, 
generating speculation that the running back might be rethinking 
his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, a family friend, said Wednesday he came in response to a  
long-standing invitation -- and not at the urging of the Lions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not down here to try to convince anyone,'' he told The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes said he told only one coach that he was coming so he  
wouldn't be considered absent without leave. He said he decided to 
take a few days off during training camp and planned to stay in 
Wichita another day or more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came here to relax and have a good time,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Lions spokesman Bill Keenist said Hughes was visiting Sanders as  
a Lions official, but would not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Conspicuously absent was Barry Sanders, who was traveling in  
Europe. His father said he hasn't heard from him recently, and 
didn't even know exactly where he was now. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only time Barry called me often was when he was at  
Oklahoma State and he needed money,'' he said. ``He only calls me 
every once in a while now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Sanders said he expected to see his son when he comes  
back from Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said his son called to tell him about his decision to  
retire only so that he heard it from him rather than the news 
media. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was disenchanted with the direction the team was going. He  
was tired of losing,'' Sanders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders said he would do everything he could to get his son to  
come back to the team and had promised the Lions before Hughes' 
visit that he would try. 
</P>
<P>
	``It stung me a little bit, but it didn't disappoint me,'' he  
said of the retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lions have not made a significant move to replace Sanders.  
Only one back, Jerris McPhail, was not on the roster at the time 
Sanders announced his retirement. McPhail was with the Lions last 
year but did not carry the ball or catch a pass. He was picked by 
the Browns in the expansion draft, but was cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Rivers, Sanders' backup the last four years, is No. 1 on the  
depth chart. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders has avoided all contact with the Lions' front office and  
coaching staff since the final game of the 1998 season. Coach Bobby 
Ross attempted to contact him through a total of 13 telephone calls 
or handwritten letters, but Sanders did not respond to any of them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 20:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Magic Ships Austin to Wizards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Orlando Magic, undergoing a massive  
overhaul, traded center Ike Austin to the Washington Wizards for 
Terry Davis, Ben Wallace, Tim Legler and Jeff McInnis on Wednesday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Austin, who signed a three-year, $15 million as a free agent in  
January, is the fourth Magic starter from last season to be dealt 
since the club initiated plan to assemble a younger, more athletic 
team for first-year coach Doc Rivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Horace Grant was sent to Seattle in a draft-night trade  
that brought rookie Corey Maggette to Orlando. Swingman Nick 
Anderson was moved to the Sacramento Kings for Tariq Abdul-Wahad, 
and four-time All-Star Penny Hardaway went to the Phoenix Suns last 
week in a sign-and-trade deal for Danny Manning and Pat Garrity. 
</P>
<P>
	Point guard Darrell Armstrong is the only starter remaining for  
a team that posted a surprising 33-17 record before losing in the 
first round of the playoffs last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``This transaction continues to set the foundation for our plans  
to relaunch the Magic,'' general manager John Gabriel said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We look forward to the contributions of Terry Davis and Ben  
Wallace in the frontcourt and Tim Legler and Jeff McInnis in the 
backcourt. We certainly wish Ike well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Austin, who will turn 30 next week, was a disappointment in his  
only season in Orlando. He averaged 9.7 points and 4.8 rebounds, 
and his role diminished as the year progressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this trade, we have acquired a talented center in Isaac  
Austin,'' Washington general manager Wes Unseld said in a 
statement. ``Ike is just coming into his prime, and he addresses a 
vital need for this team. His abilities in the low post give us 
weapons we just did not have last season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, 32, started 34 games and averaged 3.4 points and 3.8  
rebounds for Washington last season, while Wallace, 24, led the 
Wizards with 8.6 rebounds and 1.6 blocks per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Legler, 32, is a 44 percent career 3-point shooter who headed to  
his seventh team in 10 seasons. He averaged four points during the 
lockout-shortened season. 
</P>
<P>
	McInnis, 24, was a second-round draft pick of the Denver Nuggets  
in 1996. He appeared in 35 games last season, averaging 3.7 points 
and 2.1 assists. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 10:35:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y.'s Lazio Suspends Senate Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAY SHORE, N.Y. (AP) -- Rep. Rick Lazio said today he will put  
his U.S. Senate campaign plans on hold while New York City Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani mulls getting into the race. But he urged the 
mayor to decide quickly for the good of the Republican Party. 
</P>
<P>
	While bowing to Gov. George Pataki's wish to give Giuliani a  
chance to make up his mind, Lazio said he was not withdrawing from 
the race and did not rule out a primary run against the mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not closing any doors,'' Lazio said at a news conference  
where he stood at a podium adorned with a Lazio 2000 campaign 
poster. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he publicly disagreed with the governor's view that  
Giuliani has earned the right to be the GOP candidate, Lazio said 
he was acquiescing ``out of respect'' for Pataki. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Pataki asked Lazio to defer the Senate candidacy  
announcement he had planned to make next week. The Republican 
governor said Giuliani had earned the right to the GOP Senate 
nomination and urged the mayor to quickly declare his candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio's action could allow Giuliani to concentrate completely on  
his likely Democratic opponent in the general election, first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	But Giuliani on Tuesday warned that ``everybody has escalated  
this election way too fast. People are going to be really bored 
with it in about three months if we don't slow it down a little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, the mayor refused to comment on Lazio's plans.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've got my own decisions to make, campaign to put together,  
money to raise, political support to gather,'' Giuliani said. ``I'm 
not going to pay attention to anybody else's campaign until some 
time a year from now when this election really gets started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki's move was designed to avoid a potentially bitter GOP  
primary. The governor had been under pressure from some national 
and New York GOP leaders to use his muscle to keep Lazio out of the 
race on the grounds that Giuliani would be a stronger Republican 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	State GOP Chairman William Powers, a Pataki ally and Giuliani  
booster, said Tuesday that he has encouraged the mayor to announce 
his candidacy before the end of this month. Powers said the mayor 
was noncommittal, but had agreed to step up his campaign-like trips 
across the state. Giuliani planned a speech to a Republican women's 
club in Cooperstown today. 
</P>
<P>
	Powers said he feared that by not declaring his candidacy  
quickly, the mayor could hurt his money-raising efforts for a race 
in which Mrs. Clinton's backers have set a fund-raising target of 
$25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats were quick to jump into the fray, claiming Tuesday  
that Lazio was a victim of the governor's desire to please Texas 
Gov. George W. Bush and enhance his own chances of winning the No. 
2 spot on the GOP national ticket next year by forging Republican 
unity in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	While both Mrs. Clinton and the mayor have formed Senate  
exploratory committees and are raising money for their possible 
Senate bids, neither has formally announced their candidacies. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki has had frosty relations with Giuliani since 1994 when  
the mayor crossed party lines to endorse then-Democratic Gov. Mario 
Cuomo in the governor's race won by Pataki. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 01:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton and Gore Campaign Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The good, the bad. The wins, the losses.  
Whatever legacy history bestows upon Bill Clinton's White House 
also belongs to Al Gore. Or so goes the president's endorsement of 
his vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``The record of this administration is his record,'' Clinton  
told Democratic fund-raising bigwigs Tuesday night after an 
unusually joined-at-the-hip day with Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really is a record of achievement,'' Gore replied. ``But  
the question is where we go from here.'' Gore, who wants to go from 
No. 2 to No. 1, called Clinton ``a true friend ... a partner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, they toured a mop factory together and conducted a  
