</P>
<P>
	``They were times of great elation, times of great triumphs,  
times of defeat, times of frustration, times of intense 
difficulty,'' the president said. ``But we've also been together in 
personal ways. I talk to him about everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, Clinton and Gore paired up for the first time on  
the Campaign 2000 trail, picking up more than $300,000 in Arkansas 
and trying to put to rest lingering reports of dissension between 
them. More joint fund-raisers are planned. 
</P>
<P>
	But no money changed hands Tuesday night. Instead, said Gore  
campaign spokesman Roger Salazar, the reception and two dinners 
were intended to energize the people organizing future 
fund-raisers, thank those who already have and recruit new blood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need your help,'' Gore said. ``The decision will be  
contested because change always is resisted and we have been 
bringing change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side, Republican National Committee Chairman Jim  
Nicholson put out a mock Gore 2000 campaign poster with the caption 
``Bosom Buddies'' under a photo of Gore hugging Clinton with both 
arms. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release, Nicholson recalled Gore's statement in June,  
as he launched his presidential campaign, that Clinton's Oval 
Office affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky was 
``inexcusable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now Gore and Clinton are back on the prowl, as a fund-raising  
tag team, working to shake down Democrat fat cats,'' Nicholson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Begala, a veteran of the 1992 Clinton-Gore campaign and a  
former White House political strategist, said Gore is smart to 
exploit the president's ``unmatched ability to raise issues and 
money'' and to rally Democrats. Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley 
is challenging Gore for the party's presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	But, added Begala, a Gore booster, ``You don't want them joined  
at the hip. Gore has to stand up and define himself with some 
force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their identical Tuesday schedules, Clinton and Gore kept  
distinctly different paces. Gore was the man with things to do, 
places to go. He kept the president and his motorcade waiting at 
the White House before dinner then dashed from dinner with a cell 
phone to his ear. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton acted the part of a man with time on his hands,  
lingering at the Hay Adams Hotel for a full 32 minutes after Gore 
and many dinner guests already filtered out. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
