<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Death Upheld for N.J. Girl's Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court affirmed today the  
murder conviction of Jesse Timmendequas and his death sentence for 
the 1994 rape and slaying of 7-year-old Megan Kanka. 
</P>
<P>
	The court in a 4-3 ruling rejected arguments by defense  
attorneys that Timmendequas' 1997 trial in Mercer County was 
tainted by local publicity since it was only a few miles from the 
murder scene. 
</P>
<P>
	The murder prompted a state and national movement to enact  
``Megan's Laws'' to keep track of convicted sex offenders after 
their release from prison and to provide community notifications on 
the whereabouts of the most dangerous ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Timmendequas had been convicted twice of serious sex crimes but  
the Kanka family, who lived across the street from him in quiet 
Hamilton Township, had no idea of his past. 
</P>
<P>
	Timmendequas, 37, was convicted of luring the girl into his  
home, raping and strangling her and dumping her body in a nearby 
park. Megan's mother, Maureen Kanka, has become a national advocate 
for tougher sex-offender laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Timmendequas' lawyers argued that because the case was so widely  
known, it is likely the jury -- which was bused in from neighboring 
Hunterdon County -- was aware of his prior convictions. Information 
about prior offenses is usually not permitted at criminal trials 
because it could prejudice the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Timmendequas is now entitled to two more appeals to check the  
verdict for fairness as compared with other cases and to seek a new 
trial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
