<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Futures Rocket Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures rose sharply Wednesday on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange after industry reports showed U.S. inventories 
fell to their lowest levels since January. 
</P>
<P>
	Other energy prices also gained. On other markets, grain and  
soybean futures fall sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude rose to its highest level in nearly two years after the  
American Petroleum Institute reported inventories fell 3.16 million 
barrels, or 1 percent, last week to 323.1 million barrels, the 
lowest level since Jan. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	That was double what even the most optimistic analysts had  
estimated, and came as imports tumbled 5 percent during that week. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline inventories also fell an unexpectedly sharp 3.476  
million barrels, the API reported, while heating oil and other 
distillates fell unexpectedly by 647,000 barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline, the third in as many weeks, highlighted the  
concerted effort made by world oil producers to keep supplies off 
the market in a bid to boost prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude futures also gained after Chevron Corp. reported a fire  
forced it to close a pipeline that ships 210,000 barrels a day of 
crude through Texas. The pipeline moves nearly 4 percent of U.S. 
production and could further reduce supplies across the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The gains come amid estimates that predict world oil demand will  
rise sharply next year as Asian markets rebound from an economic 
slump and U.S. and European demand remains strong. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for September delivery rose 22 cents to $21.52 a barrel;  
September unleaded gasoline rose 0.94 cent to 65.97 cents a gallon; 
September heating oil rose 0.55 cent to 55.65 cents a gallon; 
September natural gas fell 4.4 cents to $2.704 for each 1,000 cubic 
feet. In London, Brent crude rose 14 cents to $20.63 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures retreated on the Chicago Board of  
Trade as beneficial showers moved into Midwest growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	While rains across key growing states were expected to do little  
to reverse damaged caused by hot, dry weather over the past few 
weeks, some market participants believed the precipitation will 
slow the deterioration in crop conditions that has occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers were expected in Illinois and Indiana, two key growing  
states that hold the most potential for yield loss, but forecasters 
predict rainfall totals will amount to less than an inch. Still, 
the moisture gave investors a chance to take a breather after a 
sharp rally in the past few sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices also fell as investors squared their positions in  
advance on Thursday's early morning release of the U.S. Agriculture 
Department's latest production estimate and demand reports. 
</P>
<P>
	December wheat fell 7 1/2 cents to $2.89 1/4 a bushel; December corn  
fell 5 1/2 cents to $2.35 1/4 a bushel; December oats fell 1/4 cent to 
$1.19 a bushel; November soybeans fell 7 1/4 cents to $4.86 1/4 a bushel. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
