<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clematis, a Many-Splendored Vine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POUND RIDGE, N.Y. (AP) -- For Father's Day my son, a middle-aged  
gardener himself, gave me a clematis I appreciated not only for its 
beauty but for his confidence that I could make it grow. 
</P>
<P>
	I've been lucky before with clematis, a sometimes difficult  
vine, but each new plant presents a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Before this June's gift, I have had success with two clematises,  
both large-flowered, which intertwine on a split rail fence. One, a 
Barbara Jackman, blooms early in summer with bluish purple flowers 
and creamy white stamens. The other, a Henryi, also early blooming, 
displays creamy white flowers with dark stamens. 
</P>
<P>
	The new arrival, called Niobe, came potted and about to bloom,  
so I waited to see what the flowers would look like before I 
planted it along the same fence. 
</P>
<P>
	They turned out glorious -- a deep ruby red with yellow stamens.  
You could think of them, if you want, as creating a floral Old 
Glory motif together with the blue and white flowers already 
established there. That is, if the plant prospers; I'll have to 
wait until next year to find out. 
</P>
<P>
	The name Niobe is not a happy omen. If you recall, she was the  
prideful queen in classical mythology who bragged that she had many 
more children than a goddess who had only two. They were then all 
slain and she was turned to stone. Makes you wonder what people 
want to commemorate when they choose the nonbotanical names of 
flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyway, by the time my new clematis had flowered in its pot and  
I was ready to plant it, we were in the middle of a July heat wave. 
</P>
<P>
	The best times for planting clematis are early spring and fall,  
but plants from pots can be set out throughout the summer if kept 
well-watered, so I dug a hole and planted it. At this time of the 
year, my site is in shade until midday, which was a help. Clematis 
needs only four or five hours of sunlight a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the foot of the fence is shadier than the rest, and thus  
cooler, a condition that clematis likes. 
</P>
<P>
	Its vines climb up the fence and into the sunlight. The soil  
where you plant should be rich and well drained. My grounds tend 
towards the acid, so I put some lime in the hole to sweeten it. 
That had worked well before for my other clematises. 
</P>
<P>
	The reputation for difficulty that clematis has acquired  
probably stems mainly from the need to make sure the original 
planting conditions, especially the shady base, are right. A summer 
mulch helps to retain moisture. In cold weather, north of 
Washington, it's wise to mulch before a heavy frost. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest buzz on clematis has large-petaled blooms like mine  
going out of fashion in favor of varieties with smaller flowers. 
The larger ones supposedly are prone to disease. Also, some people 
think they're too showy. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, anyone who has gardened awhile knows that flower fashions  
come and go. My large-petaled Barbara Jackman and Henryi have been 
blooming early each summer for more than 20 years without trace of 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	And I'm not embarrassed to say I revel in their spectacular  
beauty, or showiness, and hope to continue to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, there's a clematis for every taste and with various  
blooming seasons. A catalog I'm looking at right now, Greer 
Gardens, 1280 Goodpasture Island Road, Eugene, Ore. 97401-1794 
(telephone 800-548-0111), features 39 large varieties and 28 of the 
smaller kind. 
</P>
<P>
	My son started a small-petaled, fall-blooming one, Paniculata,  
this year at the bottom of a stone fence where it will climb among 
the crevices and, if all goes well, cover the site with pure white 
fragrant flowers. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from use as a climber on fences, walls, arches, posts,  
trees -- or onto other vines, like roses -- clematis, especially the 
small kind, makes a good ground cover. In one season, it can 
blanket the desired area with its green foliage and you get bonuses 
of blossoms here and there. 
</P>
<P>
	With clematis, the larger the flowers the fewer the number of  
blooms. It's up to you whether you want profusion or show or both. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	George Bria retired from the AP in 1981 after 40 years that  
included coverage of World War II from Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
