<DOCNO> APW19990811.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 14:01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jewish Center Security Tightened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Security was tightened at Jewish community centers and schools  
around the country today following the shootings that wounded 
youngsters at a similar center in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Buford O'Neal Furrow, identified as the suspect in the  
shootings, surrendered today in Las Vegas, Nev., the Union of 
American Hebrew Congregations had advised its synagogues and Jewish 
schools across the country to take steps following Tuesday's 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sacramento, Calif., where the FBI is investigating arson  
attacks that caused more than $1 million in damage to three 
synagogues, the Shalom School combined its classes into one and 
locked the classroom door Tuesday, said parent Stuart Nussbaum. 
Police stationed a patrol car outside, and the school also hired an 
extra security guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just very scary,'' Bloom said. ``It (the shooting) brings  
home the harsh reality that you can be shot at any moment. When 
things happen to the Jewish community anywhere in the world, as a 
Jew it makes your hair stand on end.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the shooting at the North Valley Jewish Community Center  
near Los Angeles, security also was heightened at centers in 
Denver; New Orleans; the Boston area; the District of Columbia; and 
communities in New York, Maryland and Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We brought in an off-duty police officer,'' said Bernie  
Karshmer, associate director of the Jewish Community Center in 
Denver. ``We'll have him at the preschool, and we'll have off-duty 
police here for the next three days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Denver police stepped up patrols of the area Tuesday and said  
the patrols would continue indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just decided to do that on our own,'' said police Lt. Eric  
Rubin. ``We're taking reasonable precautions at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once an hour in Washington, D.C., police officers stop by the  
Jewish Community Center, which houses a day-care center, a summer 
camp and a gym. A center in nearby Rockville, Md. was taking 
similar precautions. 
</P>
<P>
	Security in Massachusetts was stepped up at all 13 locations of  
the Jewish Community Centers of Greater Boston, said Alan Mann, 
executive vice president. Doors were locked and guards were posted, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as we heard about the incident in Los Angeles we  
convened a staff crisis team to review what we wanted to do,'' Mann 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Anti-Defamation League in San Francisco sponsored seminars  
on security for religious groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Tight security runs counter to the way religious people operate,  
said Jonathan Bernstein, director of the league's Central Pacific 
region. 
</P>
<P>
	``They want to open their institutions to anyone who wants to  
come in,'' Bernstein said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0132 </DOCNO>
