<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teams Using All Available Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	In this summer of blowout baseball, with team earned run  
averages hovering at the second-highest figure this century, usable 
pitchers are in short supply. Resourceful managers are searching 
for available arms wherever they can find them -- even on aging 
third basemen with 3,000 hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice this week, position players showed up on the mound, sent  
out as sacrificial lambs to finish off fiascos. For Matt Franco of 
the Mets, it was the second outing this season; for Wade Boggs of 
the Devil Rays, it was the second of his career. 
</P>
<P>
	The good news is that nobody got hurt. That, however, was purely  
by accident. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Franco's 75-mph fastballs nearly hit Mark Grudzielanek of  
the Dodgers in the head. Franco was so shaken by the episode that 
he felt obliged to call the Los Angeles clubhouse after the game to 
apologize. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they were guessing,'' he said, ``because I was  
guessing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Famer Tom Seaver, now broadcasting Mets games, was  
outraged by the affair, calling it a travesty that displayed a lack 
of respect for the game. Manager Bobby Valentine couldn't see what 
all the fuss was about, saying he had only one pitcher left and he 
wasn't going to use him in a lost cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Franco came away from his adventure allowing one run -- on a  
bases-loaded walk. At least he was well-rested. He hadn't pitched 
since July 2 in another Mets rout. 
</P>
<P>
	That paled by the amount of rest Boggs had between assignments.  
He tried out his knuckleball for one scoreless inning in 1997 with 
the New York Yankees, then put it in mothballs until Tuesday night 
when the Orioles were en route to a 17-1 victory over Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got a feeling about the fifth inning,'' he said. ``My palms  
started getting sweaty and Bobby Witt kept saying, `You're in this 
game, dude.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Three days after getting his 3,000th hit, Boggs trudged out to  
the mound, pitching out of a bases-loaded jam in the eighth inning 
and sticking around to work the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Franco, he gave up one run and nobody got hurt, not even  
him. It was a little dicey in the ninth inning, though, when he 
faced slugger Albert Belle. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing I was thinking about when Albert came up was,  
don't hit it back to me,'' Boggs said. ``I can take it at 90 feet, 
but 60 feet is a little close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franco and Boggs were the latest position players pressed into  
mound duty this season, where the team ERA stands at 4.75. Earlier, 
catcher Keith Osik of the Pirates threw an inning against Houston 
and third baseman Gary Gaetti of the Cubs worked one inning against 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies scored twice on Gaetti, who threw one shutout  
inning each of the last two years for St. Louis. Osik went through 
a tougher ordeal. He was lit up for four runs, all of them earned, 
and now is laboring under the burden of a 36.00 ERA. Compared to 
that, Franco's 13.50 is acceptable, and Boggs' 6.75 and Gaetti's 
6.00 are absolutely brilliant. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the best part-time pitcher in history was a guy who  
started out in that role, but found more productive work elsewhere. 
Even after Babe Ruth became baseball's most feared slugger, he made 
cameo mound appearances for the Yankees, winning five games. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth is the only pitcher who had over 700 home runs but Boggs is  
just the latest 3,000-hit man to make it to the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	At one time or another during their Hall of Fame careers, Cap  
Anson, Honus Wagner, Tris Speaker, Stan Musial and Ty Cobb, all 
members of that exclusive club, took turns pitching. 
</P>
<P>
	Wagner was the best of them, appearing in one game in 1900 and  
another in 1902. He allowed seven hits in eight innings with six 
walks and six strikeouts. What's more, he didn't give up any runs, 
leaving him with the best earned run average in history -- 0.00. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
