<HEADLINE> Banker Convicted in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Macquarie Bank executive director Simon  
Gautier Hannes was found guilty Wednesday of Australia's biggest 
insider trading crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Hannes showed no emotion as the jury forewoman declared him  
guilty of using confidential information to make 2 million 
Australian dollars ($1.3 million) from the 1996 takeover of 
Australian transport company TNT Ltd. by Dutch company Koninklijke 
PTT Nederland NV. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, after a two-month trial, the jury found Hannes, 39,  
guilty of two other breaches of the Financial Transaction Reports 
Act. 
</P>
<P>
	Hannes had entered pleas of innocent to all three charges.  
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution said Hannes used confidential information and  
the alias Mark Booth to invest in TNT call options ahead of the 
Dutch company's share offer in October 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Macquarie Bank, an Australian investment bank, was advising TNT  
on the transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Cecily Backhouse revoked Hannes' bail until sentencing on  
Aug. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian Securities and Investments Commission said he was  
the fourth person convicted of insider trading but the first to 
plead innocent and go to trial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
