<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Utah Tornado Kills 1, Injures 100  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A rare tornado swept through downtown Salt  
Lake City today, tossing trucks and trees around and shredding 
tents set up for a convention. At least one person was killed and 
more than 100 were injured. Power lines were ripped down, windows 
blown out and shards of glass were everywhere. The tornado also 
damaged the roofs of the Delta Center, home of the Utah Jazz, and 
the Salt Palace Convention Center, which was hosting an outdoor 
retailers show. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Surrenders in L.A. Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The white supremacist wanted in the shooting of  
five people at a Los Angeles Jewish community center turned himself 
in to the FBI today, telling authorities ``You're looking for me -- 
I killed the kids in Los Angeles.'' Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., 37, 
mistakenly thought he had killed some children. Los Angeles County 
Deputy District Attorney Craig Hum said he planned to file a 
warrant charging Furrow with five counts of attempted murder, which 
allows authorities in Las Vegas to hold him for extradition. A 
5-year-old boy was in critical condition today. Three of the 
shooting victims were in stable condition and one was released from 
the hospital. 

</P>
<P>
	Gov't Grants Disaster Declarations  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- All of Connecticut, most of Maryland and parts  
of three other states were declared drought disaster areas today, 
allowing farmers who have lost crops to qualify for low-interest 
loans. Six counties in New York, five counties in Virginia and one 
in New Mexico received disaster declarations from the Agriculture 
Department. The loans are limited to farmers who have lost at least 
30 percent of their crops and can't get commercial credit. All of 
New Jersey and West Virginia and 34 New York counties were declared 
disaster areas previously. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Gives Clemency to Activists  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton offered today to commute the  
sentences of 16 members of a Puerto Rican independence group if 
they sign agreements renouncing the use of violence. Their group 
staged some 130 bomb attacks on political and military targets in 
the United States from 1974 to 1983. An administration official 
said that the prisoners were not involved in any deaths. Clinton's 
action was in response to a campaign by human rights advocates who 
have argued that members of FALN were punished too harshly. 

</P>
<P>
	Pill Treats Deadly Brain Tumors  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Patients who fail therapy for a particularly  
deadly brain tumor are about to get an option that may extend their 
life a few more months. The government today approved the first new 
chemotherapy for brain tumors in 20 years. Temodar, known 
chemically as temozolomide, is an oral form of chemotherapy for 
adults with anaplastic astrocytomas. In a study, 12 of 54 patients 
-- a fairly impressive 22 percent -- had their tumors significantly 
shrink or temporarily disappear, the Food and Drug Administration 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Cos. To Bankroll Family-Friendly TV  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Eleven major advertisers said today they will  
pay to have writers develop family-friendly shows for consideration 
by the WB network. The advertisers, including Procter &AMP; Gamble, 
General Motors, IBM and Sears, say they are finding fewer 
prime-time programs during which they feel comfortable selling 
their products. The advertisers won't say how much money they are 
committing. But it generally costs between $60,000 and $90,000 to 
come up with a script, and they've agreed to bankroll at least 
eight. WB will decide which scripts, if any, go into production. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Offers Built-In Digital Modem  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM is introducing personal computers with  
built-in digital modems. The internal modems, made by Texas 
Instruments, are being offered as an optional feature with IBM's 
Aptiva line of computers, boosting the price by about $100, IBM 
said today. A built-in modem would likely make it easier and 
cheaper for people to switch from a dial-up Internet connection to 
the speedy, ``always-on'' technology known as DSL, or digital 
subscriber line. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends 132.65 Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks made their broadest, sharpest gains of  
August today as the Federal Reserve offered calming words on the 
growth of the U.S. economy. The Dow Jones industrial average closed 
up 132.65 points at 10,787.80. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 
1,865-1,171. The Nasdaq composite index rose 74.33 to 2,564.44. 

</P>
<P>
	Anderson, Falcons Agree to Terms  
</P>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson, who  
missed the first two weeks of training camp because of a contract 
dispute, agreed to a deal with the Atlanta Falcons after nearly 
four hours of talks today. Anderson and his agent reached the 
agreement after a meeting with Falcons coach Dan Reeves and general 
manager Harold Richardson. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  



  	   	
</P>
