<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Governors Plan Summit With Senators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Governors seeking a closer partnership with  
federal lawmakers wrapped up their summer meeting here by inviting 
the U.S. senators to join them at a summit next winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said the gathering, to be held February 2000 in  
Washington, would be the first time in recent history that the 
state executives would meet with federal lawmakers to discuss the 
balance of power. Governors also would meet with their individual 
U.S. House delegations on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah Gov. Michael Leavitt, a Republican, made the announcement  
Tuesday as he took over as chairman of the National Governors 
Association. He said he hoped the meeting would ``reopen, nurture 
and enhance'' the relationship between state and federal leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``As states, we have a very serious responsibility to protect  
the people as a counterbalance to the federal government,'' Leavitt 
said in a conference call. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as education was the focus during Delaware Gov. Thomas  
Carper's one-year term as NGA chairman, it appears federalism might 
get the same kind of attention under Leavitt. That is also a major 
interest of the new vice chairman; Gov. Parris Glendening of 
Maryland has written two books on the subject. 
</P>
<P>
	Leavitt compared the current balance to that of a mainframe  
computer, in which most decisions are made from a centralized 
source in Washington. He proposed state governments instead should 
resemble a network of personal computers, with national 
coordination but local control. 
</P>
<P>
	The NGA agenda for next year's meetings will include discussions  
on how to simplify sales taxes, improve environmental management 
and create public-private partnerships, as well as continued 
efforts to infuse technology into classrooms. That was the theme of 
the St. Louis NGA conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Leavitt admitted governors and senators likely wouldn't work out  
their differences overnight, but he said the meeting's symbolism 
alone would have immense benefits. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
