<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Regulators Nix Tent Camps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) -- Federal and state regulations aimed at  
improving housing for migrant farm workers have clashed in 
Washington state, closing camps and leaving seasonal cherry pickers 
scattered along riverbanks or sleeping in cars. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, a state program allowed the estimated 16,000 workers  
who pour into central Washington each summer to pitch tents on 
growers' lands if running water, sanitation and refrigeration were 
provided. In 1998, 25 such camps provided shelter for about 2,000 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Labor effectively shut down the program  
this year, threatening the state with large fines and saying the 
effort did not meet minimum federal standards. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials closed some illegal camps and paid for motel  
rooms for some workers. Other workers were left to compete with 
tourists for sites at campgrounds, sleep in their cars or camp 
along rivers without any facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Doc Hastings, R-Wash., has introduced a bill to exempt farm  
worker housing from requirements of the federal Migrant and 
Seasonal Worker Protection Act, providing the housing is already 
regulated by other state or federal agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Washington state worked hard to develop a reasonable plan that  
addresses the housing needs of migrant workers,'' Hastings said 
Monday. He said the state's own laws and inspectors would ensure 
the camps were safe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Farm Bureau and the Washington Growers League  
support Hastings' measure. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many farmers want to provide places for their workers to stay,  
if the program is reasonable, affordable and offers some protection 
against being sued by outside groups,'' said Jon Warling, the farm 
bureau's vice president for legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	But the measure is not popular with farm-worker housing  
advocates, who previously opposed the state's tent plan. State 
United Farm Workers officials say the bill would further relegate 
farm workers to second-class status. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastings said hearings on the bill will begin after Congress  
returns from its August recess. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 23:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Introduce Layden As GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Improving the chemistry between the general  
manager and the coach was the key reason why the New York Knicks 
hired Scott Layden. 
</P>
<P>
	That was Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts'  
oft-repeated explanation Wednesday as the team introduced Layden as 
its new general manager while also formally announcing coach Jeff 
Van Gundy's contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went after Scott Layden when I learned that he might have  
some interest in this job because I thought that the chemistry 
between these two would be very powerful and strong in a positive 
direction,'' Checketts said. ``I think today starts a new era.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Layden started that era as low-key as possible, giving few  
answers of much substance as he steered away from controversies 
past and present surrounding the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts selected Layden over Ed Tapscott, the Knicks' player  
personnel director who had been performing the general manager's 
duties on an interim basis since the end of the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Tapscott was considered to be aligned with former general  
manager Ernie Grunfeld, who was demoted last April when the Knicks 
were in danger of missing the playoffs and a rift developed between 
him and Van Gundy. 
</P>
<P>
	``His association with Ernie had very little to do with this  
decision,'' Checketts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts said race had nothing to do with choosing Layden, who  
is white, over Tapscott, who is black. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not about race or ethnic origin, it's not about  
sending messages,'' Checketts said, ``it's about making the right 
decision for this organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Layden, who spent 18 years with the Utah Jazz, will also have  
the title of executive vice president. Van Gundy, who has survived 
four mostly tumultuous seasons as coach of the Knicks, got a 
multiyear contract extension lasting at least through the 2002-03 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I keep having these press conferences to say I'm still here,''  
Van Gundy said, ``and here I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts said he interviewed other candidates, all of whom were  
``all too willing to give their opinions'' on Knicks personnel and 
the way the offense was run last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden will be Van Gundy's boss and will have final say on  
personnel moves, although everything will be bounced off Checketts. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden diplomatically refused to discuss any specifics related  
to the Knicks, be it Latrell Sprewell's history, Patrick Ewing's 
reduced role or the possibility that Charles Oakley might be 
reacquired. The first question he was asked dealt with the widely 
perceived notion that the Knicks need a top-notch point guard to 
replace Charlie Ward as the starter. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden would not say whether he'd maintain some of the  
philosophical standards he employed in Utah, such as refusing as a 
matter of principle to illegally stash players on the injured list, 
as most NBA teams do. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden also refused to give his take on the Knicks'  
turmoil-filled 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``My focus is to look forward, and I don't know the details of  
what went on,'' Layden said. ``It'd be foolish from my perspective 
to dwell on the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy said he expected to take the same roster to training  
camp in October while also disclosing that he's ``leaning'' toward 
moving Sprewell into the starting lineup on a permanent basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell seethed last season as Van Gundy kept him in a sixth  
man role until the Eastern Conference finals. Sprewell will be 
entering the final season of his contract, and could choose to play 
it out and become a free agent if he is returned to a reserve role. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts said the Knicks are eager to sign Sprewell to a  
contract extension that will keep him in New York well into the 
next decade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
