<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Short Circuit Slows Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The short circuit aboard space  
shuttle Columbia has been traced to a damaged wire and is holding 
up work on Endeavour, scheduled to lift off next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the weekend, technicians discovered the source of the short  
circuit that occurred five seconds into Columbia's launch on July 
23. The half-second short knocked out the primary computers for two 
of the three main engines. Backup computers took over. 
</P>
<P>
	It turns out that an electrical wire in the cargo bay had its  
insulation stripped away in one spot by a rough screw. NASA 
suspects a worker may have inadvertently pressed on the wire during 
preparations for a previous launch, agency spokesman Joel Wells 
said Wednesday. Contact between the wire and screw caused the 
short. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA has ordered additional lab analysis of Columbia's wiring to  
make sure there's nothing wrong with the wiring in Endeavour, 
scheduled to lift off Sept. 16 on a radar-mapping mission of Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia's launch, the first in NASA history to be commanded by  
a woman, Eileen Collins, also was marred by a fuel leak. 
</P>
<P>
	A nail-size plug in the right main engine came loose and banged  
against the nozzle moments before liftoff; three 
hydrogen-circulating tubes were ruptured. Endeavour has newer 
engines, none of which have this plug. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
