<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Security High at Jewish Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	In the halls of Jewish community centers and schools around the  
nation Wednesday, security guards and teachers watched for signs of 
trouble and strangers while police cars circled outside. 
</P>
<P>
	One day after a white supremacist opened fire on a group of  
children in the lobby of a community center near Los Angeles, many 
Jewish leaders were worried about copycat crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't feel like an isolated incident, it feels like  
somehow a little bit of a wave,'' said Rabbi Shea Hecht of the 
National Committee for the Furtherance of Jewish Education in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's an organized thing, but I think it's the  
copycat syndrome, where one says, `Why don't I do it, why don't I 
act on my hate?''' Hecht said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Coleman of Akiba-Schechter Jewish Day School in Chicago  
said Tuesday's attack appeared similar to a string of shootings in 
the Midwest last month. The shooter, a white supremacist, targeted 
blacks, Jews and Asians, and killed two people before turning the 
gun on himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Five people were injured in Tuesday's attack at the North Valley  
Jewish Community Center, including a 5-year-old boy who remained in 
critical condition Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., 37, turned himself in Wednesday in Las  
Vegas and told authorities he wanted the attack to be a ``wake-up 
call to America to kill Jews,'' said an FBI source, who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewish leaders said most of their community centers and schools  
step up security when major crimes, particularly anti-Semitic 
attacks, occur. 
</P>
<P>
	David Sorkin, executive director of two Jewish Community Centers  
in suburban Detroit, said his centers last increased security 
precautions about a year ago after a bombing in Libya. 
</P>
<P>
	``When things happen to the Jewish community anywhere in the  
world, as a Jew, it makes your hair stand on end,'' said Rabbi Brad 
Bloom of Temple B'nai Israel in Sacramento, Calif., one of three 
synagogues damaged by arsonists in June. 
</P>
<P>
	In Columbus, Ohio, two police officers stood watch over a tennis  
match at the Maccabi Youth Games. The five-day, four-city 
Olympic-style event involves about 700 young Jewish athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Security was also tight at the Jewish Community Center of  
Cleveland, with a police car at the front door and another one 
circling the center. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have any reason to think anything will happen, but we  
have to be cautious,'' said Bob Cahen, the center's executive vice 
president. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
