<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Webb Goes for Another Triumph  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WOBURN, England (AP) -- Karrie Webb, who just added a major to  
her growing list of victories, goes for another triumph in the 
Women's British Open, a tournament she has dominated. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Australian, fresh off a two-stroke victory in  
the du Maurier Classic, has won the British twice in the last four 
years and goes into the opening round Thursday with some of her 
toughest foes absent. 
</P>
<P>
	Juli Inkster, who trails Webb's $1.25 million at the top of the  
LPGA money charts, isn't here. Neither are Meg Mallon and Se Ri 
Pak, who have each won two tournaments this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest dangers to Webb appear to be England's Laura Davies,  
who let a late lead slip away in the du Maurier, and defending 
champion Sherri Steinhauer. 
</P>
<P>
	Davies won the WPGA Championship of Europe last weekend, while  
Steinhauer squandered a two-stroke lead going into the final round 
of the LPGA Challenge at Sutton, Mass., and saw the title go to 
Mardi Lunn of Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Davies strongly believes that the Women's British Open should be  
classed as a major. Although she triumphed back in 1986, that was 
long before the tournament started to attract the leading American 
players and she hasn't won since. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the one, the ultimate,'' Davies said. ``For me I would  
trade in the other 56 tournament victories for this one. It's the 
British Open, there's not more you can say about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's probably why I can't win it. I want to win it too  
much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although disappointed with last week's final-round slump,  
Steinhauer won the JAL Big Apple Classic last month and is pleased 
with her form. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year's win gave me a lot of confidence and I have been  
having a very good season this year,'' she said. ``Since the summer 
months I have been very, very happy with how I played, while at the 
beginning of the season I was rusty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Women's British Open returns to the Duke's Course at Woburn  
after visits to Sunningdale and Royal Lytham, and that will suit 
Webb, who won here in 1995 at age 20 before she joined the U.S. 
Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	When she went to Sunningdale two years later, she won by eight  
strokes in a tournament-record 19-under 269, five better than the 
previous mark by Jane Geddes. 
</P>
<P>
	Webb goes into this tournament as a top 10 finisher in 17 of 18  
events this season, topped by the du Maurier, the final major of 
the LPGA season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Six wins to the beginning of August is something I never  
really expected to happen,'' Webb said. ``I was hoping to have a 
good year but this is definitely above my expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A winner of the Australian Ladies Masters in February, a victory  
here would mean she would have triumphed in four different 
countries so far this season, with visits to Bermuda and Japan 
still to come. 
</P>
<P>
	Another big rival could be another former winner here, Emilee  
Klein, who won in 1996 at 22 but hasn't won an LPGA event since. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
