<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Colt Heyward Adjusts to Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- He's long past the anger and depression.  
</P>
<P>
	It's been almost a year since Craig Heyward's NFL career came to  
an end because of a rare tumor in his right eye. And even as his 
former Indianapolis Colts teammates are preparing for the 1999 
season, Heyward has moved on to life without football. 
</P>
<P>
	The best news is, he has one.  
</P>
<P>
	The tumor, called a chordoma, has been operated on twice and  
bombarded with radiation. Only tiny remnants are left, and they 
appear to be dormant. He still is blind in his right eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with training camps in full swing, Heyward doesn't feel the  
game tugging at him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't miss it. It's too damn hot. And the hotter it gets,  
the less I miss it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went through a funk -- 'Why me? Why me?' -- a little  
depression, stuff like that. I stayed in the house, didn't go 
outside, slept, didn't do anything,'' he told The Indianapolis Star 
by telephone from his home in suburban Atlanta. ``But then we 
started to go to church and, slowly but surely, it's lifted my 
spirits up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played 11 years,'' he said. ``Most athletes don't play that  
long in the NFL. I'm at peace with it. I've come to terms with 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After starting his third consecutive game at fullback for the  
Colts last Nov. 1 at New England, Heyward woke up the next morning 
unable to see out of his right eye. A battery of tests revealed the 
chordoma, a rare, slow-growing tumor that began at the base of his 
skull, extended behind his right eye, and was spreading into his 
brain and sinuses. It also encased his optic nerve and his right 
carotid artery, which supplies blood to the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a cruel, ironic twist for a player whose nickname was  
``Ironhead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Troy Payner, an Indianapolis neurosurgeon, was able to  
remove all of the tumor except the portion that surrounded the 
carotid artery. When he regained enough strength, Heyward headed to 
Boston, where he underwent the radiation treatment five days a week 
for two months, through mid-May. The result was as good as could be 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no evidence that the tumor is growing,'' Payner said.  
``But we will follow up with periodic MRI scans. I think he will 
look forward to a long and happy life, but his tumor does have to 
be followed. He can't ignore it. But my advice to him is to live 
his life as if he's going to live a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heyward went through treatment for alcoholism in 1993. Then he  
addressed a career-long weight problem with visits to a weight-loss 
center at Duke University in 1994. In the process, he rehabilitated 
his career, topping 1,000 yards for the first time with Atlanta in 
1995. He was released by the Rams after the 1997 season and signed 
with the Colts, his fifth team in seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of think everything happens for a reason and you don't  
know the reason as soon as it happens,'' his wife, Charlotte, said. 
``Slowly but surely, you figure things out. One of the reasons the 
tumor was discovered is he has been so resilient and he has 
overcome so many different things. 
</P>
<P>
	``Football has to end one way or another. This might've actually  
been easier than being cut because he was overweight or because of 
his age. We have a lot of friends who can't deal with being out of 
football because they feel it's not their time. With Craig, there's 
more to life than football and he's just concerned with getting 
healthy. It's made him a lot stronger, and it's made ... our faith 
in God a lot stronger.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
