<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albanians Want Access to Serb Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Ethnic Albanians demanding access to  
a Serb-controlled area again confronted NATO peacekeepers today at 
a bridge north of the capital, and several were injured 
accidentally. Others were reportedly beaten by Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a U.N. refugee agency official criticized some ethnic  
Albanians for what he called ``disgusting'' revenge attacks on 
Kosovo's Serbs -- including murders, assaults and forced removals. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kosovska Mitrovica, north of Pristina, Capt. Bernard Bonneau  
of the French NATO contingent said a 9-year-old boy suffered a cut 
in his hand and a young girl sustained a deep cut in her leg after 
being caught under barbed wire inadvertently dragged by a NATO 
vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other ethnic Albanians were beaten overnight in the  
Serb-controlled part of the divided city after Serbs forced their 
way into Albanian apartments and told inhabitants to leave, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three and 13 others in the group were taken to a French  
military base after the incident, said Bonneau. No arrests have 
been made, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	French peacekeepers shut the bridge separating the Serb from the  
Albanian side of Kosovska Mitrovica again late Tuesday, when 
hundreds of Albanians gathered there to protest the beatings. 
During a demonstration earlier this week, the French put barbed 
wire across the span to keep ethnic Albanians demanding access to 
homes in the Serb-dominated section of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	New barbed wire was put up today after a French armored vehicle  
inadvertently dragged the existing barrier into the demonstrators, 
causing the injuries. Kosovska Mitrovica is about 20 miles north of 
Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	The bridge is a symbol of the ethnic hatreds that complicate  
attempts by NATO and the United Nations to establish order in the 
wake of the vicious Serb crackdown on Kosovo's Albanians and the 
NATO bombing campaign that forced a Kosovo settlement with 
Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pristina, Ron Redmond, spokesman for the U.N. High  
Commissioner for Refugees, said the agency ``strongly condemned'' 
the ethnic violence, which he said appeared to be ``systematic'' 
and ``organized'' in nature. 
</P>
<P>
	He urged ethnic Albanian leaders to use their influence to stop  
``thugs,'' who he said ``employ some of the same disgusting tactics 
that were used against the ethnic Albanians themselves just a few 
months ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO spokesman Maj. Jan Joosten reported one woman shot to death  
and her 4-year-old child injured in eastern Kosovo, an area 
patrolled by U.S. and Russian troops. Dozens of ethnic Albanians 
were arrested for weapons violations or arson attacks, Joosten 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 35,000 NATO-led peacekeepers and an international  
police force are trying to control rampant crime and instability in 
Kosovo, where murders, arson and looting often motivated by ethnic 
hatred occur daily. Some of the crime is blamed on gangs seeking to 
exploit the postwar disorder, but revenge attacks by ethnic 
Albanians on a dwindling Serb minority also are occurring. Most of 
the province's 200,000 Serbs have fled. 
</P>
<P>
	According to statistics provided by the UNHCR, fewer than 2,000  
Serbs remain in Pristina, compared to a pre-war population of at 
least 27,000. Many of those remaining are elderly or infirm people, 
dependent on help from relief agencies to survive, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is highly unlikely that these people were involved in the  
persecution of Albanians, but that doesn't seem to matter to the 
thugs terrorizing them,'' Redmond said. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on information gathered during interviews with Serbs and  
compiled from NATO and other agencies' reports, Redmond said ethnic 
Albanian gangs often give the Serbs a written warning to leave 
their houses, then follow with a verbal warning. If the Serbs 
refuse to leave they are then assaulted or killed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO troops were working to prevent Serbs from leaving, but it  
was impossible to protect everyone individually, Joosten said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The final decision to leave lies with the people themselves,''  
he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
