<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Professor Won't Leave Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWTON, Mass. (AP) -- Professor Mary Daly, a self-described  
radical feminist theologian, is refusing to vacate her Boston 
College office, flouting an order from administrators who insist 
she has retired. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jesuit institution claims the tenured professor agreed to  
retire in January when told she had to admit male students to her 
seminars, which the 70-year-old had refused to do. Daly says she 
never signed any retirement agreement, and merely took a leave of 
absence. 
</P>
<P>
	The university gave her until Tuesday to remove her belongings  
from her office. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's a retired faculty member,'' said Jack Dunn, a university  
spokesman. ``We need her office for the new faculty member who's 
coming in to teach in September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Daly said she planned to return to her office today.  
</P>
<P>
	Known for works such as ``Gyn/Ecology: The Metaethics of Radical  
Feminism'' and ``Outercourse,'' Daly has long been a controversial 
figure at Boston College. She claims administrators pushed her out 
when threatened with a lawsuit by a male student. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, Daly took the university to court, but a judge ruled in  
a preliminary injunction that she was not automatically entitled to 
teach at the school. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision did not address whether she can legally refuse to  
teach men, although the judge did say that a school can set its own 
polices -- including insisting that all courses be open to both 
sexes. 
</P>
<P>
	The case now proceeds as a contract dispute and is scheduled for  
trial next summer. 
</P>
<P>
	But until the court issue is resolved, Daly is ``entitled to all  
the administrative support of a tenured faculty member, including 
an office and voice mail,'' said her lawyer, Gretchen Van Ness. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
