<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. Co. Faulted for Deadly Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- An Allentown chemical company was at fault  
for a deadly explosion that killed five people and leveled an 
industrial plant, a federal safety agency said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Concept Sciences Inc. was cited for 20 alleged violations  
including 11 willful violations which carry a proposed penalty of 
more than $600,000, the Occupational Safety and Health 
Administration said. If OHSA's rules had been followed before the 
Feb. 19 explosion, ``it is more than likely this catastrophe would 
have been avoided,'' OSHA spokeswoman Kate Dugan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion caused the walls of the 25-foot high building to  
buckle and collapse inward, dumping tons of concrete and steel on 
the workers inside and leaving nearly $5 million in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The blast happened in a 2,500-gallon fiberglass reinforced  
charge tank containing about 750 pounds of the hazardous chemical 
hydroxylamine, a volatile chemical used by semiconductor makers and 
pharmaceutical companies, the six-month OSHA investigation 
concluded. The tank was used in the distillation process. 
</P>
<P>
	``The explosion had the equivalent of 750 pounds of TNT,'' Dugan  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	OSHA could not determine what ignited the tank, since the  
building was destroyed by the blast. 
</P>
<P>
	Concept Sciences has 15 days to contest the citation or appeal  
before an administrative law judge. A spokeswoman said they were 
informed today of the OSHA findings and proposed penalties but had 
no immediate comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11 willful violations cited by OSHA included failure to  
compile safety information about hazardous chemicals; inadequate 
procedures for dealing with chemical disasters; and failure to 
train employees about hazards of dangerous chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't do a process hazard analysis or determine 'what  
could happen' and worse, they didn't train their employees about 
what could happen,'' Dugan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 07:50:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Takes Toll in Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW LISBON, N.J. (AP) -- From the 100-foot tower in New Jersey's  
Pinelands, Sean Morgart can spot trouble 10 miles away -- and the 
Forest Fire Service employee has seen plenty during this dry, hot 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it comes up in a dark cloud with a lot of turmoil in the  
plume,'' he said of smoke in the million-acre region, ``you know 
you're in trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the drought of 1999 has devastated Eastern farms --  
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman today made Connecticut farmers 
eligible for emergency loans, after doing the same Tuesday for New 
Jersey and parts of New York and Pennsylvania -- the dry spell also 
is taking a severe toll in woodlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Forest fires are easier to ignite, burn hotter once they get  
started and are harder to extinguish. Three times as many wildfires 
as normal have been reported in New Jersey this year, and other 
states are facing similar threats. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Massachusetts, 5,000 acres have burned since April; in a  
typical year, 3,000 acres burn. 
</P>
<P>
	--New Hampshire officials have counted more than 1,245 wildfires  
this spring and summer, compared with 550 in a normal year. 
</P>
<P>
	--West Virginia has recorded more than 100 forest fires this  
summer, instead of the usual three or four. And autumn -- when dry, 
fallen leaves pose the biggest danger of fire -- is still ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Even places that have escaped major forest fires have had small  
underground fires that burn into the forest floor, where root 
systems are starved for water. Firefighters must continually check 
back on blazes that appear to have been extinguished. 
</P>
<P>
	``They follow the root systems and sometimes burn horizontally  
under the ground for days -- sometimes weeks -- before they resurface 
again,'' said Jim Downie, a forest ranger with the Maine Department 
of Conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	Fires can start with burning cigarette butts thrown from  
automobiles, lightning strikes, campfires, arson -- even tall grass 
ignited by an automobile's overheated catalytic converter. 
</P>
<P>
	While few of this summer's fires have caused significant  
property damage and no deaths have been reported, they are 
decimating trees and shrubs that -- in some places -- will never 
recover, according to botanist Bruce Stein of The Nature 
Conservancy, an Arlington, Va.-based group. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem in an extreme drought is that you can have fires  
that burn hotter than normal,'' Stein said. ``Where the forest 
might be adapted for low-intensity fires, a hotter-than-average 
fire can be more destructive than normal fires.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey and other states have imposed drought emergency  
restrictions, including a ban on outdoor fires. They hope that's 
enough, especially come fall, when the danger increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so dry, anything can light a fire,'' Morgart said. ``The  
only thing left to do is to close the woods entirely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered rain fell on parts of the Northeast on Tuesday -- not  
nearly enough for Don Warne, a farmer with 600 parched acres near 
Romulus, in central New York's Finger Lakes region. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of towering over his head, his corn stalks now barely  
reach his waist. The corn itself is no more than half its usual 
size, some as small as his finger. 
</P>
<P>
	``The corn is cooked,'' Warne, 52, said with resignation, adding  
that he expects no better than half his usual yield and losses of 
up to $30,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
