<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo To Sell Securities Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea's debt-ridden Daewoo Group  
bowed to pressure from its creditor banks Wednesday and agreed to 
sell its most profitable subsidiary -- the Daewoo Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of South Korea's largest securities company was a key  
demand of Daewoo creditors. Daewoo had previously resisted on the 
grounds that it needed a cash pipeline from the business to support 
its automaking operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to sell Daewoo Securities came as creditor banks  
were forging a rescue program to keep the country's second-largest 
conglomerate afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo also agreed to sell its 46-percent stake in Seoul  
Investment Trust Co., a small financing firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo has said it will sell or spin off most of its 40  
subsidiaries and restructure itself around its core businesses of 
car manufacturing and trade. 
</P>
<P>
	But it had wanted to keep Daewoo Securities, which serves as a  
key financing vehicle for the rest of the conglomerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Creditor banks argued that Daewoo could not quickly relieve its  
cash strains without selling the profitable subsidiary by the end 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	While agreeing to spin off the firm, Daewoo declined to set a  
deadline. Such a deadline would deprive Daewoo of a chance to get a 
proper price, Daewoo spokesman Jang Sae-chan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo's last-minute refusal to set the deadline for selling the  
business delayed an announcement planned for Wednesday of a 
detailed restructuring plan. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been rescheduled for Monday, said Daewoo's main creditor,  
Korea First Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo is struggling under the weight of $46.5 billion in debt.  
It barely avoided becoming the country's largest ever bankruptcy 
when creditors agreed to roll over short-term debts for six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Desperate for cash, it is asking General Motors Corp. to buy  
part of its flagship automaker Daewoo Motor Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The government of President Kim Dae-jung believes that slimming  
down the country's bloated, family-controlled conglomerates, known 
as chaebol, is the key to rebuilding foreign confidence in the 
South Korean economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Such reform was a key condition of the record $58 billion  
bailout package South Korea took from the International Monetary 
Fund in late 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But chaebol have been accused of dragging their feet in spinning  
off their sprawling assets. A typical Korean chaebol controls 40 to 
60 companies that make such diverse goods as ships, computer chips, 
garments and food. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, creditor banks of Samsung, South Korea's No. 3  
conglomerate, threatened to suspend fresh credit and start calling 
in its $37 billion debt unless it moved swiftly to sell its 
debt-ridden Samsung Motors Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Samsung and Daewoo had tentatively agreed to swap their  
carmaking and home appliance subsidiaries as part of a government 
drive to reduce redundant facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	But more than six months of talks broke down after they failed  
to narrow their differences over how to resolve Samsung's $3.3 
billion in debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Samsung owner and chairman Lee Kun-hee had offered personal  
stock worth an estimated $2.3 billion to pay off part of the debt. 
But creditors said that was not enough. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker applied for court protection from creditors on  
June 30. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
