<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Tax Bill Helps Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- They pale in size compared with tax cuts for  
individuals, but tax relief items for businesses from railroads to 
arrowhead-makers were tucked into the $792 billion package 
Republicans pushed through Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Roughly $72 billion of the total cuts over 10 years would  
benefit businesses directly, and many stand a good chance of 
eventually becoming law even if President Clinton vetoes this 
version of the bill as he has promised. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you've gotten into the bill, you can go back up to the  
Hill and say: 'This is noncontroversial because it's been passed by 
either the House or Senate.' You've gotten a foot in the water,'' 
said Evan Liddiard, a partner at the KPMG accounting firm's 
national tax office. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the breaks are big and complicated, such as a $24  
billion change in the arcane world of international taxes to allow 
U.S.-based companies a new global way to calculate credits for 
interest expenses incurred while operating in foreign countries. 
General Motors Corp. led the lobbying effort for that. 
</P>
<P>
	Some are simple and much smaller: A provision with negligible  
cost inserted by Rep. Dave Camp, a Republican whose Michigan 
district is prime hunting territory, would allow makers of 
specialty big-game arrowheads to pay a lower excise tax because 
they would no longer be defined as ``essential components'' of 
standard arrows. 
</P>
<P>
	For business lobbyists, the changes merely rectify unfair or  
onerous portions of the tax code, even if they benefit primarily 
single industries or just one company. ``It redresses many 
inequities of the current tax law that needlessly restrict small 
business growth, stability and job creation,'' said Nelson Litterst 
of the National Federation of Independent Business. 
</P>
<P>
	Even some Republicans recoiled at the numerous provisions aimed  
at specific interests. 
</P>
<P>
	``For years -- and this bill is no exception -- we have ... put  
tax loopholes for special interests ahead of tax relief for working 
families,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who nonetheless voted 
for the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The sheer size of the tax cut, the largest since 1981, ensured  
that lobbyists stood a good chance of getting their provisions 
included. 
</P>
<P>
	Railroads and inland waterway barge companies, for example,  
objected to laws forcing them to continue paying a 
4.3-cents-a-gallon fuel excise tax to help reduce the federal 
budget deficit -- a deficit that no longer exists. Excise taxes, 
they argued, normally are earmarked for a specific purpose, and 
this tax no longer has one. 
</P>
<P>
	The money, GOP sponsors said in a letter to colleagues, could be  
used by the companies themselves to ``improve our nation's railways 
and reduce transportation and shipping costs for agriculture and 
businesses.'' The Republican bill would repeal the tax. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, defense contractors led by Lockheed Martin won  
passage of a provision allowing them to deduct from U.S. taxes all 
their earnings from foreign sales. That item, costing $1.1 billion, 
is intended, like many others in the international tax section of 
the bill, to help U.S. companies compete against European rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``These were designed to put American companies on a more equal  
footing,'' said Martin Regalia, chief economist at the U.S. Chamber 
of Commerce. ``They do have the option to leave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other items were aimed at struggling industries, such as  
independent crude oil producers, who would gain the ability to 
deduct five-year net past losses on a single year's income tax 
return. That change, costing $246 million, is similar to one made 
for farmers last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Still more provisions appeared tailored to specific companies.  
Enron Corp., for example, obtained an exemption from U.S. income 
taxes for oil and gas pumped through a pipeline that begins and 
ends in two countries but moves through a third. The exemption, 
costing $126 million and also affecting electricity, would be for 
what runs through that third country. 
</P>
<P>
	``Enron could run a pipeline through a third country and not  
have that income taxed in the U.S.,'' the company said in a ``tax 
issues briefing'' document for Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	At the other end of the spectrum, one $30 million break would  
repeal the 10 percent excise tax imposed on fishing tackle boxes 
but not on similar ``utility'' boxes often sold as cheaper 
substitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	This item was supported by the Illinois congressional  
delegation, led by House Speaker Dennis Hastert, on behalf of the 
Plano Molding Co. of Plano, Ill. Company officials say they've lost 
anglers' business to the utility boxes since the tax was imposed in 
1984. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think the purpose of the tax is to put us out of  
business, and that's what is happening,'' said George Mannina, a 
Washington lawyer for Plano. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Hastert's influence, Mannina said fellow Illinois  
Republican Rep. Jerry Weller, a member of the tax-writing Ways and 
Means Committee, actually took the lead, and Plano officials didn't 
invoke the speaker's name in making their pitch to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought our substance was so strong that we didn't need the  
political oomph,'' Mannina said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
