<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 18:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seahawks' Top Choice Agrees to Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHENEY, Wash. (AP) -- The Seattle Seahawks agreed to terms with  
their first-round draft choice, Lamar King, and unrestricted free 
agent wide receiver Michael Jackson on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	King, a 6-foot-3, 294-pounder from Saginaw (Mich.) Valley State,  
was the 22nd player selected in the April draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-4, 195-pound Jackson has played in the NFL for eight  
seasons -- five with the Cleveland Browns and three with the 
Baltimore Ravens. He had 38 receptions for 477 yards and no 
touchdowns with the Ravens last season. 
</P>
<P>
	King reportedly agreed to a five-year contract for $5.075  
million, with a $3.6 million signing bonus. He wanted a four-year 
deal, but went for a longer contract because he got a larger 
signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is an agreement,'' Seahawks general manager and coach  
Mike Holmgren said. 
</P>
<P>
	King, 24, will begin practicing with the Seahawks after he signs  
his contract, Holmgren said. He is projected as the backup to 
starting defensive right end Phillip Daniels this season, but 
Holmgren said he's put himself far behind the other players by 
reporting late to training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, 30, gives the Seahawks another tall receiver. They  
signed 6-4 wide receiver Sean Dawkins as an unrestricted free agent 
in May. 
</P>
<P>
	In his eight years of pro ball, Cleveland's 1991 sixth-round  
draft choice from Southern Mississippi has played in 114 games, 
with 92 starts. He has 353 receptions for 5,393 yards and 46 
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Ravens in 1996, he made 76 catches for 1,201 yards and  
14 touchdowns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
