<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navajo Nation Sues Tobacco Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Mirroring successful claims made by numerous  
states, the nation's largest Indian tribe sued the tobacco industry 
on Wednesday to recover the cost of caring for sick smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	A 135-page complaint filed in Navajo court alleges tobacco  
companies deceived Navajo Nation consumers, illegally targeted 
minors and burdened their healthcare system. 
</P>
<P>
	The claim seeks unspecified damages from eight tobacco  
companies, including Phillip Morris and R.J. Reynolds. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is about protecting our Navajo youth from a campaign  
targeted toward them,'' said Levon Henry, attorney general for the 
Navajo Nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Phillip Morris and Reynolds said they had not seen  
the lawsuit Wednesday and wouldn't comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice as many American Indians smoke in comparison to other  
groups, according to the surgeon general. The figures are worse for 
the Navajo. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, 29 percent of Navajo high school students said they  
smoked on a regular basis. The number increased to 47.5 percent in 
1997, said Louis Denetsosie, a lawyer representing the Navajo 
Nation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 12:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *That Was the Week That Was    	
</P>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of Aug. 15-21:  
</P>
<P>
	70 years ago: King Vidor's ``Hallelujah'' opened in New York.  
The film offered a stylized view of black life in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	65 years ago: Cecil B. DeMille's ``Cleopatra'' starred Claudette  
Colbert. 
</P>
<P>
	60 years ago: ``The Wizard of Oz'' premiered in Hollywood. The  
film starred Judy Garland, Ray Bolger, Bert Lahr and Jack Haley. 
</P>
<P>
	45 years ago: ``Dragnet'' opened in theaters in Chicago, New  
York and Atlantic City, N.J. Jack Webb, star of the popular 
television series, directed and starred in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Beatles opened a North American tour at the  
Cow Palace in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	And ``You Really Got Me'' by the Kinks was released in Britain.  
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: The Woodstock Music and Art Fair was held in  
Bethel, N.Y. Performers included Santana, Joe Cocker and Pete 
Townshend of the Who. The event was filmed and recorded. 
</P>
<P>
	And Frank Zappa disbanded the Mothers of Invention, saying he  
was ``tired of performing for people who clap for the all the wrong 
reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	25 years ago: Burt Reynolds starred in ``The Longest Yard,''  
directed by Robert Aldrich. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: ``The Woman in Red'' starred Gene Wilder, Charles  
Grodin, Gilda Radner and Kelly LeBrock. 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: Jennifer Tilly was dubbed Hollywood's busiest  
actress by the trade paper Daily Variety. She had 11 films to her 
credit in a three-year period. Commented Tilly: ``I do a lot of 
small character parts while some other actresses with bigger roles 
work on them a year or more. I don't think Meryl Streep called to 
complain that she wasn't on the list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And MTV decided to restrict the airtime of Cher's video ``If I  
Could Turn Back Time.'' MTV said the video showed more of Cher than 
some people wanted to see. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Actor David Caruso quit the cast of ABC's ``NYPD  
Blue'' to pursue a movie career. He was replaced by Jimmy Smits. 
</P>
<P>
	And ``The Lion King'' soundtrack became the first album of 1994  
to sell 5 million copies. The soundtrack included Elton John's 
``Can You Feel the Love Tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Carlos Santana, leader of the rock band Santana,  
was honored with a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. Santana's 
hits included ``Black Magic Woman,'' ``Evil Ways'' and ``Oye Como 
Va.'' The group performed at the original Woodstock festival in 
1969. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``So I just walked in, wearing my tux and my old `rubber-head  
makeup' and these big, fluffy, feathery, high-heeled, blazing red 
spiked heels.'' -- Actor James Woods, recalling how Robert DeNiro 
had sent him a pair of red high-heeled pumps before he did a scene 
in ``Once Upon a Time in America.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``Elvis was a great person and a very electrifying entertainer.  
He was a good friend of mine. And we had good times. And it just 
seems like yesterday, and it was back 35 years ago.'' -- Singer 
Jerry Lee Lewis, referring to rock legend Elvis Presley. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``What happened at Woodstock is that people remembered `Tommy'  
and people remembered the Who. What brought me back is a sense of 
looking at the reality of the whole thing and how it related to my 
career as an artist.'' -- Pete Townshend, who returned to the 
Woodstock rock music festival in Bethel, N.Y., for its 29th 
anniversary show. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
