<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parents React To Shooting News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) -- Jamie Jernigan first heard the  
news at work: A man with an automatic weapon had burst into a 
Jewish community center and shot five people, including three boys 
at day camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours later, picking up her young son Mackenzie from a day care  
center and school at a synagogue, she was overcome with emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't her son's school. It wasn't even her city.  
</P>
<P>
	``It just hits so close to home. My son's only 2 and one of the  
boys who was shot was only 5. It just shows that it can happen 
anywhere, to any child,'' she said, fighting back tears. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting at the North Valley Jewish Community Center in Los  
Angeles on Tuesday was the latest at workplaces and schools across 
the nation. They have teachers and parents worrying how to make any 
place safe enough for children. 
</P>
<P>
	The Union of American Hebrew Congregations on Tuesday advised  
its synagogues and Jewish schools to tighten security, and police 
in at least two Southern California counties increased patrols at 
schools and community centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gray Davis announced California agencies will form a task  
force to advise churches and child care centers on improving 
security. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congregation Emanu El Clare Cherry School, a non-secular,  
private school in this community of 180,000 about 60 miles east of 
Los Angeles, locked its doors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We told the children this was like an earthquake or fire  
drill. But instead of going outside, we told the children we were 
doing an inside drill because sometimes you have to stay inside the 
building,'' said the school's director, Roni Stein. 
</P>
<P>
	A handful of parents called the school concerned about security,  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In nearby Redlands, counselors at the Teen Center tried to ease  
fears with group discussions, said Paul O'Neill, the center's 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	Krinshanda Watts, 14, said most of the time she greets visitors  
to the center with a smile and a handshake. But Tuesday, she was 
keeping an eye on people. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time I saw somebody I didn't know, I was like `Who's  
that? Who's that?''' she said. ``You just never know about people 
these days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Back at Emanu El Clare, April Wursten was struggling with how to  
explain the shooting to her sons, ages 11 and 9. While she and her 
husband had discussed previous school shootings with her older son, 
she had never brought up the issue with her younger son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'll put my arms around him and tell him sometimes  
rotten people do rotten things, and then let him ask questions. 
It's something I'd hoped I wouldn't have to discuss with him yet,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	For Carla Herring, whose 7-year-old daughter and 4-year-old son  
attend the school, the job was more difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``I put my children in private school because I didn't want them  
to have to deal with gangs, drugs and crime,'' she said. ``Now, I 
have to tell them that even in a private school, a great private 
school, they aren't safe.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
