<HEADLINE> Main Tokyo Stock Index Rises / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The main Tokyo stock index rose slightly Wednesday  
in thin trading during the peak of Japan's summer holiday season. 
The dollar edged lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained a scant 9.07  
points, or 0.05 percent, to 17,211.16 at the end of the afternoon 
session. On Tuesday, the average closed up 11.64 points, or 0.07 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 114.70 yen at 5 p.m. (4 a.m. EDT)  
Wednesday, down 0.18 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below 
its late New York level of 114.81 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In the stock market, traders said strong June machinery orders  
reinforced the view the that the Japanese economy is strengthening, 
and many expected the Nikkei to trade in the same territory for the 
rest of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is firm market support at the 17,000 mark,'' said  
Yoshiyuki Higashi, an investment information manager at Taiheiyo 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Economic Planning Agency said Tuesday that core  
machinery orders in June were up 6.3 percent from May after 
seasonal adjustments, far above forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Machinery orders are a leading indicator of capital investment  
trends. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, trading was scant, with many participants retreated to  
the sidelines as Japan headed into the peak of the summer holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 325.39 million shares, while retreating shares 
outnumbered advancers 616 to 521, with 153 issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 52.55 points  
to close at 10,655.15 on Tuesday. The technology-rich Nasdaq 
composite index fell 28.87 points to 2,490.11. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 3.61 points, or 0.25 percent, to 1,420.64. 
The TOPIX closed down 0.28 point, or 0.02 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders said the dollar inched down during  
the day after Japanese institutional investors adjusted positions 
during the vacation lull. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the market's attention was fixed on a news  
conference by Ichiro Ozawa, leader of Japan's Liberal Party. But it 
was postponed. 
</P>
<P>
	Ozawa has threatened to break away from the alliance with the  
Liberal Democratic Party over a dispute regarding a proposed 
reduction in seats in the lower house of Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Although analysts have said Ozawa's departure would have little  
impact on policy, the end of the eight-month-old coalition could 
shake confidence in Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's administration. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 122.99 yen, down  
from 123.30 late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond dropped to 1.8300 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8950 
percent, driving its price to 99.74 yen from 99.19 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
