<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Launches Caucasus Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANSALTA, Russia (AP) -- Russia launched a new offensive today  
against Islamic rebels who are fighting for a Muslim-controlled 
state in the Caucasus mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian officials maintained they would only need a few more  
days to eliminate the rebels who invaded the southern Russian 
republic of Dagestan on Saturday, seizing several villages and 
clashing with Russian troops. 
</P>
<P>
	By today, the rebels claimed to have entrenched themselves in  
Dagestan's Botlikh region. They said they still controlled parts of 
the Tsumadinsky region, to the south. 
</P>
<P>
	But the commander of Russia's Interior Ministry troops,  
Vyacheslav Ovchinnikov, said Russian soldiers had taken full 
control of the Tsumadinsky region and were eliminating remaining 
rebels there. He said the rebel fighters in the Botlikh region's 
villages were surrounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia launched a new combat operation in Botlikh, Ovchinnikov  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels, who on Tuesday proclaimed an independent state under  
Islamic control in Dagestan, showed no sign of backing down. 
</P>
<P>
	A council of Muslim leaders, or Shura, named Shamil Basayev to  
lead their proclaimed state. Basayev is a Chechen fighter who 
played a key role in deadly attacks against Russia during the 
1994-96 war in Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	Basayev, speaking in the rebel stronghold of Ansalta, told an  
Associated Press reporter that all villages in Botlikh except for 
the main city of Botlikh itself were under rebel control. 
</P>
<P>
	He claimed his fighters had shot down seven Russian helicopters  
and one plane. Russia has said it has lost only two helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will fight until the full victory of Islam in the world,''  
Basayev said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had given control of the rebel army to Khattab, a  
Jordanian who has become one of the most prominent warlords in 
Chechnya. 
</P>
<P>
	The presence of Khattab and Basayev would appear to verify  
Russian government claims that the rebels are members of the 
Wahhabi sect of Muslims. The sect supports independence for 
Russia's mostly Muslim regions in the Caucasus. 
</P>
<P>
	Khattab, who uses only that single name, has long been said to  
be a Wahhabi. Basayev considers the group his allies. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian authorities raised their estimates of the size of the  
rebel contingent today, saying it included at least 1,200 people. 
Earlier reports had put the rebels at 300 to 600 gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	Khattab, however, told The AP the rebels were 3,000 strong.  
</P>
<P>
	Ovchinnikov said that 10 Interior Ministry troops had been  
killed and 27 wounded during the five-day campaign. Dagestan's 
Interior Ministry said 44 militants were killed and 80 were wounded 
in fighting Tuesday. There was no way to confirm the figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign is the largest challenge to Russian authority since  
the war with Chechnya, which gained de facto independence for that 
republic. Chechen gunmen have made frequent cross-border attacks 
into Dagestan and other regions since. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Basayev and authorities in Chechnya denied that the  
fighters in Dagestan were connected in any way to the Chechen 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Wary of repeating mistakes made during that war, Russia has been  
proceeding cautiously, amassing troops and launching attacks mostly 
from the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia was also enlisting the help of some 300 volunteers, who  
boarded buses today with an assortment of personal firearms to join 
the battle against the rebels. The volunteers were responding to a 
plea by local authorities to help put down the insurgency. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the ITAR-Tass news agency, 6,000 refugees have fled  
the fighting so far. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
