<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Taiwan in $2.5 Billion Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Boeing Co. signed a $2.5 billion contract  
to supply Taiwan's China Airlines with 13 airplanes on Wednesday, a 
day after losing a deal to sell the airline additional $1.5 billion 
in 777 jets. 
</P>
<P>
	The order to sell 13 747-400 cargo jets is Boeing's largest-ever  
order for the freighters, said Boeing's Asia president Fred Howard. 
The package includes options for four more cargo planes and two 
747-400 passenger models worth $1 billion more. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a year of nose-diving orders, Boeing is still smarting  
from its loss to rival Airbus Industrie in a bid to sell China 
Airlines a dozen Boeing 777 jets for $1.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus, the European airplane maker, will sign contracts with  
China Airlines for seven A340 jetliners worth about $2 billion, 
with an option to buy four A330s and another A340. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard said Seattle-based Boeing was disappointed at losing the  
passenger jet deal. The loss triggered accusations in Boeing's home 
state that Taiwan was snubbing Boeing to retaliate against U.S. 
government policies seen as unfavorable to the island. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course we would have liked to have gotten the other  
portion, but we respect their decision and will continue to work 
with our good friends and partners,'' Howard said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
