<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	For the second straight year, Jim Druckenmiller is the San  
Francisco 49ers' No. 2 quarterback in camp. Once again he's 
fighting to hold onto the job. 
</P>
<P>
	Druckenmiller is in competition with Jeff Garcia and Steve  
Stenstrom for the opportunity to back up Steve Young. All three 
will see action Thursday night, when the 49ers play host to the San 
Diego Chargers (0-1) in an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	Druckenmiller, a former first-round pick who is starting his  
third season in San Francisco, will follow Young. Garcia, signed as 
a free agent after starring in the CFL, and Stenstrom, a former 
Stanford star who played last season for the Chicago Bears, will 
finish up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have a healthy competition,'' coach Steve Mariucci  
said. ``All three are capable of being the backup. We're going to 
have to give them all a fair shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mariucci said he and his staff will closely monitor the  
performance of all three but in particular Druckenmiller because he 
will be the first one off the bench and will spend at least some 
time with the front-line units. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important for him to show us that he knows the system and  
that he's made strides from last year,'' Mariucci said. ``That he's 
a capable guy and can move the club. It's going to be a heck of a 
test because the San Diego Chargers have the best the defense in 
the league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Druckenmiller lost a training camp battle for the No. 2 job to  
Ty Detmer last year. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Falcons    	
</P>
<P>
	All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson, who missed the first two  
weeks of training camp because of a contract dispute, finally 
agreed to a new deal with the Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and his agent, Jim Sims, reached the agreement after a  
meeting at a Greenville hotel with Falcons coach Dan Reeves and 
general manager Harold Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the contract were not immediately available. The sides  
had basically agreed on a five-year contract worth $28 million to 
$30 million but stumbled over the signing bonus, guaranteed money 
and the structure of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who set a franchise record with 1,846 yards rushing  
and an NFL mark with 410 carries as the Falcons advanced to the 
Super Bowl last season, was expected to join the team for practice 
Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons play their first exhibition game Friday night  
against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Colts    	
</P>
<P>
	The Indianapolis Colts signed veteran quarterback Steve Walsh  
and released quarterback Stoney Case. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts are the sixth NFL team for Walsh, who was drafted by  
Dallas in the 1989 supplemental draft, traded to New Orleans in 
1990 and later played for Chicago, St. Louis and Tampa Bay. The 
6-foot-3, 215-pounder signed a two-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``He looked real good in the workout yesterday, better than I  
anticipated,'' coach Jim Mora said of Walsh, who had his first 
training camp practice Wednesday. ``I'm familiar with Steve. ... 
He's won, he's taken teams to the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Case had played four seasons in Arizona and appeared of four  
games. 
</P>
<P>
	Walsh has played in only 65 games during his NFL career with 38  
starts. He completed 9-of-19 passes in five games for Tampa Bay 
last season. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Bills    	
</P>
<P>
	Rookie fullback Shawn Bryson is gone for the season with a torn  
anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryson was hurt Tuesday afternoon when he cut and went down  
without being hit. Teammates said they heard a popping sound when 
Bryson went down. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Wade Phillips said Wednesday that Bryson, a third-round  
pick from Tennessee, will undergo surgery on the knee and will be 
placed on injured reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough situation. That's why it is such a tough game,''  
Phillips said. ``Some people begrudge them and they talk about the 
money these guys make, but they can get hurt at any time, 
certainly, and it effects your job.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
