<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lycos Nixes 'Jews for Jesus' Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) -- Lycos Inc., the popular Web destination,  
said it will not renew an advertisement from Jews for Jesus because 
of complaints from some in the Jewish community. 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos Inc. said it received complaints about the ad from several  
Jewish people who took offense when the ad popped up on their 
screens as they searched for Web sites containing the word 
``Jewish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jews for Jesus paid $1,700 for the ad, which started running  
July 6. 
</P>
<P>
	The ad, which promotes a book on the group's religious  
philosophy, read: ``The end of the world is no time to finally 
realize Jesus is the Messiah. (It's all in the book.) Click here 
for a free copy!'' 
</P>
<P>
	When users clicked, a Web page for Jews for Jesus appeared.  
</P>
<P>
	The page originally also referenced Lycos, but was changed after  
complaints were received and at Lycos' prompting. Jeffrey Snider, 
Lycos' general counsel, said the company did not want to give users 
the impression it endorsed Jews for Jesus. 
</P>
<P>
	Started in the 1970s, Jews for Jesus practices Judaism, yet  
regards Jesus as the Messiah. It has 70,000 followers nationally. 
</P>
<P>
	Snider told The Boston Globe that the ad's contract, which  
expires in several days, was not renewed because ``controversial 
advertising is bad for business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added the company does not want Jews to boycott Lycos.  
</P>
<P>
	The ad was opposed by the Anti-Defamation League's Boston  
office. Diane Kolb, associate director, said she believes the 
message is misleading and blasphemous. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jews can't be for Jesus,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Lycos officials did not say how many complaints they had  
received. 
</P>
<P>
	Jews for Jesus officials said they were disappointed their  
message was restricted. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Web is supposed to be a marketplace for all kinds of  
ideas, and people can click on them or pass them by,'' said Susan 
Perlman, spokeswoman for Jews for Jesus. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 15:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intidab Wins at Saratoga </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Intidab beat Artax by 1 1/2 lengths  
Wednesday in winning the $150,000 A Phenomenon Handicap for older 
horses at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	With Robbie Davis in the saddle, Intidab went six furlongs in  
1:09 in besting a field of seven horses aged 3 and up. 
</P>
<P>
	Artax was 2 3/4 lengths ahead of the favorite, Yes It's True. Good  
and Tough was fourth, followed by Run Johnny, Mint and Kashatreya. 
</P>
<P>
	Intibad, a 6-year-old, earned $90,000 for Shadwell Stable with  
his second victory in six starts since being shipped to the United 
States from the United Arab Emirates where he competed previously. 
</P>
<P>
	Intidab returned $22.80, $14.40 and $4.50. Artax paid $10.20 and  
$3.50 and Yes It's True was worth $2.10. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
