<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Wednesday morning as gains on  
Wall Street buoyed sentiment in Tokyo. The dollar rose further 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 130.27  
points, or 0.76 percent, to 17,341.43 in the first 30 minutes of 
trading. On Wednesday, the average closed up 9.07 points, or 0.05 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.64 yen in late-morning trading, up 0.94  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York 
level of 115.35 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices opened higher as investor sentiment  
was bolstered by rises in New York and Chicago, where futures 
prices advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shares have been boosted by the overnight rise in New York and  
the yen's relative stability around the mid-115 yen level,'' said 
Hidenori Karaki, general manager at Tokyo-Mitsubishi Personal 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 132.65 points  
to 10,787.80 at Wednesday's close. The technology-laden Nasdaq 
Composite Index climbed 74.87 to 2,564.98. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 12.54 points, or 0.88 percent, to 1,433.18. 
The TOPIX closed down 3.61 points, or 0.25 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, Japanese institutional investors covered  
short, or oversold, dollar-positions ahead of a long weekend for 
Japan's ``Obon'' holiday season. 
</P>
<P>
	There was little impact on the market from a Finance Ministry  
announcement that Japan's current account surplus expanded in June 
to 1.427 trillion yen ($12.4 billion), up 0.7 percent on year, 
traders said. June's rise came after four straight months of 
decline. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry also said that the surplus contracted in the first  
half of 1999, the first decline over a six-month period since 1996. 
For the January-June period the surplus was 6.3 trillion yen ($54.8 
billion), down 14.9 percent from a year-earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.22 yen, up from  
122.99 late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.8700 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.8300 percent, 
driving its price down to 99.40 yen from 99.74 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 07:10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Underwood Won't Play With Vikings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood's short and strange  
stay with the Minnesota Vikings is over. 
</P>
<P>
	The first-round draft pick who went AWOL after his first pro  
practice on Aug. 2 flew to Minneapolis on Tuesday night to meet 
with coach Dennis Green. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings issued a short statement this morning that read:  
``Dimitrius told Coach Green that he has no desire to play football 
and has decided not to play for the Vikings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team added: ``There will be no further discussion by the  
Vikings until certain other issues are resolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those are most likely the financial implications of the team and  
Underwood parting ways. He could be waived, suspended or placed on 
reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood's agent, Chris Domann, didn't immediately return a  
phone call to his office this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old rookie had decided after a phone conversation  
with former Green Bay Packer and minister Reggie White on Monday 
that he wanted to try to balance faith and football and that he 
hoped Green would have him back. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood flew to Minneapolis on Tuesday and was met by Vikings  
scout Jeff Robinson and team chaplain Keith Johnson. Underwood and 
Domann met with Green and others in a conference that lasted past 
midnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Green insisted Underwood's strange case and its  
salary cap ramifications won't alter the organization's risk-taking 
philosophy, a principle that reaped huge rewards in wide receiver 
Randy Moss last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't second-guess yourself,'' Green said. ``We have  
always been involved in second chances. That's part of our way we 
do business. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we're not going to change how we do business and how we  
look at things because of one time. We believe in what we do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, the 29th pick in the NFL draft out of Michigan State,  
where he missed his senior season with an ankle injury, left the 
Vikings without explanation one day after signing a five-year, $5.3 
million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	He hitched an 80-mile ride to the Minneapolis-St. Paul  
International Airport and apologetically told his agent the next 
day that he'd had to tend to a family crisis and was on his way 
back to the team. 
</P>
<P>
	But he didn't return and didn't call anybody.  
</P>
<P>
	A reporter from the Star Tribune of Minneapolis finally tracked  
him down over the weekend in a Philadelphia hotel lobby, where 
Underwood said he'd been torn between his faith in God and a career 
in professional football. 
</P>
<P>
	After speaking at length with White, the NFL's career sacks  
leader who retired from the Packers this winter, Underwood said 
he'd decided to return to the Vikings and ask for Green's 
forgiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, White told The Associated Press that, while he  
preferred to keep his conversation with Underwood private, he felt 
the troubled rookie needed to get in touch with Green ``and explain 
what he was going through because one thing he's done is left Denny 
hanging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the Vikings began exploring ways to part company with  
Underwood. 
</P>
<P>
	If he is waived and claimed by another team, his new team would  
be responsible for his $475,000 base salary for 1999. But the 
Vikings would take the salary cap hit for Underwood's entire 
$1,725,000 partially deferred signing bonus this season, rather 
than a prorated one-fifth slice of it. 
</P>
<P>
	If Underwood weren't picked up by another team, the Vikings' cap  
number this year would be only $345,000, the 20 percent cut of his 
bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	The team could keep Underwood on the active roster and fine him  
up to $5,000 for each day he was absent from camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood got about $543,000 of his bonus wired to his bank in  
Milwaukee, but the team had all but about $27,000 of it frozen upon 
his disappearance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
