<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Tornado Hits Salt Lake City  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Without warning, a tornado hit the  
downtown area today, damaging buildings and injuring dozens of 
people. The downtown area looked like a disaster zone with trucks 
overturned, power lines down, windows blown out, shards of glass 
everywhere. Police and firefighters attended to dozens of injured. 
Helicopters were landing to ferry injured to hospitals. The black 
funnel uprooted trees and temporary buildings set up for a 
retailers convention. It damaged the roof of the Delta Center, home 
of the Utah Jazz, and a nearby hotel where windows were blown out. 

</P>
<P>
	Shooting Suspect Gives Up  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The white supremacist accused of wounding five  
people at a Jewish community center in suburban Los Angeles 
surrendered today, telling authorities he wanted his act to be ``a 
wake-up call to America to kill Jews.'' Authorities said Buford 
O'Neal Furrow, 37, also would be charged in the slaying of a postal 
worker not far from the Jewish center. The man who identified 
himself as Furrow, who had walked into an FBI office to give 
himself up, told authorities he took two cabs for the 275-mile trip 
from Los Angeles to Las Vegas. 

</P>
<P>
	Solar Eclipse Sweeps Across Europe  
</P>
<P>
	NOYON, France (AP) -- Skies were blue and clear in Romania where  
today's total eclipse had its longest run: 2 minutes and 23 
seconds. Over Turkey, Iran and Iraq, the highly predictable yet 
overwhelming celestial event was unblemished. Everywhere in its 
swath, from the North Atlantic to Europe and Asia, the eclipse 
turned day to night, plunging temperatures within seconds. Millions 
saw the moon pass in front of the sun. The Eiffel Tower, its sensor 
cells fooled, blazed with its own lights. 

</P>
<P>
	Customs Changing Search Policy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Customs Service said today that it will  
obtain the approval of a federal magistrate when it wants to hold a 
passenger for more than four hours who is suspected of smuggling 
drugs. The change will take effect Oct. 1. The move comes as the 
agency is dogged by investigations and lawsuits alleging abusive 
searches. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Seeks India-Pakistan Peace  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States urgently called on India and  
Pakistan today to reinstitute a 1991 agreement aimed at avoiding 
clashes between military aircraft of the two countries. The 
agreement forbids aircraft from flying within 10 kilometers of each 
other's border without advance notification. The appeal came after 
the second aerial clash in two days between the South Asian rivals. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Troops Confront Albanians  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Peacekeepers from the United States,  
Russia and France confronted ethnic Albanian protesters today in 
three incidents. No injuries were reported in two of the 
confrontations, but two children were hurt accidentally by barbed 
wire erected on a bridge in the divided town of Kosovska Mitrovica. 
Ethnic Albanians accuse NATO troops from France and Russia of 
favoring Serbs. NATO officials deny that. 

</P>
<P>
	N.Y.'s Lazio Suspends Bid  
</P>
<P>
	BAY SHORE, N.Y. (AP) -- Rep. Rick Lazio, R.-N.Y., said today he  
will put his possible U.S. Senate campaign bid on hold while New 
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who Gov. George Pataki backs, 
mulls getting into the race. But Lazio said he was not withdrawing 
and did not rule out a primary run against the mayor. 

</P>
<P>
	Fed Finds Strong U.S. Economy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy is still growing strongly  
with labor shortages reported nationwide, the Federal Reserve said 
today in a new report that highlighted concerns that the economy 
may be growing too rapidly. That could lead to the Fed raising 
interest rates for the second time this year. The Fed's survey of 
economic conditions around the country found only scattered signs 
of mounting wage pressures and little evidence of rising inflation 
in general. But the Fed survey did note developments that could 
lead to increased inflationary pressures. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Is Up 130.75  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the hour, the Dow Jones industrials  
were at 10,785.90, up 130.75. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 
1,777-1,214. The Nasdaq was at 2,556.71, up 66.60. 

</P>
<P>
	Bills Lose Rookie Fullback  
</P>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Bills have lost rookie  
fullback Shawn Bryson for the season with a torn anterior crucuiate 
ligament. Bryson will undergo surgery and will be placed on injured 
reserve. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
  	   	
