<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Orders FBI Mole at ADM to Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A federal judge has ordered an FBI mole who  
helped uncover price fixing at the food processor Archer Daniels 
Midland Co. to pay back $1.17 million in salary and benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from his role helping the investigation, Mark Whitacre is  
serving a 9-year sentence for embezzling $9 million from ADM. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Michael McCuskey ruled on Aug. 5 that because Whitacre  
didn't faithfully perform his job with the Decatur-based company, 
ADM was entitled to the salary and benefits it paid him over a 
four-year period. The amount is part of a $6.3 million judgment. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitacre and two other senior ADM executives were sentenced last  
month in what persecutors called one of the largest antitrust 
conspiracies ever brought to court. 
</P>
<P>
	They were charged with conspiring with competitors in Japan and  
Korea to fix the $600 million world market in lysine, a 
soybean-based feed additive that promotes growth in hogs and 
poultry. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996 the company pleaded guilty to price-fixing charges.  
</P>
<P>
	Whitacre was sentenced to 30 months in the price-fixing case.  
</P>
<P>
	Because Whitacre is in prison and has multimillion-dollar  
judgments against him, the new ruling will likely have little 
effect on him. But Whitacre's attorney said it could have an 
adverse effect on corporate whistleblowers in the future. ``It 
opens the door,'' Bill T. Walker told the Chicago Tribune in 
comments published Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitacre, the former head of ADM's bioproducts division, set the  
FBI investigation in motion by telling top executives that Japanese 
rivals were trying to sabotage the company's lysine operation. 
</P>
<P>
	But ADM called in federal investigators, who found no trace of  
sabotage. Whitacre then told the government about a global 
price-fixing conspiracy and wore a wire as an undercover informant 
at ADM. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 23:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed: Economy Continues To Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The economy is growing strongly and widespread  
inflation pressures are not evident even though every region of the 
country is complaining about shortages of qualified workers, the 
Federal Reserve says. 
</P>
<P>
	In its latest survey of business conditions, the Fed was even  
able to find some encouraging developments in the battered 
manufacturing sector, which has been hard-hit by the global 
currency crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports from the Fed's 12 regional banks, known as the  
``beige book'' for the color of its cover, will be used by Fed 
policy makers when they meet Aug. 24 to review interest rate 
policies. 
</P>
<P>
	While financial markets took heart from the Fed's lack of alarm  
about inflation, private economists said the report did not change 
their conviction that the central bank will raise interest rates 
once again at that meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message from this report is that the economy is doing very  
well with inflation tame, but it is bumping up against capacity 
constraints,'' said Mark Zandi, economist at Regional Financial 
Associates in West Chester, Pa. ``Fed officials are laying the 
groundwork for another rate hike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Private economists noted the numerous warnings the beige book  
included about labor shortages, low inventory stockpiles for 
retailers and supply constraints. They said all of this supported 
their view that the Fed will raise interest rates by another 
quarter-point later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want to hike rates, there is sufficient justification  
to do it,'' said Cynthia Latta, economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI. 
``If they didn't hike rates that might alarm financial markets more 
because they would become worried that the Fed is letting down its 
guard against inflation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised its target for the federal funds rate, the  
interest that banks charge each other, for the first time in two 
years on June 30, nudging it up by a quarter point to 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations of another rate increase have increased since  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told Congress last month 
the central bank would move ``promptly and forcefully'' at the 
first signs of price pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed report, released Wednesday, said that the economy  
continued to show strength in late July and early August as 
consumer spending and housing construction remained strong. 
</P>
<P>
	``Widespread labor shortages persist in virtually every  
district, but there have been only scattered reports of 
acceleration in wages,'' the Fed survey said. ``There are some 
reports of accelerating prices -- largely related to home 
construction -- but there is no evidence of any broad-based pickup 
in consumer price inflation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even manufacturing exhibited signs of shaking off the effects of  
the Asian currency crisis, which has cut sharply into exports and 
opened many U.S. manufacturers to increased competition from lower 
priced imports, the Fed reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston, Cleveland, Dallas and San Francisco Fed districts  
noted strong demand for computer and telecommunications equipment 
while Cleveland and Chicago reported orders for heavy trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said that ``manufacturers in the West -- Dallas and  
San Francisco -- report some pickup in exports to Asia'' but as of 
yet the export rebound was not widespread. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed report said that housing construction was continuing at  
a vigorous pace in most districts although there were signs that a 
lack of available building materials and skilled workers was 
limiting growth in many areas. 
</P>
<P>
	While hot and dry weather was causing crop damage in the eastern  
part of the country, the Fed said that crops were generally in good 
shape in other areas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
