<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians See Second-Quarter Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Higher ticket prices and more broadcasting,  
advertising and promotion revenue helped drive earnings and revenue 
higher in the second quarter for the Cleveland Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cleveland Indians Baseball Co. Inc., the general partner of  
the partnership that owns the team, said Wednesday the club earned 
$2.9 million, or 46 cents a share, on revenue of $67.7 million in 
the quarter that ended June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	It isn't possible to make a direct comparison of the team's  
profits to the second quarter of 1998 because the club was 
privately owned through June 8, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians went public the following day by selling $60 million  
worth of stock at an initial price of $15 per share. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Indians said the ownership group led by Richard  
Jacobs earned $418,000 from April 1, 1998 through June 8, 1998. The 
publicly held company made $1.8 million during the rest of June. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue in the second quarter of 1998 totaled $59.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	``The improvements in the second quarter reflect our ability to  
grow revenues from local sources directly under our control,'' 
Jacobs said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs, who holds majority interest and control of the Indians,  
is trying to sell the team and shareholders will likely have to 
give up their stock if a deal is reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Indians stock closed at $18.87 Wednesday on the Nasdaq stock  
exchange, up 31 cents. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
