<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holdsclaw Likely To Be in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Chamique Holdsclaw, who has followed her brilliant college  
career with an outstanding rookie season as a pro, is likely to 
find herself playing in Sydney next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw is expected to be chosen for the U.S. national women's  
basketball team that will be announced Saturday. Those players are 
slated to become the Olympic team that will compete in the 2000 
Games in Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	Five players already have been chosen for the team by USA  
Basketball: Lisa Leslie, Nikki McCray, Ruthie Bolton-Holifield, 
Dawn Staley and Katie Smith. Jennifer Azzi also had been selected, 
but she withdrew in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to seven others will be named to the team, which will train  
and play a series of exhibition games over the next several months 
in preparation for the Olympics. Nell Fortner, the U.S. national 
coach and formerly the coach at Purdue, will coach the Olympic 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie, McCray, Bolton-Holifield and Staley were on the 1996  
Olympic team that won all 60 of its exhibition and Olympic games en 
route to the gold medal. All three are now playing in the WNBA. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post, quoting what it identified as a  
knowledgeable source, said in Wednesday's edition that Holdsclaw 
had been picked for the U.S. team. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of USA Basketball refused to comment on the Post  
report. But Holdsclaw long has been considered an Olympic team 
prospect. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw, one of the most dynamic players ever in the women's  
game, is in her first season with the WNBA's Washington Mystics 
after leading Tennessee to three NCAA championships. She was twice 
the national player of the year and was a first-team All-America 
selection three times. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Holdsclaw was the youngest member of the U.S. team  
that won the world championships and was its fourth-leading scorer. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Mystics, Holdsclaw is the league's No. 5 scorer with an  
18.2 average and has a high of 24 points. She's also averaging 
eight rebounds and 2.5 assists and was voted a starter for the East 
team in the all-star game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
