<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Helps Airlines With E-Tickets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A collaboration between IBM and the airline  
industry could make ticketless air travel much more convenient for 
passengers and air carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	At some domestic airlines, up to half of all passengers now use  
electronic tickets. Ticketless travel saves the airlines money they 
would otherwise spend handling paper tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike paper tickets, airlines cannot honor each other's  
electronic tickets unless they establish costly links between their 
e-ticket systems. 
</P>
<P>
	International Business Machines Corp. and the International Air  
Transport Association announced today that they are developing a 
computer system that would link all airlines that offer ticketless 
travel beginning next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at IBM Corp. and travel experts said the system could  
help passengers who must fly more than one carrier -- for example, 
to reach smaller cities served only by commuter airlines or to link 
with foreign carriers on international trips. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to have multiple carriers on your itinerary, you  
most likely won't be able to do that with e-ticketing'' with the 
current technology, Patti Jones, an air transport executive with 
IBM said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the system also would help ticketless passengers who  
must change airlines because of flight cancelations. Currently, 
most have to get a printed ticket from their carrier to present to 
the second airline. 
</P>
<P>
	No airlines have yet signed up for the IBM system, but the air  
transport group believes it will be an easy sell, because it will 
be much cheaper for airlines than establishing individual links 
with each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think the economics of the solution are quite powerful.  
We're comfortable we'll get a large critical mass of carriers or we 
wouldn't be building it,'' said Louis Daigle, a marketing director 
for the air transport association. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM and air transport officials declined to discuss how much it  
would cost to develop and run the system or how much they would 
charge airlines for the service. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
