<HEADLINE> Yanks' Grimsley Won't Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- New York Yankees pitcher Jason Grimsley  
dropped his appeal of a three-game suspension stemming from a brawl 
last week at Seattle and began serving the penalty Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Grimsley was suspended for throwing at and then hitting Edgar  
Martinez of the Mariners on consecutive pitches after Alex 
Rodriguez had homered. One inning later, Seattle's Frankie 
Rodriguez hit Chuck Knoblauch with a pitch, touching off a brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	Grimsley had appealed his suspension on Tuesday, and was  
available in the bullpen as the Yankees played the Oakland 
Athletics that day. He was not used. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees activated reliever Jeff Nelson off the disabled list  
Wednesday before their game against the A's and have an off-day 
Thursday, making Grimsley expendable. 
