<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teenage Star To Join Galaxy in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- DaMarcus Beasley, a 17-year-old  
midfielder from Fort Wayne, Ind., was assigned to the Los Angeles 
Galaxy by Major League Soccer on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Beasley will not report to the team until he graduates  
from high school next June. 
</P>
<P>
	Beasley signed a contract with the league March 16 under its  
Project-40 youth development plan, but hadn't been assigned to a 
team. He played for the United States' 17-and-under and 
23-and-under national teams, helping the latter to a bronze medal 
in the Pan American Games last month. 
</P>
<P>
	He also played two matches with the U.S. Pro-40 Select team,  
comprised of other Project 40 signees and MLS reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	The youngest player to sign an MLS contract, Beasley will remain  
in the U-17 Residency Program, part of the under-17 national team's 
preparation for November's FIFA World Youth Championship in New 
Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	He will also attend classes at the Bradenton Academy High  
School. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
