<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Wants 2008 Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Having suffered defections and a drug scandal,  
Cuban sports officials called the Pan Am Games in Canada ``the 
worst in history'' and vowed Wednesday to restore their pride by 
aiming to host the 2008 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The president of the Cuban Olympic Committee, Jose Ramon  
Fernandez, said in a televised discussion that Cuba soon would 
begin work on the bidding process. 
</P>
<P>
	He praised Cuba's sports culture and its record of hosting  
events, such as the 1991 Pan Am Games. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 2 1/2-hour conversation about the Pan Am Games at Winnipeg,  
Manitoba, sports officials denounced ``maneuvers'' they said hurt 
Cuban athletes, such as unfair judging, schedule changes, lack of 
security and harassment by athletic scouts who encouraged 
defections. 
</P>
<P>
	During the July 23-Aug. 8 events, 13 Cubans defected, including  
11 athletes, said Humberto Rodriguez, president of the Cuban Sports 
Institute. Reports during the Pan Am Games indicated that nine 
members of the Cuban delegation defected. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials condemned a Winnipeg newspaper's contest which  
challenged readers to guess the number of Cubans who would defect, 
with the winner to receive a vacation trip to the communist island. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans reiterated their support for high jumper Javier  
Sotomayor, who was stripped of his gold medal after testing 
positive for cocaine, and said the nation planned to build its own 
top-of-the-line, drug-testing facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Alberto Juantorena, vice president of the Cuban Sports  
Institute, called the Winnipeg events ``the worst games in 
history.'' The panel complained of everything from official 
delegates having to buy tickets to a lack of sufficient bathrooms 
and meager food supplies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
