<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Urges Money To Stop Recidivism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Admitting the justice system is failing at  
stopping repeat offenders, Attorney General Janet Reno on Tuesday 
suggested creating new ``re-entry courts'' to oversee the release 
of inmates and their return to society. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless we bring them back to our communities with a chance of  
success the criminal justice system is going to fail again,'' Reno 
told the American Bar Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno suggested the re-entry courts could be modeled on the  
special local drug courts that were established during her tenure 
as a Miami prosecutor -- a concept that has spread to several other 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Those courts have focused on providing rehabilitative programs  
to treat defendants and giving judges the authority to establish 
criteria and incentives for avoiding prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``You say somebody else can do that,'' Reno told the ABA.  
``Ladies and gentlemen, there is something magic about a judge.... 
That black robe can make a difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While some people may question the cost of such programs, Reno  
pointed to the costs that repeat criminals generate to both their 
victims and to taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do we afford what we have now, with people recycling  
through the system again and again and again?'' she asked. ``It 
makes no sense to send somebody to prison for an armed robbery and 
have them come out in four years ... without the problem being 
addressed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reno has long advocated greater efforts at rehabilitation to  
prevent repeat offenders. If a former inmate has no job and no high 
school diploma, she told the assembled lawyers, ``Guess what? 
They're going to be doing it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``No wonder people don't have confidence in the system,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeremy Travis, director of the Justice Department's research  
group, said the population in state prisons now totals 1.2 million, 
four times what it was in 1980. And with more prisoners being 
released, parole violations also are on the rise, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the growth now in state prisons is not because of  
people committing new crimes, but parolees being returned to 
prison,'' Travis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Re-entry courts could better manage parolees and reduce the  
criminal behavior that would send them back behind bars, he 
suggested. Judges would see parolees much more frequently and have 
more hands-on control, using coercion and support to keep them out 
of trouble, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea draws inspiration from ``problem-solving courts'' such  
as those for family violence and drug offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's much more interactive between judge and offender,''  
Travis said, adding that judges can hold people accountable in ways 
that a parole officer with a caseload of 500 people cannot. 
</P>
<P>
	``People react differently if they have to explain their  
behavior to a judge in a courtroom than they would explaining their 
behavior over the phone to a parole officer,'' Travis said. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, the Justice Department plans to ask the states for  
suggestions on how to best implement re-entry courts. Many states 
are interested in the program and Nevada will begin having judges 
oversee the release of prisoners in October, Travis said. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Justice Department official, speaking on the condition  
of anonymity, said Reno also has ``expressed strong interest'' in 
also exploring the use of re-entry courts on the federal level. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- David Ho in Washington contributed to this  
story. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
