<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Shooting Suspect Turns Himself In  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The suspect in the shooting at a suburban  
Jewish community center has reportedly turned himself in to 
authorities in Las Vegas. Buford Oneal Furrow allegedly strode into 
the community center's lobby yesterday and opened fire with a 
semiautomatic gun resembling an Uzi, peppering the building with 
some 70 shots. Five people were injured, including three children. 
The gunman gave the slip to police who arrived a the center within 
four minutes of the shootings. He allegedly carjacked a Toyota at 
gunpoint. Police aren't discussing a motive, but Furrow reportedly 
had ties to hate groups. 

</P>
<P>
	Death Upheld for N.J. Girl's Killer  
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court affirmed today the  
murder conviction of Jesse Timmendequas and his death sentence for 
the 1994 rape and slaying of 7-year-old Megan Kanka. The court 
rejected arguments by defense attorneys that Timmendequas' 1997 
trial was tainted by local publicity since it was only a few miles 
from the murder scene. The murder prompted a state and national 
movement to enact ``Megan's Laws'' to keep track of convicted sex 
offenders after their release from prison and to provide community 
notifications on the whereabouts of the most dangerous ones. 

</P>
<P>
	Court: UPS Avoided Taxes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A court has ruled that the United Parcel  
Service owes millions of dollars in back federal taxes that the 
package carrier avoided by creating a subsidiary located in 
Bermuda. The court said that Atlanta-based UPS is liable for taxes, 
penalties and interest for the income of Overseas Partners, a 
subsidiary created to provide ``excess value'' insurance for 
certain packages costing several times the normal market value. The 
ruling directly covers penalties and interest on $67 million in 
taxes from 1983 and 1984, a total estimated at $300 million. UPS 
said it ``believes there are grounds for appeal.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Airline Bomb-Screening Lapses Cited  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A published report says bomb detection machines  
installed at the nation's major airports are being underutilized by 
many airlines. The CTX 5000 machines are intended to scan the 
baggage of people identified as high security risks by a 
passenger-screening process. It can process 225 bags an hour, but a 
government audit found some airlines run as few as four bags an 
hour through the $1 million machines, the Chicago Tribune reported 
in today's editions. The FAA's wants airlines to run 2 percent to 
20 percent of all checked baggage, but nationally, the CTX 5000s 
now screen less than 1 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Launches Caucasus Offensive  
</P>
<P>
	ANSALTA, Russia (AP) -- Russia launched a new offensive today  
against Islamic rebels who are fighting for a Muslim-controlled 
state in the Caucasus mountains. The rebels invaded the southern 
Russian republic of Dagestan on Saturday, seizing several villages 
and clashing with Russian troops. Russia claimed it would need only 
a few days to ``eliminate the rebels.'' The Russian government says 
the rebels are members of the Wahhabi sect of Muslims. The sect 
supports independence for Russia's mostly Muslim regions in the 
Caucasus. 

</P>
<P>
	Alcoa Offers To Buy Rival Reynolds  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Alcoa, the world's largest aluminum company,  
offered today to buy No. 3 Reynolds Metal for $5.6 billion in cash 
and stock. The combined companies would have roughly $21 billion in 
revenue. Alcoa disclosed its offer the same day three international 
aluminum companies agreed to a merger that would create an aluminum 
concern with $25 billion in sales. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 38  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 38.62 to 10,693.77. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,474-1,294. The Nasdaq was up 23.46 to 
2,513.57. 

</P>
<P>
	Underwood Won't Play With Vikings  
</P>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- Dimitrius Underwood's short, strange stay  
with the Vikings ended today when he told Minnesota coach Dennis 
Green he ``has no desire to play football.'' Underwood, the team's 
first-round pick, left training camp last week because he was 
unsure whether he wanted to play in the NFL or devote his life to 
the ministry. He returned to camp after speaking with former NFL 
star Reggie White, who is now a minister, but told the team last 
night his heart wasn't into playing. The Vikings could either 
release or suspend him, but he won't get any of his $5.3 million 
contract. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
