<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anderson, Falcons Agree to Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- All-Pro running back Jamal Anderson, who  
missed the first two weeks of training camp because of a contract 
dispute, agreed to a new deal with the Atlanta Falcons after nearly 
four hours of talks Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and his agent, Jim Sims, reached the agreement after a  
meeting at a Greenville hotel with Falcons coach Dan Reeves and 
general manager Harold Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's agreed on and done,'' Reeves said after Anderson arrived  
at the Furman University campus for the first time at 5:30 p.m. 
EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who set a franchise record with 1,846 yards rushing  
last season as the Falcons advanced to the Super Bowl, was expected 
to join the team for practice Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the contract were not immediately available. The two  
sides had basically agreed on a five-year contract worth $28 
million to $30 million but stumbled over the signing bonus, 
guaranteed money and the structure of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	A news conference was scheduled for 6:45 p.m.  
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and Sims arrived in a stretch limousine for their first  
face-to-face meeting with the Falcons since training camp began 
July 29. Reeves and Richardson pulled up to the hotel shortly 
afterwards in a green Buick. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves, who has final say in contract matters, sat in on the  
talks for over an hour before leaving the hotel. ``We've had a good 
meeting, but I've got to go to practice,'' the coach said. ``I'm 
late.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Falcons practiced at nearby Furman, Richardson  
remained behind to continue the talks with Anderson and Sims. 
Finally, shortly after 5 p.m., a weary-looking Anderson emerged 
from the meeting room. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're working toward getting things done,'' he said.  
``Hopefully, we'll have a definitive result tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson and Sims crawled back into their limo and followed  
Richardson's car to the Furman campus through rush-hour traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson emerged from the vehicle at the player dormitories and  
pumped his arms in the air just as three of his offensive linemen -- 
Ephraim Salaam, Calvin Collins and Bob Whitfield -- pulled into the 
parking lot on a golf cart. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, big money!'' Collins yelled.  
</P>
<P>
	Anderson embraced all three before jumping on the golf cart and  
riding away with them to his new room. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Wednesday, Anderson said he was confident a contract  
could be worked out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a deal could be done today,'' he said in an interview  
with WHTA-FM in Atlanta. ``I'm trying to remain here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By this afternoon, he said, ``me and Dan will be dancing and  
smiling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As it turned out, he was right. Now, the Falcons can focus their  
energies on preparing for the Sept. 12 season opener against 
Minnesota, the team they shocked in the NFC championship game to 
reach the first Super Bowl in Atlanta's 33-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts not being in training camp,'' Anderson said after  
agreeing to a new contract. ``But I have plenty of time to get 
ready before the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons play their first exhibition game Friday night  
against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, set to make $2.6 million in the final year of his  
current contract, refused to report to training camp without a new 
deal. He has accumulated at least $70,000 in fines. 
</P>
<P>
	Sims had raised the possibility of asking for a trade if  
Wednesday's talks didn't produce an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we don't get it done, I think from that point on we'll  
really have to push the trade option,'' Sims said Tuesday night. 
``He's not retiring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reeves flatly rejected the idea of trading Anderson to another  
team, and the two sides finally worked out their differences. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
