<HEADLINE> Jesdanun Named AP's Internet Writer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Anick Jesdanun, Pennsylvania regional reporter  
in Washington for The Associated Press, has been named to the 
position of national writer in New York reporting on news about the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was made Wednesday by Mike Silverman, deputy  
managing editor for national news. 
</P>
<P>
	Working with writers across the United States and abroad,  
Jesdanun will focus on social, technical and commercial development 
of the Internet and related communication channels. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesdanun, 30, joined the AP in 1991 in Philadelphia. After a  
year covering state government in Harrisburg, Pa., he moved to 
Washington in 1994 to write about political, congressional and 
business matters that affect Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Pittsburgh and raised in Edison, N.J., Jesdanun  
graduated from Swarthmore College near Philadelphia. 
  	   	
</P>
