<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't To Pay for Indian Suit Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taxpayers will have to pay more than $624,000  
because the Interior Department failed to produce documents 
promptly in a lawsuit concerning the troubled Indian trust fund, a 
judge has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth said the payment is to cover  
``all expenses and reasonable attorney fees'' incurred by Indian 
plaintiffs who were blocked for two years from getting government 
records detailing trust fund mismanagement. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamberth said he was dismayed that taxpayers ``will be forced to  
pay for the misconduct of their government's officials and 
attorneys.'' If he could, he would have made individual attorneys 
liable, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think this is a reasonable decision,'' said Interior  
Department spokesman Tim Ahearn. The government previously had 
offered to pay $476,700. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's action Tuesday does not address the merits of the  
class-action lawsuit brought by the Indians. The suit, which 
Lamberth could decide within weeks, asks that the court take over 
the trouble-plagued $550 million trust fund, overhaul its 
error-filled accounting system and make restitution to Indians who 
lost money. 
</P>
<P>
	The Interior Department admits it cannot accurately document the  
$550 million fund that belongs to individual Indians from land 
holdings, royalty payments and other assets dating back 
generations. Officials have testified that they are working to fix 
the accounting system. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate $2.5 million in the fund belongs to Indian tribes but  
is not part of the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The award of legal fees stems from a two-year period in which  
lawyers for the Indians were blocked repeatedly from obtaining 
documents on five accounts belonging to the leading plaintiffs in 
the case. The legal fees and other expenses, covering work from 
November 1996 to January of this year, total $624,643.50 to be 
awarded to seven attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is gratifying that the judge is holding the government  
accountable,'' said Jim McCarthy, spokesman for plaintiff group. 
``The Department of Interior's tactics of delay and denial and 
cover-up against American Indians will no longer be tolerated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Interior Department was ordered in late 1996 to turn over  
statements, checks and other documents concerning trust-fund 
accounts held by five Indians who are lead plaintiffs in the 
lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers and officials ``almost immediately disobeyed  
(the order) and successfully covered up their disobedience through 
semantics and strained, unilateral, self-serving interpretations of 
their own duties,'' wrote Lamberth in assessing the legal fees, 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Lamberth found Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and  
then-Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin in contempt because they 
failed to produce documents sought by the Indians in connection 
with the suit. He accused Interior officials of foot-dragging and 
making ``outright false statements'' to keep from turning over the 
records. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
