<HEADLINE> Killer Had Book on Serial Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- The man charged in the decapitation  
slaying of a Yosemite National park naturalist was carrying a novel 
about a serial killer when he was first questioned, according to 
court records. 
</P>
<P>
	Hotel handyman Cary Stayner, who reportedly told FBI  
investigators he killed the naturalist and three female tourists, 
has pleaded innocent in the killing of naturalist Joie Ruth 
Armstrong. No charges have been filed in the case of Carole Sund, 
her daughter Juli and family friend Silvina Pelosso. 
</P>
<P>
	Stayner was carrying a paperback copy of ``Black Lightning'' in  
his backpack when he was questioned on July 22, the day after 
Armstrong's body was found, according to the court records. He was 
arrested two days later, at a nudist camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1995 best seller by John Saul describes a series of killings  
in Seattle, with images of women being slashed with knives and 
power saws. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents also searched Stayner's vehicle and his room at the Cedar  
Lodge where he lived and worked, but their findings have not been 
made public. 
  	   	
</P>
