<DOCNO> APW19990811.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 10:28:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nostalgia Networks: When Old Is New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- One recent afternoon in Manhattan, the  
boundaries fell -- both between television networks and TV-viewing 
generations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Brady Bunch'' theme played in the background. The jalopy  
from ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' sat just outside. WKRP's Johnny 
Fever found himself in an animated discussion with Mayberry's own 
Barney Fife. ``Maude'' met ``Three's Company'' -- Edith Bunker's 
cousin chatting quietly with Jack Tripper. 
</P>
<P>
	What was this all about? Just an industry ``upfront'' -- one of  
those fetes where networks show off new fall shows for advertisers. 
But this was for Nickelodeon's Nick at Nite and TV Land, and all 
that was new was actually old -- even the stars on hand to greet 
clients. 
</P>
<P>
	That old quote about the past being another country -- ``they do  
things differently there'' -- is anathema for this group of the 
nostalgia faithful. To the folks at Nick at Nite and TV Land, the 
past isn't another country. It's home. 
</P>
<P>
	But the innocent 1970s sexuality of ``Three's Company,'' the  
just-folks charm of ``The Andy Griffith Show'' and the good-natured 
grousing of ``Maude'' and ``The Jeffersons'' (all of which have 
surfaced again like video Brigadoons) have something deeper to say 
-- about the comfort that baby boomers and, now, Gen-Xers, find in 
the programming of their childhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nick at Nite programming block (``preserving our television  
heritage'') and its younger sibling, the TV Land nostalgia channel, 
are shrewdly tooled and packaged to evoke memories of living-room 
tube watching. 
</P>
<P>
	These shows have already been successful with many of these same  
viewers; surely they will be again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every single show is a hit,'' the network's president, Herb  
Scannell, is able to boast to advertisers. And TV Land general 
manager Larry Jones talks of ``the safe, familiar haven that our 
shows provide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Here's the odd thing, though: In an ironic, cynical age, this  
stuff isn't presented as irony or cynicism. Sure, there's a 
wink-nudge aspect to it, but it's sincere. 
</P>
<P>
	The network's execs clearly love the stuff (they had the time of  
their lives vamping around with WKRP's Loni Anderson and Howard 
Hesseman) and they know we love it, too. If some of it is dated and 
a bit like a 35-year-old heading straight for the baby-food aisle, 
so what? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my childhood,'' said Alya Grinshpun of Ogilvy and Mather,  
one of many guests at the recent upfront who were under 35. Her 
colleague, Adrienne DeSanto, agreed: ``It's something you can rely 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Advertisers are in tune with such sentiment: StarKist is  
resurrecting Charlie the Tuna after a decade's absence; Charmin's 
Mr. Whipple has returned for a few more squeezes; and the Jolly 
Green Giant is on his way back to the air. 
</P>
<P>
	At Nick at Nite and TV Land, they offer Andy Griffith and  
``Three's Company'' marathons. They air old commercials and call 
'em ``Retromercials.'' And a TV Land Saturday morning lineup called 
``Retrovision'' takes aim straight at the Count Chocula set. It's 
resurrecting such 1970s fare as ``H.R. Pufnstuff,'' the animated 
``Star Trek'' and a really weird cartoon version of ``Happy Days'' 
that sends Richie, Malph and the Fonz into a time machine and back 
to a stereotype-saturated ancient Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	It's all available now -- all eras, all the time, 23,000 hours'  
worth in Nickelodeon's vaults alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's so much product, so much preservation, that things  
exist simultaneously in time and space like never before,'' says 
actor John Ritter, Jack Tripper of ``Three's Company.'' He didn't 
expect it to survive two seasons, much less two decades. That seems 
to be the consensus. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never dreamed how long this would last,'' says Don Knotts,  
a 1960s staple as jumpy Deputy Barney Fife in ``The Andy Griffith 
Show'' and jumpier landlord Mr. Furley in ``Three's Company'' 
(1977-1984). 
</P>
<P>
	It's television as sense memory -- what Robert Thompson, director  
of the Center for the Study of Popular Television at Syracuse 
University, calls ``the aesthetic of the anesthetic.'' This is our 
common ground, even if it's more Samantha and Darrin than Socrates 
and Da Vinci. 
</P>
<P>
	But what happens down the road? Already, as Gen-Xers join  
boomers on demographic center stage, shows from the 1970s and early 
1980s are joining those from the 1950s and 1960s as nostalgia 
staples. 
</P>
<P>
	If the latest generation of TV watchers comes of age with ``I  
Love Lucy'' and ``Petticoat Junction'' reruns, is there enough 
stuff being created in the post-''Webster'' era to fill TV Land's 
2015 fall schedule? Or could the incessant tumbling into 
Pleasantville someday backfire on the nostalgia network? 
</P>
<P>
	Probably not. We'll always have ``Seinfeld'' and ``Frasier'' and  
``Friends,'' not to mention ``The Fresh Prince of Bel Air'' and 
``Head of the Class.'' And if things get really lean, there's 
always ``Growing Pains'' and ``Saved by the Bell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the quality, whatever the era that belches it forth,  
we'll always have our yesterdays. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`SNOOPS' IS SHOOTING: Production has begun in Los Angeles on  
``Snoops,'' a new series from David E. Kelley, the prolific creator 
of ``The Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Chicago Hope,'' ABC has 
announced. The program, which ABC will air Sundays, takes an 
amusing look at a sexy ensemble of unconventional L.A. private 
eyes. Glenn Hall (Gina Gershon), the city's most savvy and 
seductive private eye, doesn't let a little thing like the Bill of 
Rights bog her down. Glenn's newest recruit is Dana Plant (Paula 
Marshall), a by-the-book police detective looking to escape the 
Santa Monica Police Department and a failed love affair with her 
boss. ``Snoops'' premieres Sept. 26. Kelley is executive producer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 12:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 126.96 in Late Trading / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks extended their gains today as a battered  
market revived, due in part to a strong earnings report from 
networking company Cisco Systems and calming words from the Federal 
Reserve on the growth of the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 126.96 points at 10,782.11. The gains followed through on a 
rebound that began Tuesday afternoon, when the Dow and other 
indicators struggled back from steep losses to end modestly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher today. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 17.71 at 1,299.14, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was up 60.84 at 2,550.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the market was ripe for a minor rally following a  
slump that has left every major market index well below the lofty 
records reached in mid-July. But most Wall Street players believe 
the market will have trouble sustaining gains at least until Aug. 
24, when Fed policy-makers hold their next meeting to set interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a nervous market and will continue to be for a  
while,'' said Barry Berman, head trader for Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. 
in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed offered some reassurance this afternoon, saying its  
latest economic survey turned up little evidence of rising 
inflation in general. But the Fed survey, dubbed the ``beige 
book,'' did note developments that could lead to increased 
inflationary pressures, most notably widespread labor shortages and 
scattered reports of higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed, which raised rates slightly on June 30, has clearly  
signaled its willingness to raise short-term interest rates for a 
second time this year, hoping to prevent inflation from creeping 
into the robust U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of economic news for people to look at in  
advance of the next meeting,'' Berman said. ``Under different 
circumstances, the beige book might not attract a lot of attention, 
but investors are looking for guidance on what exactly the Fed 
plans to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Growing fears of a third rate hike this fall have hurt stocks  
and bonds alike. Plummeting bond prices have pushed up the yield on 
the 30-year Treasury bond closer to 6.25 percent, leaving long-term 
borrowing costs at the highest level in nearly two years. 
</P>
<P>
	For some investors, rising bond yields have presented an  
attractive alternative to returns on volatile stocks. Other stock 
investors are unsettled that an uptrend in interest rates will cut 
into corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco helped spark buying today, rising 3 5/8 to 62 3/8. Late Tuesday,  
the company reported fourth-quarter earnings that beat analysts' 
estimates, rounding out a fiscal year in which revenues grew 43 
percent and operating profits improved 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A wave of deals in the aluminum industry also moved the market.  
Early today, Alusuisse-Lonza (Algroup) of Switzerland, Pechiney of 
France and Alcan Aluminium of Canada said they would merge, passing 
U.S.-based Alcoa as the world leader in aluminum. 
</P>
<P>
	But Alcoa had a surprise of its own, going public with an offer  
to buy No. 3 Reynolds Metal Co. for $5.6 billion in cash and stock. 
Reynolds soared 9 13/16 to 65 11/16, or more than the $65-a-share 
offer, and Alcoa, a Dow component, rose 2 1/2 to 68 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Alcan gained 2 7/16 to 36 1/16 and Pechiney rose 2 1/8  
to 30 3/8. Algroup shares slipped on the Zurich stock exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The market for new stocks was mixed today. Shares of video  
rental chain Blockbuster were priced at 15 and were unchanged in 
late afternoon trading. 
</P>
<P>
	But Red Hat, a seller of Linux software, saw its shares soar  
from an offering price of 14 to 53 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 616.64 million 
shares, slightly behind Tuesday's late afternoon pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 5.91 at 609.28, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 4.20 at 774.97. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 3.30 to 426.12.  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
