<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Richardson Backs Defense Bill Veto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration and Congress are  
moving toward a showdown over reorganizing the Energy Department, 
with a widely popular defense bill a possible casualty. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson told reporters Wednesday he  
probably will recommend that President Clinton veto the $289 
billion defense authorization bill because he said it would put the 
nuclear weapons programs under a powerful new agency over which he 
would have modest control. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson hedged somewhat on the veto issue, knowing that the  
White House has yet to take a final position. The defense bill has 
widespread political support and among other things would give a 
hefty pay boost to the military and provide new spending for 
military readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	A veto could open the administration to sharp criticism from  
Republicans who have argued the Pentagon is spread too thin and 
that a pay increase for the military is long overdue. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Department reorganization is all but certain as a fallout  
over months of controversy about charges of lax security and 
Chinese espionage at the department's nuclear weapons labs -- much 
of the spying going back 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But Richardson said the proposal approved as part of the defense  
bill by House and Senate conferees just before the summer recess 
``clearly goes too far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I would most likely recommend to the president that he veto  
the bill,'' said Richardson. Congress is expected to send the bill 
to the president shortly after Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	The provision as crafted in negotiations between the House and  
Senate would create a new nuclear weapons agency within the 
department that would largely set its on budget, make its own 
personnel decisions and be insulated from most of the rest of the 
department. Richardson argues it would be largely beyond the reach 
of the energy secretary as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's supporters argue that department meddling in  
nuclear weapons programs is what caused the security problems that 
led to China obtaining nuclear secrets from the weapons labs, 
including information about one of the country's most sophisticated 
warheads. 
</P>
<P>
	``The changes in this bill are long overdue,'' said Rep. Mac  
Thornberry, R-Texas, who crafted much of the weapons agency 
language. ``Over the last 10 years alone there have been nearly 20 
reports critical of the department's management of the nuclear 
weapons complex.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said he accepts ``the concept'' of a semi-autonomous  
nuclear weapons agency and would go along with a version approved 
by the Senate. But he said the structure in the defense legislation 
``undermines the secretary's authority'' and ``blurs the lines of 
responsibility'' in areas of security, counter-intelligence and 
health, safety and environmental protection. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department reorganization would be the most  
wide-reaching overhaul of the department since it was create in the 
1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	On other subjects during a hour-long meeting with reporters,  
Richardson said: 
</P>
<P>
	--He will announce within days disciplinary action against a  
number of individuals stemming from the mishandling of the 
espionage investigation at the Los Alamos weapons laboratory. He 
has said in the past some individuals will be fired, but was less 
clear on that today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now we're looking at very serious disciplinary action,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	--He is determined to pursue a broad investigation and make as  
much information public as possible about the exposure of workers 
to highly dangerous plutonium at a government uranium reprocessing 
plant in Paducah, Ky., and make certain restitution is made to 
those who suffered illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson also said he wants to investigate whether the  
civilian contractors operating the facility during the Cold War 
years misled workers and the government as to health risks. 
</P>
<P>
	--He has met resistance ``from all sides'' on his plans to  
require polygraph tests on thousands of nuclear weapons laboratory 
workers, but is determined to pursue ``narrowly focused'' tests. 
``I don't think anybody should be afraid of that,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
