<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Pipeline Deal Falls Apart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A last-minute glitch reportedly squashed a deal  
between a consortium of energy companies led by Chevron to build a 
natural gas pipeline in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron's five partners, including Royal Dutch/Shell, refused to  
sign onto the joint venture after Nigeria suddenly demanded to be 
named project leader in place of Chevron, Dow Jones News Service 
reported late Wednesday, citing a person familiar with the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron said in a statement it signed a political pact with  
Nigeria, Ghana, Benin and Togo, giving the consortium the right to 
develop the pipeline, which could start supplying the region with 
energy in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear Wednesday where that left the project.  
</P>
<P>
	Chevron spokeswoman Jan Golon told Dow Jones the company was  
optimistic the joint-venture problems will be resolved in the next 
several days. Golon did not return a call from The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The pipeline would initially carry 120 million cubic feet of  
natural gas a day from Nigeria for sale into the other nations. 
Construction, which started six years ago, is expected to cost $400 
million, Chevron said. 
</P>
<P>
	The project will supplement the unreliable hydropower in the  
three consuming countries, starting in mid 2002. The initial 
customers will be three power plants in Ghana. 
</P>
<P>
	It also will help Nigeria reach its target of eliminating gas  
flaring by 2003. At present almost 70 percent of natural gas in 
Nigeria is flared -- or burned off -- as a byproduct of oil 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigeria has the 10th-largest gas reserves in the world,  
estimated at 124 trillion cubic feet in 1996, or 2.6 percent of 
estimated world reserves. Nigeria's gas reserves are three times 
its crude oil reserves, which make up 65 percent of the country's 
revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Chevron and Shell's Nigerian unit, the consortium  
included national energy companies of the four nations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
