<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Adrian Grenier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``The Adventures of Sebastian Cole'' is taking  
its star, Adrian Grenier, on an adventure of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	The journey began with the hectic 24-day shooting schedule in  
upstate New York. The town was so small -- and so unaccustomed to 
moviemaking -- that the local fire department showed up every time 
the filmmakers used a fog machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Grenier has the title role, a restless teen-ager blessed and  
cursed by his nontraditional family. The film is set in 1983, and 
his character has hit the doldrums of high school. He restlessly 
bides his time reading the ``wrong'' books and underachieving. 
</P>
<P>
	Sebastian wants to get out and find adventure. That's when fate  
steps in. His family is thrown into a tailspin when his stepfather 
Hank (Clark Gregg) announces that he is going to become a woman. 
Sebastian ends up living with Hank, who changes his name to 
Henrietta. 
</P>
<P>
	Grenier said he shares many thoughts and traits with Sebastian,  
particularly the rebellious streak, although he is beginning to 
outgrow it. ``I have to force myself to be bad. It doesn't come as 
naturally as it used to. But I can't forget that side of me, I 
think it's healthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After dropping out of college and spending a few years  
concentrating only on ``being a ragamuffin,'' Grenier, 23, said he 
is now taking his career seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	But not too seriously.  
</P>
<P>
	He shares an apartment in Williamsburg, Brooklyn, with a high  
school friend, and spent a recent summer evening playing a 50-cent 
kiddie xylophone at the beach on Fire Island. He arrived unshaven 
at a Manhattan hotel for a day of press interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	Moving out of his mother's home and into his own apartment  
helped him discover his domestic side, Grenier said. ``I like to 
read and make dinner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``The place isn't very clean right now, but sometimes  
we get fanatical about cleaning it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Drive Me Crazy,'' starring Grenier and Melissa Joan Hart, is  
scheduled for release in October. 
</P>
<P>
	And while he is trying to build a name for himself in the movie  
industry, Grenier said he won't jump at just any role. 
</P>
<P>
	``After doing `The Adventures of Sebastian Cole,' I know there  
are parts for me to do that are very enjoyable and movies that are 
enjoyable to work on. I needed this job and they gave it to me, but 
because of it, I am more selective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	1. How did you know that acting is the career for you?  
</P>
<P>
	Grenier: Well, I know I don't want to be a Wall Street broker. I  
know I don't want to be a lot of things, but I never dismissed 
acting, so I guess that's how I got into it. 
</P>
<P>
	2. What makes you different from other young actors still  
looking for their big break? 
</P>
<P>
	Grenier: I was lucky. It was fated for me to do this and I don't  
feel guilty about it. Just because I'm getting this recognition 
doesn't mean someone else can't. 
</P>
<P>
	3. You've had an agent since you were a teen-ager. How active  
are you in shaping your career? 
</P>
<P>
	Grenier: I've realized as you get further into the business side  
of acting that you have to seek out scripts and play an active part 
in what you do. You have to start to take control of what happens 
to you. If you lose control, you'll look back and you won't be in a 
good place. 
</P>
<P>
	4. In both ``Sebastian Cole'' and ``Drive Me Crazy,'' you play a  
high school student. Do you want to graduate to more adult parts? 
</P>
<P>
	Grenier: I'll go for a 20-year-old, not too mature. I'll age  
slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	5. Do you see yourself trading the city for a small-town life  
like Sebastian Cole had? 
</P>
<P>
	Grenier: I think it's inbred in me somewhere. I just recently  
started to get to know my father again. He's from Ohio, so I went 
out to Ohio and I liked it. There's this comfortableness there. I 
can see how people not from there want to get in and be a part of 
it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
