<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tuesday, Aug. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Shooting Suspect Turns Himself In  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- The suspect in a shooting spree at a Jewish  
community center in suburban Los Angeles turned himself in to the 
FBI here, and authorities say he confessed to the attack. A federal 
prosecutor in Los Angeles says Buford O'Neal Furrow will also be 
charged in the fatal shooting of a postal worker who was shot 
yesterday near the scene of the attack at the community center. 
Furrow, 37, told authorities ``he wanted this to be a wake-up call 
to America to kill Jews.'' Furrow allegedly opened fire yesterday 
at the center with a semiautomatic gun resembling an Uzi, peppering 
the building with some 70 shots. Five people were injured, 
including three children. 

</P>
<P>
	Fed Finds Strong U.S. Economy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy is still growing strongly  
with labor shortages reported nationwide, the Federal Reserve said 
today in a new report that highlighted concerns that the economy 
may be growing too rapidly. That could lead to the Fed raising 
interest rates for the second time this year. The Fed's survey of 
economic conditions around the country found only scattered signs 
of mounting wage pressures and little evidence of rising inflation 
in general. But the Fed survey did note developments that could 
lead to increased inflationary pressures. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawyers Say Drug Maker Misled MDs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- One of the manufacturers of the  
fen-phen diet drug misled doctors about the damage the pills could 
do, putting patients at increased risk for heart and lung ailments, 
a lawyer said today. Plaintiffs' attorney Esther Berezofsky 
comments' came as opening statements got under way in the first 
class-action suit to come to trial against American Home Products, 
manufacturer of half of the fen-phen diet drug combination. Three 
New Jersey women are suing the company on behalf of 94,000 New 
Jerseyans who took the pills. AHP -- which made fenfluramine, the 
``fen'' half of the drug duo, could be forced to pay more than $1 
billion over the next decade if it loses the civil case. 

</P>
<P>
	Customs Changing Search Policy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Customs Service said today that it will  
obtain the approval of a federal magistrate when it wants to hold a 
passenger for more than four hours who is suspected of smuggling 
drugs. The move comes as the agency is dogged by investigations and 
lawsuits alleging abusive searches. The change will take effect 
Oct. 1. Customs can now detain passengers for any period of time 
without having to go to a federal judge for approval. Under the 
change, Customs would be required to make a case before a federal 
judge showing that it has ``reasonable suspicion'' to keep the 
passenger in custody. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Seeks South Asia Clashes Ended  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States urgently called on India and  
Pakistan today to reinstitute a 1991 agreement aimed at avoiding 
clashes between military aircraft of the two countries. A key 
provision of the agreement forbids aircraft from flying within 10 
kilometers of each other's border without pre-notification and 
advance notification of such flights. The appeal came after the 
second aerial clash in two days between the South Asian rivals. 

</P>
<P>
	N.Y.'s Lazio Suspends Senate Plans  
</P>
<P>
	BAY SHORE, N.Y. (AP) -- Rep. Rick Lazio said today he will put  
his U.S. Senate campaign plans on hold while New York City Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani mulls getting into the race. While bowing to Gov. 
George Pataki's wish to give Giuliani a chance to make up his mind, 
Lazio said he was not withdrawing from the race and did not rule 
out a primary run against the mayor. Pataki asked Lazio to stop 
aside so the Republican party would be united in a race against 
likely Democratic candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 117  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 117.14 to 10,772.29. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,725-1,192. The Nasdaq was up 51.56 to 
2,541.67. 

</P>
<P>
	Bills Lose Shawn Bryson for Season  
</P>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Bills have lost impressive  
rookie fullback Shawn Bryson for the season with a torn anterior 
crucuiate ligament. Bryson will undergo surgery on the knee and 
will be placed on injured reserve. He is expected to spend the next 
6-8 weeks in rehabilitation. Bryson suffered the injury during 
practice yesterday afternoon when he made a cut during a run 
upfield. Teammates said they heard a popping sound when Bryson went 
down. He was a third-round pick this past April. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  



  	   	
</P>
