<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' QBs Know Their Roles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Kent Graham and Kerry Collins are trying to  
make the best out of what is an awkward situation at quarterback 
for the New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	The company line according to coach Jim Fassel is absolutely  
clear. 
</P>
<P>
	Graham, who led the team to five wins in its final six games  
last season, is the starting quarterback. Collins, whose career hit 
turbulent times the past two seasons in Carolina and New Orleans 
because of driving under the influence, poor play and allegations 
of racism, is the backup. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into the preseason opener at Minnesota on Friday night,  
there also is the constant speculation regarding the job. There is 
a belief that Collins, who was signed to a $16.9 million contract, 
will be the starter sometime this season. You don't pay someone a 
bundle of money to sit on the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Both have handled the situation well. They've been asked enough  
times, so they should know what to say. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know what my job is and I'll treat this like any preseason  
game,'' Graham said Wednesday between practices at the University 
at Albany. ``I'll just try and go out and execute, and not worry 
about any mitigating circumstances. I'll just try and go out and do 
a good job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, the fifth pick overall in the 1995 draft, has come to  
the Giants on his best behavior, knowing this might be his last 
shot. He was released by Carolina last year after saying his heart 
wasn't in the game any more, then he signed with New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he was arrested two weeks later on a drunken driving  
charge after a game in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins has worked hard to get his life and career back together  
since signing with New York in February. That led to the release of 
Danny Kanell, the man who led the Giants to the playoffs in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be foolish not to take advantage of this  
opportunity,'' said Collins, who helped Carolina get to the NFC 
championship game in his second season. ``I think I'm in a great 
organization which has given me a chance to really get things back 
on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every time Fassel has been asked, he has not hesitated to say  
Graham is his quarterback. He also has found time to praise the 
strong-armed Collins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see a level of maturity and self assuredness which is  
paramount in any quarterback,'' Fassel said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both played well in last week's intrasquad scrimmage. Graham hit  
5 of 8 passes for 83 yards and a touchdown. Collins was 5 of 12 for 
107 yards and a TD, including a 60-yard pass play to Joe 
Jurevicius, a fellow Penn State product. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the quarterbacks will go up against the Vikings, an  
early frontrunner to go to the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good test,'' Graham said. ``They are very good up  
front and we're going to have to be much sharper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Collins said his goal is to execute well. His main focus will be  
on third down since the Giants use a shotgun formation and 
different protections he has had to learn. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked point blank, Collins doesn't deny he wants to start.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants to play,'' the 26-year-old said. ``I don't  
think there is any doubt about that. The situation is what it is. 
I've accepted that. I understand what my role is. 
</P>
<P>
	``My focus is to just try to improve and be comfortable with the  
offense and try to make sure I can run it efficiently, if and when 
the time comes,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Giants trying to rebound from an 8-8 record after  
winning the NFC East the previous year, one has to wonder how 
patient Fassel will be if the team starts off slowly. Counting this 
year, he has two years left on his contract. Winning will be 
paramount. 
</P>
<P>
	That could put the pressure on Graham, a seven-year veteran who  
started his career with the Giants in 1992 as an eighth-round draft 
pick. Released prior to the 1995 season, he spent a year in Detroit 
and two in Arizona prior to signing with the Giants as a free agent 
in February, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He was almost a hero last year in replacing Kanell.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, he's on the spot, knowing Collins is ready to replace him.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
