<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Umpires Told: Shed Arrogance, Weight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Fat and arrogant.  
</P>
<P>
	That's the assessment of American major league umpires made by a  
Japanese ump who recently suspended himself for three games for 
blowing a call. 
</P>
<P>
	``Major league umpires are stubborn, and they're spiritually  
strong,'' umpire Toshiyuki Tanaka said. ``For me, it's about 
staying humble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 59-year-old Tanaka, a 35-year umpiring veteran, said he  
respects the pride that major league umps have in their work, but 
believes they have overstepped their bounds in their current labor 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't realize that there are plenty of guys out there who  
can do their job,'' he said. ``Handing in resignations -- that's 
exactly what the league wants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a bid to force an early start to negotiating a new contract,  
major league umpires announced last month that they would quit en 
masse on Sept. 2. That plan collapsed after major league baseball 
accepted 22 of the resignations and hired 25 new umpires. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to shedding their arrogance, Tanaka suggests U.S.  
umpires lose some weight as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can't move. They're too fat,'' said Tanaka, a muscular  
6-foot-tall man who jogs daily and has little flab, weighing 210 
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	In a nation where harmony is valued over conflict, the attitude  
of Japanese umpires like Tanaka stands in stark contrast to the 
American men in blue. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese umpires patiently endure insults from managers that  
major league umps would never tolerate. They wouldn't dare to call 
strikes with the trademark howl of their American cousins. 
</P>
<P>
	Compared with their assertive U.S. counterparts, Japanese  
umpires are almost apologetic. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanaka's fateful decision came during a game between the Yomiuri  
Giants and the league-leading Chunichi Dragons on July 22. 
</P>
<P>
	In the bottom of the eighth, Giants slugger Domingo Martinez hit  
a fly ball to right. Dragons outfielder Kazuki Inoue ran in to make 
the catch, his glove touching the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanaka, at first base, thought the ball popped out of Inoue's  
glove onto the grass before he scooped it up, and he awarded 
Martinez a hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Pandemonium broke out, with Inoue and Dragons manager Seinichi  
Hoshino protesting vigorously. Even usually reserved TV announcers 
questioned the call, which was replayed over and over in slow 
motion to viewers at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanaka did not reverse his call on the spot, and the Dragons  
went on to win 11-2. But when he later reviewed a videotape of the 
play, the truth was clear, and he voluntarily sat out for three 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``An umpire's job is about confidence. But being humble and  
doing your best everyday are just as important to improve your 
skills,'' Tanaka said. ``There's no progress if you can't doubt 
yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That kind of humility hasn't won Japanese umpires much respect.  
Batters and catchers here routinely curse what they think is a 
wrongly called strike. At least several times each season, players 
and managers rush out of the dugout to hurl shouts in the umpire's 
face, sometimes pushing him. 
</P>
<P>
	The only American to work as an umpire in Japan on a  
professional level, Mike DiMuro, lasted only a few months in 1997, 
quitting in disgust after being poked in the chest by a batter over 
a strike call. He is one of the minor league umpires who has been 
hired as a replacement in the labor dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	While Japanese umpires have to put up with abuse, fans and  
players complain that bad calls are on the increase. The 
high-profile Central League, where Tanaka works, even planned a 
special meeting this week to deal with the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel a need to uplift umpires' skills because of a series  
of troubles over calls,'' league spokesman Hideo Okoshi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tanaka doesn't expect his misjudged call to undermine his  
authority over players. But he is prepared to lose his job at the 
end of the season, and he has already lost a great deal of sleep 
over it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is really a thankless job. There's relief when one day  
goes by, but then you have to worry about the next day,'' he said. 
``It's impossible to hit a home run as an umpire.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
