<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> History To Repeat at Woodstock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHEL, N.Y. (AP) -- The heady idealism of Woodstock rose from  
the mud of this upstate hamlet 30 years ago, only to crash in the 
flames of July's anniversary concert. 
</P>
<P>
	But now some veteran artists from the original 1969 show are  
returning to give peace another chance. 
</P>
<P>
	David Crosby, Richie Havens and seven other '60s stalwarts will  
strum and sing on Max Yasgur's old farm on Aug. 15, this time as 
part of a nostalgia-tinged reunion. The modest one-day festival 
kicks off in the shadow of the far larger official Woodstock '99 
festival held in Rome, N.Y. in July. But given that Woodstock '99 
ended notoriously with fires and rioting, some veteran performers 
feel they can set a few things right. 
</P>
<P>
	``All over the world people know about Woodstock. It's just too  
bad it reflects this other stuff,'' said Rick Danko, the former 
bassist with The Band. Danko will return to Bethel with his old 
Band-mate, Garth Hudson. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything is going to restore it to something that isn't  
advocating violence and stupidity, that will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, maybe.  
</P>
<P>
	``A Day in the Garden'' looks to be a far cry from the  
counterculture mega-event that drew 400,000 people here for three 
days in August 1969. Many of the concert's top draws are dead (Jimi 
Hendrix, Janis Joplin) or disbanded (The Who, Grateful Dead). Nor 
will this show be heavy on hype and youth-oriented acts, as were 
the official Woodstock anniversary concerts held in Saugerties in 
1994 and Rome this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``A Day in the Garden'' figures to be more like your parents'  
Woodstock, with gray-haired acts whose names might draw blank 
stares from latter-day Woodstock moshers. Others in the lineup are 
Johnny Winter, Melanie, Country Joe McDonald and Arlo Guthrie. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the artists have remained friendly over the decades, and  
the concert has the feel of old buddies getting together. Some of 
the artists, like Guthrie and Crosby, are even performing with 
their kids this time around. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will be a little nostalgic, obviously,'' Guthrie  
said. ``There's a lot of aspects of this to me personally that mean 
more than just going to another gig.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guthrie fondly recalled 1969 as the year he was married and  
appeared in a movie based on his signature song, ``Alice's 
Restaurant.'' And, of course, it was the year the 22-year-old with 
a cloud of dark scraggly hair played at Woodstock for a huge crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was absolutely devastating to me. I don't know how I  
breathed,'' Guthrie said. ``It was totally bizarre to see that many 
people in that place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Danko remembered flying in a helicopter for the first time and  
being stunned during its descent by the sheer mass of people 
sitting on the hillside. 
</P>
<P>
	While Danko never again set foot on the field 80 miles northwest  
of New York City, Guthrie and some other veterans have come back. 
Those visits often resulted in impromptu anniversary performances 
for the tie-dyed masses who annually converged on the site. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference this time is that the rolling field now has a  
'90s makeover complete with groomed grass and a perimeter fence. 
This concert is a regulated event, with advance tickets selling for 
$19.69 (get it?) each. 
</P>
<P>
	A local businessman, Alan Gerry, recently bought the land and is  
developing it into a year-round entertainment attraction to tap 
into Woodstock's cultural cachet. 
</P>
<P>
	The upgraded site made its debut last August with a three-day  
concert featuring a few Woodstock alums like Pete Townshend along 
with contemporary acts such as the Goo Dolls. That concert was also 
called ``A Day in the Garden,'' a lyrical reference to the Joni 
Mitchell's song, ``Woodstock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Promoters said they drew 76,000 people over three days last  
August, with the largest crowd drawn to the contemporary acts on 
the last day. There is no early word on ticket sales for this 
year's one-day show, although it has piqued the interest of at 
least some former flower children. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say you can't go home again, but this is going to be like  
getting a Western Union from home,'' said Duke Devlin, a reveler at 
the original show who has worked at each successive concert. 
</P>
<P>
	While long-term development plans for the site are being worked  
out, it still plays host to musical events. Teen pop queen Britney 
Spears played a show in July, and Reba McEntire headlines a country 
lineup Aug. 14. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
