<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suggestions Sought for Parole Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department plans to seek  
suggestions for implementing ``re-entry'' courts that would augment 
the parole system by having state judges oversee the return of 
inmates to society. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to the American Bar Association in Atlanta on Tuesday,  
Attorney General Janet Reno suggested that re-entry courts could be 
modeled on the special local drug courts that were successful 
during her tenure as a Miami prosecutor -- a concept that has spread 
to several other cities 
</P>
<P>
	Reno said that unless inmates are brought ``back to our  
communities with a chance of success, the criminal justice system 
is going to fail again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many states are interested in the program and Nevada will begin  
having judges oversee the release of prisoners in October, said 
Jeremy Travis, director of the National Institute of Justice, the 
Justice Department's research group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our role would be to watch states experimenting with this idea  
and learning from them,'' Travis said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The population in state prisons now totals 1.2 million, four  
times what it was in 1980, and with more prisoners being released, 
parole violations also are on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the growth now in state prisons is not because of  
people committing new crimes, but parolees being returned to 
prison,'' Travis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many states have abolished or limited parole in recent years.  
</P>
<P>
	Re-entry courts could better manage parolees and reduce the  
criminal behavior that would send them back behind bars, he 
suggested. Judges would see parolees much more frequently and have 
more hands-on control, using coercion and support to keep them out 
of trouble, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea draws inspiration from ``problem-solving courts'' such  
as those for family violence and drug offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Those courts have focused on providing rehabilitative programs  
to treat defendants and giving judges the authority to establish 
criteria and incentives for avoiding prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's much more interactive between judge and offender,''  
Travis said, adding that judges can hold people accountable in ways 
that a parole officer with a caseload of 500 people cannot. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis said judges have the legal authority to put people in  
jail and the moral authority to instruct inmates on being 
law-abiding citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	``People react differently if they have to explain their  
behavior to a judge in a courtroom than they would explaining their 
behavior over the phone to a parole officer,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Justice Department official, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said Reno has ``expressed strong interest'' in also 
exploring the use of re-entry courts on the federal level. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 17:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
