<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Declines Internet Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of the Federal Communications  
Commission has declined to open a formal review of access to 
high-speed Internet connections, saying it would slow down the 
process of making those services available to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard, in a letter to state and local  
officials that advise the agency, once again defended the FCC's 
hands-off approach to regulating high-speed Internet services, also 
known as broadband, and particularly those offered over cable 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	He said by rejecting intervention, the FCC has fostered growth  
in the marketplace with ``impressive results across the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups and some Internet companies have voiced their  
concerns that cable companies will develop a monopoly in delivering 
fast Internet service over their wires. They want government 
regulators to force the cable companies to open their lines to 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	But the FCC has declined to do so, saying that it's too soon to  
determine if any one player has an advantage in the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``While some consider cable to have a lead at this time, it is  
premature to conclude either that such a lead will last or that its 
current position amounts to a monopoly,'' Kennard wrote in his 
letter. He noted that only about one million of the 40 million 
Internet users rely on cable Internet service. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said that FCC policies have helped fuel activity among  
phone, satellite and wireless companies in the race to build their 
own high-speed connections. Competitive pressures have led to 
increased rollouts of digital subscriber line, or DSL, services by 
local phone companies over their networks and at decreasing costs, 
Kennard said. Other companies are looking more seriously into how 
they might offer such high-speed connections using wireless or 
satellite technology, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-member advisory panel of local and state officials had  
recommended that the agency open a formal proceeding on access to 
high-speed Internet service. But Kennard said such a probe ``would 
chill investment in cable modem service.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Public interest groups said the FCC's policies will lead to a  
closed system that runs contrary to the open nature of the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I find it especially painful that (the chairman) is telling  
state and local governments what to do and that he is forcing the 
restrictive cable television model down their throats,'' said 
Andrew Schwartzman, president of the public interest law firm the 
Media Access Project. ``The cable industry wants the Internet to be 
just like cable television.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
