<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oakwood Homes CEO To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Struggling manufactured-home builder  
Oakwood Homes Corp. said Wednesday its longtime chief executive 
will retire and that the company is no longer looking for a suitor. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholas St. George, chief executive officer since 1979, will  
retire Sept. 30. President and chief operating officer William G. 
Edwards will be his successor, St. George said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards, 55, was founder and president of Destiny Industries  
before Oakwood acquired the Georgia company in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which is the nation's largest retailer of  
manufactured homes, also said it had halted efforts to look for a 
buyer after a succession of poor earnings reports. 
</P>
<P>
	``After extensive deliberations, the Board of Directors believes  
that the interests of the company's shareholders are best served by 
the company and its management focusing on addressing the 
challenges facing the company,'' said Oakwood director Dennis 
Meyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakwood also said that recent layoffs, attrition and three plant  
closings have eliminated about 1,000 jobs from its 12,500-member 
workforce since April. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has about 400 company-owned stores and 29  
manufacturing plants. It also sells homes through independent 
dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under St. George's leadership, the company raised revenues from  
$37 million in 1979 to $1.5 billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But earnings tumbled last year after Oakwood had to take $45  
million in charges against earnings because more people defaulted 
on its mortgage loans than expected and more people than 
anticipated refinanced their loans. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
