<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Clears KLM-Alitalia Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- European Union antitrust regulators  
Wednesday cleared the long-term alliance between KLM Royal Dutch 
Airlines and Italy's national carrier Alitalia SpA., after the 
airlines agreed to end their monopoly on flights between Amsterdam 
and the Italian hubs at Milan and Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Commission said KLM and Alitalia pledged to allow  
competitors to operate up to four daily flights on Amsterdam-Rome 
and Amsterdam-Milan routes, including two at peak times, and to 
take other measures to open up competition on the routes. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU executive body said the alliance did not risk creating an  
anticompetitive situation on other routes. 
</P>
<P>
	KLM and Alitalia announced their pact in November, aiming to  
strengthen their position in intercontinental and European routes 
in the face of a series of alliances involving other European 
airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Although they won't take equity stakes in each other, the two  
will integrate passenger and cargo operations, sharing sales and 
reservation systems, coordinating routes and combining frequent 
flier programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance is scheduled to come into operation Nov. 1.  
</P>
<P>
	Alitalia and KLM combined hope to get 20 percent of Europe's  
commercial air travel within the next five years. KLM currently has 
about 8 percent, Alitalia 7 percent. The companies say the project 
will generate annual savings worth hundreds of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	KLM and Alitalia also have a code-sharing arrangement with  
Northwest Airlines and are expected to soon enter into a similar 
deal with another U.S. carrier, Continental Airlines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
