<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Says Economy Growing Strongly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The economy is growing strongly with even the  
beleaguered manufacturing sector showing signs of an upturn, the 
Federal Reserve said Wednesday in a new survey of business 
conditions around the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	While nearly every region of the country faced labor shortages,  
the Fed said wage pressures did not seem to be accelerating or 
causing widespread pressures on inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets took heart from the Fed's lack of alarm about  
inflation. But private economists said the Fed report, known as the 
``beige book'' for the cover's color, did not change their view the 
central bank is getting ready to raise interest rates for a second 
time this year when policy-makers meet Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message from this report is that the economy is doing very  
well with inflation tame, but it is bumping up against capacity 
constraints,'' said Mark Zandi, economist at Regional Financial 
Associates in West Chester, Pa. ``Fed officials are laying the 
groundwork for another rate hike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices, however, posted their biggest gains of the month  
with the Dow Jones industrial average rising 132.65 points to close 
at 10,787.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Private economists noted the numerous warnings the beige book  
included about labor shortages, low inventory stockpiles for 
retailers and supply constraints. They said all of this supported 
their view that the Fed will raise interest rates by another 
quarter-point later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the market took some comfort from this report, I don't  
think it changes anything,'' said Wayne Ayers, chief economist at 
BankBoston. ``Fed officials are returning to a pre-emptive mode and 
basing their policies on what they are fearful they will see down 
the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed raised its target for the federal funds rate, the  
interest that banks charge each other, for the first time in two 
years on June 30, nudging it up by a quarter point to 5 percent. 
That move immediately was followed by a matching increase in banks' 
prime lending rate, the benchmark for millions of consumer and 
business loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations of another rate increase have intensified since  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told Congress last month 
the central bank would move ``promptly and forcefully'' at the 
first signs of price pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with Wednesday's rally, stock prices are off sharply from  
their mid-July records and bond prices, always hurt when inflation 
worries increase, have fallen as well, pushing bond yields to their 
highest levels in nearly two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed report, compiled from surveys by the Fed's 12 regional  
banks, said that the economy continued to show strength in late 
July and early August. Consumer demand and housing construction 
remained strong, and various manufacturing sectors shook off the 
effects of the Asian currency crisis, which has cut sharply into 
their export markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Widespread labor shortages persist in virtually every  
district, but there have been only scattered reports of 
acceleration in wages,'' the Fed survey said. ``There are some 
reports of accelerating prices -- largely related to home 
construction -- but there is no evidence of any broad-based pickup 
in consumer price inflation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston, Cleveland, Dallas and San Francisco Fed districts  
reported strong demand for computer and telecommunications 
equipment while Cleveland and Chicago reported orders for heavy 
trucks, the Fed said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said that ``manufacturers in the West -- Dallas and  
San Francisco -- report some pickup in exports to Asia'' but as of 
yet the export rebound was not widespread. The Labor Department 
reported last Friday that employment in manufacturing rose in July 
for only the second time in 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed report said that housing construction was continuing at  
a vigorous pace in most districts although there were signs that a 
lack of available building materials and skilled workers was 
limiting growth in many areas. 
</P>
<P>
	While hot and dry weather was causing crop damage in the eastern  
part of the country, the Fed said that crops were generally in good 
shape in other areas. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
