<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Vows To Bolster Farm Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore started his  
latest campaign visit to Iowa today with a warning that the 
nation's farm policy ``is in serious need of improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to cash in on the heavy attention of this weekend's  
Republican straw poll in Ames, Gore planned a two-day trip, hopping 
from small town to small town and focusing on farm issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are, in 1999, two Iowas,'' Gore said. ``There's an Iowa  
with unemployment under 2.6 percent with an economy that's booming 
and a future that's bright. But there's also a farm economy that's 
hurting badly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's effort to draw attention to farm issues was echoed by his  
Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, making 
stops today in Sioux City and at the Dunlap Livestock Auction 
before heading to Des Moines. 
</P>
<P>
	At his first event, Gore said the Freedom to Farm Act is badly  
flawed and in need of revision. That measure largely phased out 
traditional farm subsidies while also lifting restrictions on 
planting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some provisions should be kept but others must be changed,''  
Gore said, who also called for ``immediate emergency help'' for 
farmers who are suffering historic low commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pledge my support and all out help to Iowans in both of  
those economies,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest visit to Iowa was Gore's 25th as vice president. He's  
a clear front-runner for the Democratic presidential nomination, 
leading Bradley in most early surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was solidifying that support today by announcing the  
endorsements of a long list of Polk County Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore collected the endorsement of Des Moines Mayor Preston  
Daniels, six Democratic state legislators and other prominent 
elected officials such as Polk County Attorney John Sarcone. 
</P>
<P>
	Those elected officials are important in Democratic  
organizational politics and are veterans in turning out Democratic 
activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also took note of the most recent shootings in California.  
</P>
<P>
	``My thoughts and prayers are with the families of the victims  
and the victims themselves,'' Gore said. ``It causes us all to 
pause and reflect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore planned stops in Newton, Marshalltown, Iowa Falls and Mason  
City before ending his campaign day. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine Republicans are competing in the straw poll Saturday that  
has attracted 600 journalists. Both Gore and Bradley are seeking to 
collect a bit of that attention by scheduling a campaign trip 
during the straw poll furor. 
</P>
<P>
	While Republicans are seeking to lure activists to the Ames  
straw poll, both Gore and Bradley were spelling out farm policy 
proposals. Gore was expected to announce farm proposals on Thursday 
and he said he was working with Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, to revamp 
the Freedom to Farm Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to spending the next two days in small  
towns across Iowa,'' Gore said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
