<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornoado Postpones Retailer Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Mother Nature obliterated the largest  
convention of outdoor retailers as a freak tornado tore through the 
city, shredding a display pavilion and postponing the show's 
opening. 
</P>
<P>
	The Outdoor Retailers Summer Market was scheduled to open  
Thursday, but show director Dieter Tremp said there will be at 
least a one-day delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Tremp asked exhibitors whose booths remained intact to help  
those who suffered damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Think about the gathering aspect rather than the selling  
aspect,'' he told exhibitors. ``Be prepared to offer your support 
to others tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado kicked up at about 12:45 p.m. and swirled northeast  
through the heart of the city, gouging a trail of rubble, uprooting 
trees, blowing out windows, and knocking over tractor-trailers. 
</P>
<P>
	One person was killed and more than 100 injured.  
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday was meant to be setup day for the 2,500 booths. Some  
850 exhibitors and 17,000 visitors were expected to attend. 
</P>
<P>
	But the tornado wiped out between 15 percent and 20 percent of  
the exhibits, mostly in a tent-covered pavilion designated for the 
smaller exhibitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Stock of Toronto, a sales representative for a  
rock-climbing company, said he saw the roof of the Delta Center, 
which was hosting the show, lift up when the tornado passed over. 
</P>
<P>
	``It peeled it right back, just like an orange peel,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	It will likely be three days before exhibitors can get into the  
devastated pavilion, Tremp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drew Simmons, spokesman for show organizers, said exhibitors who  
could least afford the loss were in the pavilion hit the hardest. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bank owns it all,'' Simmons said.  
</P>
<P>
	Buyers place orders for their spring products at the show, the  
largest for the $4.5 billion outdoor retail industry, Simmons said. 
</P>
<P>
	The show was expected to generate between $15 million and $18  
million for the city, said Richard E. Davis, president and CEO of 
the Salt Lake Convention and Visitors Bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	Conventioneers and others staying at the Wyndham Hotel were  
displaced when the tornado blew out windows and forced evacuation. 
Davis said other hotels found space to accommodate those left 
without a room. 
</P>
<P>
	``For Salt Lake City, this is unprecedented. We've never had  
anything like this,'' Davis said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 15:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed's Regional Assessments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Excerpts from the summaries of the 12 Federal Reserve districts  
reporting on economic conditions in their regions: 
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON: Economic activity continues its expansion. Area  
manufacturers report positive results more consistently than they 
did earlier in the year and retailers say sales growth is still 
strong. Most employers indicate labor markets are tight, but 
general wage increases remain in the 3 percent to 5 percent range. 
With limited exceptions, prices are generally level or down. 
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK: The economy continues to expand, thought at a somewhat  
slower pace than in the last report. There are indications of an 
increase in wage and price pressures in some key sectors. Most 
retailers report that sales retreated to more normal levels in 
July, following exceptionally strong activity throughout the second 
quarter. Manhattan's office market tightened further, but 
commercial real estate appears to have softened in most of the 
outlying suburbs. Housing demand continues to strengthen -- 
especially in the New York City area, where builders and Realtors 
report sharp price increases and cite lack of inventory as the No. 
1 problem. 
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA: Overall business activity advanced moderately in  
July and consumption spending appeared to be robust. Manufacturers 
posted slight gains in shipments and new orders. Retailers reporter 
an increase in total sales from a year ago and a surge in sales of 
summer merchandise. Auto dealers said sales were strong in June, 
although there was a seasonal slowing in July. ... Tourism 
officials indicated that spending for lodging, meals and 
recreational activities in most resort areas so far this season has 
been at its highest level in a decade. Farming has suffered from 
drought conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND: Employment agencies continue to have difficulty  
finding enough bodies to fill the positions available. Agencies 
report that demand for temporary workers is significantly higher 
than this time last year, with administrative assistants and 
computer support personnel in especially short supply. ... Tight 
labor markets have helped push up collective bargaining settlements 
slightly for all industries except mining. ... Low prices and a 
lack of rain have put pressure on the farming sector. 
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND: Economic activity advanced at a brisk pace in June and  
July. Retailers reported strong sales, particularly of automobiles, 
furniture and apparel. Business services and tourism revenues 
strengthened and manufacturers stepped up production and hiring. At 
financial institutions, higher interest rates slowed mortgage 
lending but had little effect on the pace of commercial lending. 
The real estate sector remained generally strong. Home sales 
advanced at a rapid pace and prime commercial property continued to 
be highly sought. Wages accelerated slightly in the retail sector 
but remained moderate in other sectors. 
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA: Moderate growth continues and the outlook is positive.  
July sales have been up moderately compared with a year ago and 
this trend is expected to continue through year-end. The tourism 
and hospitality sector continues to post strong numbers. 
Residential construction slowed recently but remains at strong 
levels while commercial construction is slightly ahead of last year 
at this time. Manufacturing has slowed recently but contacts remain 
upbeat about future prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO: Conditions in June and July were characterized by  
modest expansion and very tight labor markets. Consumer spending 
remained strong, led by resilient demand for home-related items and 
light vehicles. Construction activity was again robust, but some 
Realtors and homebuilders lowered their expectations for the coming 
months. Exceptional motor vehicle production, both light vehicles 
and heavy trucks, led a robust manufacturing sector, despite some 
segments continuing to struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS: The economy continues to grow at a brisk pace. Most  
contacts report growth in sales and demand. Despite continuing 
difficulties filling some job vacancies, upward wage pressures 
remain at bay. Housing markets are still very strong. ... Despite 
persistent heat and the lack of adequate rainfall in July, crops 
remain in mostly good condition. 
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS: The pulse of the economy continues strong. With the  
exception of natural resource-based businesses, most district firms 
are having a good year. Retail sales are robust; construction, 
particularly highway building, is healthy; tourism is gaining 
momentum after a slow, weather-induced start. Prices are generally 
stable, with a few exceptions. Signs of wage increases are evident 
as the region's businesses continue to cope with labor shortages. 
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY: The economy remained healthy in June and early  
July, but growth continued to slow from the brisk rate of last 
year. The recent boom in construction appeared to subside somewhat, 
and manufacturing activity slowed slightly from a strong 
performance in May. Retail activity was flat, although sales were 
still comfortably higher than a year ago. District farmers faced 
cash flow concerns as grain prices continued to fall. Labor markets 
remained very tight, with wage pressures present but largely 
unchanged from previous surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS: In late June and July, economic activity accelerated  
slightly. Demand for manufactured goods and cargo transportation 
services increased. Energy activity increased slightly with more 
gas drilling and less oil drilling. Demand for business and 
financial services was steady and construction and real estate 
activity was unchanged. Agricultural producers reported generally 
good growing conditions. Retail sales slowed in July. 
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO: Reports indicated strong economic conditions.  
Retailers reported solid sales growth, while service providers 
noted a pickup in growth above an already rapid pace. Manufacturing 
activity picked up in much of the district, although import 
competition continued to temper growth in some sectors. Conditions 
among many agricultural producers deteriorated in recent weeks as 
poor weather, low prices and weak demand challenged profitability. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 10:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Three-Way Aluminum Merger Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Three top aluminum manufacturers Wednesday  
announced their merger in a combination that could create the 
world's largest aluminum producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian aluminum giant Alcan Aluminium plans to combine with  
European rivals, French company Pechiney and Alusuisse-Lonza 
(Algroup) of Switzerland to form a new company provisionally called 
Alcan-Pechiney-Algroup. 
</P>
<P>
	APA may not remain atop the aluminum industry for long, however.  
Just hours after the announcement of the deal, Alcoa, the current 
leading aluminum producer in the world, revealed Wednesday it had 
made an unsolicited $5.6 billion bid for U.S. competitor, Reynolds 
Metals. 
</P>
<P>
	If both deals go through, the new companies will have similar  
annual revenue, around $21 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposed three-way arrangement, Alcan stockholders  
will ultimately hold 44 percent of the new company, Pechiney 29 
percent and Algroup 27 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Alcan chairman Jacques Bougie will head APA, but he is expected  
to hand over to Pechiney chairman Jean-Pierre Rodier in two years' 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's 12-member board will contain four members from  
each of the three companies. The company will be registered in 
Montreal, the current base for Alcan, but will be directed from New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company would have a substantial packaging business in  
addition to its aluminum side and will employ 91,000. Job cuts of 
about 5 percent would be achieved through natural attrition, the 
companies have said. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's strong presence throughout the aluminum product  
cycle leaves it well-protected from the changing price of aluminum, 
Bougie said at a press conference in London. 
</P>
<P>
	``With three divisions -- primary aluminum, fabricated products  
and packaging -- APA would be less sensitive to aluminum price 
fluctuations on the London Metal Exchange,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the new company would have to act quickly if it  
wanted to have a big impact worldwide, especially as there are 
cultural and managerial differences between the three companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``The management may have shareholder value in mind, but it may  
take some time to instill global thinking in the new company's work 
force,'' said Christoph Bohli, an analyst at Bank Sarasin in 
Zurich. 
</P>
<P>
	Pechiney's role in the three-way merger is subject to  
discussions about the fate of the work force, which are required 
under French law, and may also face a competition investigation by 
the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Algroup has signed a separate deal with Alcan, and Algroup chief  
executive Sergio Marchionne said the merger of the Canadian and 
Swiss companies would go ahead even if the French deal foundered. 
</P>
<P>
	Algroup president Martin Ebner said the deal was necessary to  
look for opportunities to expand on the world market. ``Only those 
who are big enough to act globally and produce at the lowest cost 
can survive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pechiney shares ended the day up 5.5 percent on the Paris  
Bourse. Algroup shares were down 2.2 percent in Zurich on 
profit-taking following a 3.7 percent rise Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Algroup's Lonza chemicals division will not be part of the deal.  
It will be spun off into a separate company this fall, managers 
said. Shares in Basel-based Ciba Specialty Chemicals rose 6.6 
percent as dealers speculated that it might merge with Lonza. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
