<DOCNO> APW19990811.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 16:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Hundreds of workers who lost their  
jobs when the state-run flour mill was privatized blocked its 
entrance with flaming tires Wednesday and demanded compensation for 
their lost income. 
</P>
<P>
	Waving placards demanding ``payment for our toil,'' the workers  
blocked the road from the northbound highway to the mill, about 18 
miles north of the capital, Port-au-Prince. This is the second such 
protest at the mill since July 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The flour mill was transferred to private hands in September  
1997, after it had been closed. Hundreds of workers were not hired 
back when it reopened. 
</P>
<P>
	The flour mill's privatization is part of a plan to privatize  
nine inefficient state-owned enterprises. The privatizations are 
expected to eliminate thousands of jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- A fisherman was killed Wednesday  
morning by a swarm of killer bees in the Gulf state of Tabasco, 
local authorities reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Alvarez, 40, and his three children -- aged 6, 8, and 9 --  
were attacked while fishing in the La Iguana River, 45 miles 
northwest of Villahermosa, the state capital, civil protection 
deputy director Roberto Lopez Romero said. 
</P>
<P>
	The children escaped by jumping in the river. But Alvarez did  
not follow them. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's incident came a day after another killer bee attack  
left 60 injured in the central state of Nayarit. 
</P>
<P>
	Nayarit authorities said the attack was the most serious in a  
series of killer bee attacks over the past few days. 
</P>
<P>
	The bees are dangerous because they are so aggressive when  
protecting their hives. They began moving north after a Brazilian 
laboratory accidentally released them in 1956. Several people in 
the southern United States have been killed by them. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- Heavy rains in the  
southern state of Chiapas caused two rivers to overflow their 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Two men drowned when the truck in which they were riding was  
swept away in the floodwaters. 
</P>
<P>
	The flooding Tuesday on the Pico de Loro and Ojo de Agua rivers  
also damaged 18 adobe homes, the drinking water supply and a bridge 
in the village of Pakayal, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of Pakayal residents were cut off from the village by  
landslides from the southern Sierra Madre mountains. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 17:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore for $2 Billion Biomass Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Wrioter    	
</P>
<P>
	IOWA FALLS, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore on Thursday will  
detail a $2 billion boost in Iowa farm income under an effort to 
boost the use of biomass technologies. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to bolstering income for farmers, Gore will argue  
that the effort will cut sharply into greenhouse gas emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is set to make the announcement at an Iowa campaign swing,  
touting its boost to farmers who are suffering through a sagging 
farm economy that threatens to drive thousands from the land. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is made possible by advances in farming and biological  
technologies allowing for a far more diverse use of trees and other 
crops for a variety of purposes. Those range from distilling of 
ethanol to blend with gasoline to make it burn cleaner to bio-based 
textiles and furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	Targeting an increase in the use of bioenergy and bioproducts  
would be a boon for farmers throughout the nation. The $2 billion 
boost in farm income in Iowa is certain to ripple across the 
country, and boost rural income substantially more than that. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to boosting farm income backers of the use of  
biomass technology say it's environmentally friendly as well. 
Backers argue it can cut into production of greenhouse gases often 
blamed for global warming. 
</P>
<P>
	The plants used in biomass technology -- such as trees -- absorb  
carbons during their growth, and their use in energy and other 
applications can cut into carbon emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the plants are largely deep-rooted varieties which  
are helpful in controlling erosion and filtering chemicals from 
groundwater. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowing Gore to detail the impact of such a program in a  
politically sensitive state like Iowa is yet another sign of the 
clout he gains from having the White House on his side. 
</P>
<P>
	He's competing against former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley for  
the Democratic presidential nomination, and both are campaigning in 
Iowa on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's ability to make the announcement makes him the center of  
attention, and also the bearer of very good economic news for 
farmers at avery troubled economic time. 
</P>
<P>
	Most farmers are sufffering through historic low price levels  
for most traditional commodities. 
</P>
<P>
	Opening the gate for the production of new and nontraditional  
commodities could hold out hope for farmers, and could provide the 
fodder for new research at places like Iowa State Unversity on 
seeking even more new uses for biomass technology. 
</P>
<P>
	That could be yet another fallout from the administration's  
decision to push for a sharply increased role for the rapidly 
evolving biomass technology. That technology isn't well known in 
many parts of the country, but is an emerging environmental issue 
and a hot topic in farm states like Iowa, where precinct caucuses 
launch the nominating season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 08:29:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pakistan Fires on India Choppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BHUJ, India (AP) -- Pakistan fired a missile at Indian aircraft  
flying near the crash site of a Pakistani surveillance plane today, 
the second aerial clash in the disputed border region in two days. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani military spokesman Brig. Rashid Quereshi said his  
forces fired on two Indian fighter jets escorting three helicopters 
to the crash site. An Associated Press reporter was among a group 
of journalists aboard the helicopters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two Mig 21 fighters ... approached the site of the wreckage.  
Our troops who were there engaged them and fired one time,'' 
Quereshi said. He said a surface-to-air missile was used, but 
refused to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian Group Capt. P. S. Bhangu said that from the cockpit he  
saw a missile flash coming from the direction of the Pakistani 
border, and immediately the three choppers veered away from the 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	The helicopters returned to base, and defense officials in the  
Indian capital said they had no knowledge of the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani soldiers were digging in at the crash site, placing  
anti-aircraft missiles and machine guns. India downed the navy 
plane Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan both retrieved wreckage from the downed  
surveillance plane today, and each accused the other of provoking 
their first aerial clash in nearly three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The downing of the Pakistani naval aircraft near the disputed  
border has reignited tensions between the hostile neighbors that 
had barely cooled since an undeclared war this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan said 16 crew members were killed. More than 24 hours  
after the plane was shot down, no bodies had been found. 
</P>
<P>
	India's air force chief said the Pakistani plane could have been  
scouting possible invasion routes, and that the pilots of the 
Indian interceptors feared the plane was armed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the event of an offensive, they could be looking for ...  
the possible creeks, the possible channels through which they can 
come in,'' Air Marshal A.Y. Tipnis told reporters at Naliya, an air 
base in the western state of Gujarat. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash site was near Sir Creek, about 60 miles southeast of  
the Pakistani port of Karachi and 90 miles northwest of the Indian 
city of Bhuj. 
</P>
<P>
	Both countries said they had recovered wreckage from the  
aircraft, which may have been scattered on both sides of the border 
where western India meets southeast Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pakistan's capital, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif called a  
Cabinet meeting to discuss his country's response. On Tuesday, 
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said Pakistan reserved the right to 
respond. 
</P>
<P>
	India said the French-built Atlantique, a surveillance and  
submarine-hunting aircraft, was shot down after penetrating six 
miles into Indian airspace and failing to respond to warnings. 
Pakistan said the aircraft was within its own territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian defense officials said the Atlantique could carry Exocet  
air-to-air missiles, although Pakistan said its plane was unarmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Quereshi, the Pakistani army spokesman, said his country's  
forces detected Indian naval movements near their waters. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Indian soldiers had violated Pakistan's territory and  
``stole some small parts of the aircraft'' to back Indian claims 
that the plane fell in its territory. 
</P>
<P>
	India said its air force had retrieved part of the wreckage --  
including a wing, the cockpit and the plane's cable hydraulic 
system -- from Indian territory near the Pakistani border. 
</P>
<P>
	An Indian air force statement said Indian radar detected the  
Pakistani plane in its airspace and signaled the pilot to land at 
an Indian air base. Instead, the propeller-driven plane turned 
toward an Indian jet ``in a hostile manner,'' according to the 
statement. The Indian MiG-21 fired an air-to-air missile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian military charged that Pakistan had violated Indian  
airspace in the area eight times since May. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan's Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz denied that, and  
described the attack as a ``blatant and unprovoked act of military 
aggression against an unarmed aircraft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani authorities showed reporters the mangled wreckage as  
well as a parachute, a dingy, the flight manual, a checklist and 
personal documents of the crew. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation dispelled any immediate hope of moving  
relations between the world's newest nuclear powers back onto a 
peaceful track. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan have fought three wars since they gained  
independence from Britain in 1947, and despite frequent diplomatic 
scuffles, this was their first aerial clash since they last went to 
war in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged the two rivals to  
exercise ``maximum restraint,'' and called on both countries to 
settle their differences peacefully. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan came to the brink of war this summer during  
an 11-week confrontation in the mountains of Kashmir. India said 
Pakistani troops had infiltrated its territory, but Pakistan denied 
its soldiers were involved and said all the fighters were local 
militants. 
</P>
<P>
	India said today its troops killed five Pakistani soldiers as it  
repulsed attacks Tuesday on the 20,000-feet disputed Siachen 
Glacier in northern Kashmir. There was no immediate comment from 
Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	A Defense Ministry statement said more than 20 Pakistani troops  
twice tried to capture an Indian post on the glacier, 600 miles 
north of New Delhi. Indian and Pakistani troops have been fighting 
for control of Siachen since the early 1980s despite severe cold 
and high winds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 08:29:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pakistan Fires on India Choppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
