<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Moves To Restore Tailhook Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Navy Secretary Richard Danzig took a step  
Tuesday toward restoring official ties with the Tailhook 
Association, a naval aviator booster group whose 1991 Las Vegas 
convention produced a sex-harassment scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Danzig told the organization's president in a letter that a  
three-member Navy delegation would to attend this year's Tailhook 
Association convention next week to observe it ``first hand and 
speak informally with the association's leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He held out conditional ``possible resumption of support'' for  
the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``As you know, the shameful events at the Tailhook convention in  
1991 led to a withdrawal of our support for the Tailhook 
Association,'' Danzig said in the letter to Retired Navy Capt. 
Lonny K. McClung, Tailhook's current president. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the past eight years, however, the association has taken  
a number of constructive steps that warrant a review of its 
status,'' Danzig wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Female officers were groped and fondled by aviators attending  
parties during a three-day aviator's conference at a Las Vegas 
hotel in September 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Department Inspector General implicated 117 officers  
for sexual assault, indecent exposure and other acts, and faulted 
the Navy's leaders for failing to stop the behavior. In October 
1991 the Navy ended all support ``in any manner whatsoever, direct 
or indirect'' for Tailhook. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a cautionary act, not an embrace...,'' Cmdr. Brian  
Cullin, a Navy spokesman, said Tuesday. ``But it is an action taken 
based on the progress we have seen the Tailhook Association has 
taken over the years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman also noted ``dramatic changes in the Navy'' since  
the episode, including the introduction of women combat pilots who 
fly aircraft off carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our profile has changed,'' Cullin said.  
</P>
<P>
	Danzig said the Navy delegation attending the Tailhook  
convention would include Carolyn Becraft, assistant Navy secretary 
for manpower and reserve affairs; Vice Admiral Mike Bowman, 
commander of the U.S. Pacific Fleet, and Lt. Gen. John Rhodes of 
the Marine Corps Combat Development Command. The convention is Aug. 
19-22 in Reno, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	He commended the organization for taking steps to improve its  
image, including adopting resolutions condemning harassment and 
honoring the ``services and sacrifices of all those who are ... a 
part of carrier-based aviation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``To determine whether official support of the association is  
now warranted, I need to assess the extent to which the association 
lives by these principles,'' Danzig said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that in order to earn back the Navy's support, Tailhook  
would have to show that it could focus on ``professional challenges 
and opportunities facing naval aviation,'' support all men and 
women in the carrier aviation community and ``take all reasonable 
steps'' to prevent other episodes of misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Adm. Jay Johnson, the chief of naval operations,  
called rehabilitating the Tailhook Association a remaining piece of 
``unfinished business'' in the Navy's effort to put the scandal 
behind it. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said then in an interview with The Associated Press that  
he was working with organization's leaders ``to make sure that 
we've learned the lessons we needed to learn -- which we have -- and 
that we've institutionalized those lessons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McClung, a retired Navy captain who has been president of the  
Tailhook group since 1995, said then that ``the timing is right'' 
to get back in the Navy's good graces. 
</P>
<P>
	His organization, named for the hook on a plane that snags an  
arresting cable on the landing deck of an aircraft carrier, has 
about 10,000 members -- down from its 1991 peak of about 16,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides its annual conventions, which include professional  
seminars, the group sponsors college scholarships for children of 
former naval aviators and publishes a magazine on carrier aviation 
called Hook. 
</P>
<P>
	The September 1991 convention of Tailhook members at the Las  
Vegas Hilton Hotel triggered the resignation of Navy Secretary H. 
Lawrence Garrett and the early retirement of Adm. Frank B. Kelso, 
then the chief of naval operations. 
</P>
<P>
	It also led to lawsuits, multiple investigations and changes in  
the Navy -- including more emphasis on ethics and sexual harassment 
awareness and an opening of more aviation opportunities for women. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
