<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Polio Effort Stops Congo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The warring sides in the Congo have  
stopped fighting in most areas in response to a U.N. appeal for a 
cease-fire so 10 million children can be vaccinated against polio, 
a U.N. spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary-General Kofi Annan received assurances from Congolese  
President Laurent Kabila and rebel leaders controlling the eastern 
part of the country that they would lay down their weapons on Aug. 
8 to permit the immunization campaign to proceed on Aug. 13-20. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with continued localized fighting, relief agencies believe  
that the campaign can reach over 95 percent of children under age 
5, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Congo is the top priority for the global campaign to eradicate  
polio by the end of the year 2000 because it has the most intense 
polio virus transmission in the world, according to a joint 
statement by Annan, World Health Organization Director-General Gro 
Harlem Brundtland and UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of reported polio cases worldwide has declined from  
35,000 in 1988 to 6,000 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The halt to most fighting for the immunization campaign comes as  
intensive diplomatic efforts are under way to get the main rebel 
group in Congo to sign a peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	The cease-fire agreement was signed July 10 by Kabila and his  
allies -- Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia -- and by Rwanda and Uganda, 
who are backing the rebels. The rebel Congolese Liberation Movement 
signed on Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	But the principal rebel organization, the Congolese Rally for  
Democracy, has refused to sign because of a leadership dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan reiterated his call for all parties to comply with the  
truce so the immunizations can go ahead, stressing that the ``days 
of tranquility'' could also be used to promote peace. 
</P>
<P>
	``These vaccination campaigns are a platform for the  
peace-building process. They open windows of opportunity for 
dialogue between the different sides,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Volunteers will staff some 16,000 immunization sites with  
support from WHO and the U.N. Children's Fund, who are spearheading 
the polio eradication campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every child counts,'' Brundtland said. ``In the eradication  
effort we need to gain access to children in pockets of unrest and 
strife. If we miss a single village we will fail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bellamy said immunization is recognized as the right of every  
child on Earth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a victory for children when armed conflict stops and  
these rights become real,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	War-torn countries, especially those in Africa, top UNICEF's  
list of nations where children are most at risk. In addition to 
Congo, they include Angola, Sierra Leone, Afghanistan, Somalia, 
Ethiopia, Guinea-Bissau, Niger, Burundi and Eritrea. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
