<HEADLINE> Milwaukee Park Damage Minimal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) -- Experts inspecting Miller Park have  
found no additional structural damage from a crane collapse that 
killed three people but can't say whether the ballpark will be 
ready for opening day next April. 
</P>
<P>
	The only area that showed significant damage was near first  
base, where the crane fell, according to Michael Duckett, director 
of the board overseeing the project. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is good news to report,'' Duckett said Wednesday. ``It's  
much what we assumed earlier, but now there's evidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the inspection halfway over, Duckett said it's too early to  
tell whether the retractable-roof ballpark will be completed in 
time for its scheduled opening. He said the board was waiting for 
the complete report before putting together a revised construction 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction on the $400 million stadium halted July 14 when a  
crane called ``Big Blue'' collapsed while lifting a 400-ton roof 
section of metal framework, killing the three workers and leaving a 
pile of twisted steel on the field. 
  	   	
</P>
