<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bison Herd Quarantine May Be Lifted / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT PIERRE, S.D. (AP) -- Brucellosis, a disease that has  
afflicted cattle and calves around the country, could be eliminated 
from the nation's only quarantined private buffalo herd in 15 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Elimination of the disease, which now exists in only a handful  
of cattle herds nationwide, could save many of the nation's farmers 
and ranchers the expense of vaccinating and testing their animals. 
</P>
<P>
	Brucellosis causes cows to abort and become sterile, reduces  
milk production and makes calves sick. It also can cause undulant 
fever in people who drink unpasteurized milk; the debilitating 
disease is usually not fatal but can cause infections of the brain 
and central nervous system and heart dysfunction. 
</P>
<P>
	Sam Holland, state veterinarian and executive secretary of the  
South Dakota Animal Industry Board, said a plan was developed 
earlier this year to rid the Triple U Enterprises buffalo herd of 
brucellosis. The 60,000-acre Triple U ranch, about 30 miles 
northwest of Fort Pierre, once had the nation's largest private 
herd: more than 4,000 head of buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to a $1 billion eradication program, only the Triple U  
buffalo herd and five infected private cattle herds in Texas and 
Missouri still harbor brucellosis, down from 124,000 herds 
nationwide in 1956. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time, cattlemen have been concerned about bison and  
brucellosis,'' said Sam Albrecht, executive director of the 
National Bison Association. ``Now we can say ... 'We're not a 
threat to the cattle industry as far as bison are concerned.''' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Albrecht said brucellosis still exists in the public  
bison herd and in wild elk at Yellowstone National Park. 
</P>
<P>
	After running afoul of federal brucellosis regulations, the  
Triple U ranch was quarantined in 1982, preventing sales of live 
buffalo. Instead, buffalo were slaughtered at the ranch, and the 
meat, hides and skulls were sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to rid the herd of brucellosis began in 1990. Holland  
negotiated a deal with the U.S. Agriculture Department to have 
Triple U get rid of around 1,500 infected buffalo in exchange for 
$2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of those animals, worth between $4 million and $5 million,  
were slaughtered for human consumption, since brucellosis does not 
affect meat. 
</P>
<P>
	No cattle herds in South Dakota have been infected by  
brucellosis since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) -- Maryland farmers, faced with new state  
regulations to curb nutrient runoff, are trying different methods 
to protect soil and water quality. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of Carroll County officials and state agriculture  
officials went on a tour this week of seven farms, ranging from a 
500,000-bird poultry operation to 90-head of cattle dairy farms. 
</P>
<P>
	The group toured a 2,400-hog farm near Taneytown, which features  
a 933,500-gallon earthen holding pond for manure and a homemade 
composting site. At a dairy farm in Melrose, they saw two concrete 
manure storage pits, one costing $66,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Several farms had solar-powered water troughs and were using  
contour crop farming techniques. Farmers also had planted forested 
buffers and planted grassy waterways aimed at filtering run-off 
from farms, increasing natural habitat and shading stream. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
