<HEADLINE> Personal Bankruptcies Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Personal bankruptcies declined 2 percent  
during the 12 months ending June 30, the first yearly decrease 
since 1995, the Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Personal bankruptcies in the year ending June 30, numbering  
1,352,030, accounted for 97 percent of new bankruptcies. The total 
number of bankruptcies in that period was 1,391,964. 
</P>
<P>
	New bankruptcies filed during the second quarter of 1999 dropped  
to 345,956 from a record 373,460 during the quarter a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``While bankruptcy filings are still very high, the trend over  
the past six months suggests that 1999 will fall short of last 
year's record pace,'' said Sam Gerdano, executive director of the 
American Bankruptcy Institute. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
