<HEADLINE> Mets Claim Tam Off Waivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Right-hander Jeff Tam was claimed by the Mets on  
waivers from the Cleveland Indians on Wednesday and will rejoin New 
York for the second time this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's another arm coming out of the bullpen and we know him  
pretty well,'' Mets general manager Steve Phillips said. ``He's the 
kind of guy who can give us an inning or a couple innings if we 
need it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tam, 29, had surgery Dec. 11 to remove bone chips from his right  
elbow and started the season on the disabled list. After a 
rehabilitation assignment at Norfolk of the Triple-A International 
League, he was designated for assignment June 11 and claimed by 
Cleveland seven days later. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like Tam,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``I was  
disappointed when he left. He threw strikes and did some good work 
for us last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tam was 1-1 with a 6.28 ERA in 15 games with the Mets last  
season. He made his only appearance with the Indians on July 4, 
allowing three runs, two hits and one walk in one-third of an 
inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Dan Murray was optioned to Norfolk to make room. He  
made his major league debut Monday against Los Angeles, allowing 
three runs and four hits in two innings during a 9-2 loss. 
  	   	
</P>
