<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Allentown Co. Faulted for Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- An Allentown chemical company denied  
government allegations that it ignored safety at an industrial 
plant leveled by a deadly explosion in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Concept Sciences Inc. was cited Wednesday by the Occupational  
Safety and Health Administration for 20 alleged safety violations, 
including 11 willful violations. The agency proposed penalties of 
$641,200. 
</P>
<P>
	If OSHA's rules had been followed, ``it is more than likely this  
catastrophe would have been avoided,'' OSHA spokeswoman Kate Dugan 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Five workers died in the Feb. 19 blast.  
</P>
<P>
	A company news release Wednesday said: ``CSI emphatically denies  
that it has ever intentionally taken any action that was a known 
violation with `plain indifference to the law.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it has adequate safety and training. It had not  
yet decided whether to contest the citations and wouldn't comment 
further. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion at the industrial plant in Hanover Township near  
Allentown caused the walls of the 25-foot high building to buckle 
and collapse inward, dumping tons of concrete and steel on workers 
inside and causing nearly $5 million in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	It happened in a 2,500-gallon fiberglass reinforced charge tank  
containing about 750 pounds of the hazardous chemical 
hydroxylamine, a volatile chemical used by semiconductor makers and 
pharmaceutical companies, OSHA said. The tank was used in the 
distillation process. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency could not determine what ignited the tank, since the  
building was destroyed by the blast. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
