<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia County Bets on Casino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPARTA, Ga. (AP) -- The economic tide that has buoyed much of the  
Southeast this decade has left Hancock County beached on an 
economic sandbar. 
</P>
<P>
	County leaders have tried everything to attract jobs -- any jobs  
for a population that is overwhelmingly poor and black. They've 
begged for projects no one else wanted: poultry processing plants, 
a landfill, even a waste incinerator. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the eastern Georgia county, located between Atlanta and  
Augusta, is going after the jackpot -- building the state's first 
full-scale casino. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no hope here. This has given everybody hope,'' said  
Allen Haywood, editor of the Sparta Ishmaelite, the county's weekly 
newspaper. ``The more I hear about this project, I don't think 
there's another thing in this world that would be better to come 
here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Building the casino -- along with a 350-room hotel and a golf  
course on a proposed Indian reservation -- would give the local 
economy a multimillion-dollar boost, county officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	And no amount of Bible-thumping by religious opponents or  
opposition from state officials -- including the governor -- has 
discouraged folks in Sparta from seizing the opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no jobs in this county for people to work,'' said  
71-year-old Lavonia Bennett. ``With all the jobs they say it's 
going to have, they can go to work instead of sitting around on the 
corner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cotton plantations once thrived in Hancock County, but farming  
waned after World War II and few industries stepped in to take its 
place. The county's population is 82 percent black, the highest 
percentage in Georgia and the fourth highest in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The storefronts along Sparta's Broad Street, with their cracked  
paint and faded awnings, are dotted with padlocked doors and 
darkened windows. The Hardee's restaurant at the end of the block 
is closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 30 percent of the approximately 9,500 people in Hancock  
County live below the poverty level. The unemployment rate is 10.7 
percent -- more than double the state average. 
</P>
<P>
	Latimere Harris worries that his 18-year-old daughter, an  
aspiring mechanic, will have to leave town to get a job. ``We need 
something in here,'' said Harris, 69. ``The young people ain't got 
nothing to do around here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	News that the tiny Kialegee tribe in Oklahoma had expressed an  
interest in establishing a casino in Hancock County sounded like 
the ticket out of poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kialegee, a tribe of about 450, claim that old treaties show  
they were native to Georgia and relocated to Oklahoma as part of 
the Creek Nation. The tribe owns no land in Oklahoma, so it wants 
to buy land here and have it held in trust by the federal 
government, turning it into a reservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribe had tried several times to build casinos elsewhere but  
had been rebuffed, most recently in Carroll County, Ga., on the 
Alabama line. 
</P>
<P>
	The reception has been very different here.  
</P>
<P>
	Residents packed the courthouse last month to hear the sales  
pitch from the Kialegee. The tribe said up to 3,500 jobs would be 
created in the first year alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been crushed down, stepped on and abused for years. We  
need jobs,'' said Betty Hill, chairwoman of the Hancock County 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Political opposition and federal rules aimed at discouraging  
gambling on new reservations stand in their way. But the tribe 
promises a huge windfall if the county and the state play along -- 
up to $1.25 billion over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved, Georgia would become the 27th state to have some  
form of gambling on Indian reservations. There are 260 casinos or 
bingo halls operating on reservations, compared with 70 in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	A Las Vegas casino operator already has agreed to put up the  
money to buy about 1,700 acres in Hancock County and build the 
casino in exchange for a share of the profits and the right to run 
the casino for up to seven years, said Ken Baldwin, who represents 
the tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be difficult to build the project without the support of  
Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes, who has said he doesn't want casino 
gambling in Georgia. Federal regulations allow tribes to bypass 
governors in some cases, but officials say it's unlikely that will 
happen in Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the governor of the state has said `I do not want a casino  
in my state,' that pretty much puts an end to it,'' said Rex 
Hackler, spokesman for the Bureau of Indian Affairs in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Even local ministers who oppose the casino say they have little  
reason to fear the gambling hall will ever open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like people in Hancock County in the past have put  
all their eggs in one basket when looking for economic answers. 
They haven't panned out and I don't think this one will either,'' 
said the Rev. Jerry Bradley, pastor of Sparta Baptist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to say there's a curse here in Hancock County,''  
he said. ``But it's strange how many things have not worked.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990811.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 17:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
