<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Rep Visits Barry Sanders' Dad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIVERSITY CENTER, Mich. (AP) -- A representative of the Detroit  
Lions went to Wichita, Kan., to visit with the father of recently 
retired running back Barry Sanders. But the elder Sanders said 
today his son wasn't a big topic of conversation. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Hughes, director of security for the Lions, has been at  
William Sanders' home for two days. 
</P>
<P>
	Lions spokesman Bill Keenist said today that Hughes was visiting  
Sanders as a Lions official but he would not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has a relationship with the family and beyond that I'm not  
going to make any further comment,'' Keenist said. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked why Hughes would leave in the middle of training  
camp, Keenist repeated his statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit News reported that Hughes apparently was hoping to  
set up further talks between Barry Sanders, his family and the 
team's front office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it's the start of something good,'' Sanders' father  
told the News. 
</P>
<P>
	But today, Sanders said Hughes just came down to spend some time  
with him. He said the two are friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``We discuss Barry once in a while,'' Sanders said. But he said  
he didn't think the Lions had sent Hughes specifically to discuss 
his son's football future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't discuss my son's future because I don't know what my  
son's intentions are,'' he said. He said he hasn't talked with his 
son since before Barry Sanders announced his retirement last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes, who retired from the Detroit Police Department as an  
inspector, has headed the Lions' security department for four 
years. He is a former member of the Harlem Globetrotters. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders announced his retirement July 28, the day before the  
team reported to training camp at Saginaw Valley State. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Sanders said his desire to quit football outweighed  
his desire to play. When camp opened July 29, Sanders was in London 
on a European vacation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
