<HEADLINE> Dollar Mixed, Gold Rises in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading today. Gold rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0661 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0733 Tuesday. Later, in afternoon trading in New York, the 
euro traded at $1.0644. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europs, compared with late Tuesday,  
included; 115.17 Japanese yen, up from 114.67; 1.5020 Swiss francs, 
up from 1.4901; 1.4924 Canadian dollars, down from 1.5005. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6108, down from $1.6126.  
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading in New York, the dollar bought 115.17 yen,  
and the pouns was worth 1.6090. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8346 German marks, up from 1.8223; 
6.1529 French francs, up from 6.1116; 2.0671 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0532; 1,816,22 Italian lire, up from 1,804.03. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $257.80 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$257.00 on Tuesday. In Zurich the bid price was $257.45, up from 
$256.65. Gold fell 30 cents in Hong Kong closed to $257.15. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.33 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.20. 
  	   	
</P>
