<HEADLINE> Gymnastics Champ Has Surgery on Knee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Olympic gymnastics champion Dominique Moceanu  
underwent surgery Wednesday to treat a malformation on her right 
knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the type of thing where you have kind of achy knee  
problems,'' Dr. Jack Jensen told KPRC-TV. ``It doesn't go out on 
you, it's not a ligament thing. It just keeps bothering her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The malformation wasn't caused by gymnastics, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Jensen, who performed the operation, said Moceanu will begin  
rehabilitation as early as Thursday but won't be at full strength 
for four months. 
</P>
<P>
	She is scheduled to return to her training base in Colorado  
Springs within the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Jensen said Moceanu has a good chance of rehabilitating the knee  
in time to qualify for the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Austraila. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's at the level right now where she's got skill,'' he said.  
``She can do a lot and still shelter that knee over the next few 
months and come back strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moceanu, who most recently won the individual all-around title  
in the 1998 Goodwill Games, has said she hoped that by giving 
herself time to rehabilitate she would still qualify for the 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The tiny gymnast, who at the age of 14 captivated millions  
during the 1996 Olympics, returned to training in late February 
after a high-profile rift with her parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Last October, Moceanu sued for her independence, saying her  
father, Dumitru Moceanu, had squandered the money she had earned in 
a 10-year professional career. 
</P>
<P>
	The gymnast reached a confidential financial settlement with her  
parents and ended a protective order against her father. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
