<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornadoes Rare in Utah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Tornadoes are often associated with the Midwest, but the  
swirling columns of air and debris can form anywhere if the right 
atmospheric conditions exist. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether they touch down in Kansas or downtown Salt Lake City,  
twisters need several ingredients found only in large 
thunderstorms: Warm, moist air near the ground, cool air aloft and 
winds that speed up and change direction. 
</P>
<P>
	Some regions of the United States are more vulnerable.  
</P>
<P>
	The Midwest is in an area where warm, wet air from the Gulf of  
Mexico collides with the fast-moving and cooler winds from the 
Rocky Mountains or Canada. Twisters are most likely to occur there 
in the spring and summer. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, meteorologists in Salt Lake City watched the same  
conditions develop over their state. A severe thunderstorm watch 
was issued at 12:48 p.m.; the twister touched down about seven 
minutes later. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw what was going on,'' said David Toronto, a  
meteorologist for the National Weather Service. ``But to look at it 
and say there's a tornado and it's going to hit downtown -- we 
didn't have that information because of the rapid development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It remained on the ground for about five minutes, he said. Wind  
speeds were estimated to be about 100 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Tornadoes are rare in Utah. Thirty-two have been reported in the  
last 25 years, said Tim Shy, a researcher at the University of 
Illinois at Champaign-Urbana. Oklahoma recorded 1,326 over the same 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Downtown areas also offer no special protection, he said. There  
just happen to be more rural than densely urbanized areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes we get a `Wizard of Oz' mentality that they occur in  
the middle of nowhere,'' Shy said. ``There have been enough counter 
examples here recently as Oklahoma City, Nashville and downtown 
Miami got hit in the last few years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether a tornado strikes a building or a barn, the most  
dangerous aspect is the debris carried by high winds. Researchers 
have discounted theories that pressure differences cause structures 
to explode. 
</P>
<P>
	``The damage comes from wind and flying debris, and we saw that  
downtown today,'' Toronto said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
