<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suzanne Somers Plans To Stay Thin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Suzanne Somers knows she's under a lot of pressure to stay thin.  
But she vows that she will never ``diet'' again. 
</P>
<P>
	As the author of two weight-loss books and pitchwoman for her  
ThighMaster and ButtMaster exercise products, Somers, 52, knows the 
public keeps an eye on her figure -- watching what she eats and how 
she exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't be a messenger without following through,'' she said  
in a telephone interview from her Los Angeles office. 
</P>
<P>
	Years ago, while on the set of the hit '70s sitcom, ``Three's  
Company,'' Somers said she would make daily trips to the food table 
for a cookie or a piece of chocolate with no adverse effect on her 
waistline. 
</P>
<P>
	When she turned 40, she began gaining weight.  
</P>
<P>
	``My metabolism betrayed me,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	After taking an ineffective ride on the ``diet roller coaster,''  
she began meeting with nutritionists and doctors who explained that 
as people age, it takes them longer to digest food. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar and high-starch carbohydrates, like white flour pasta and  
breads, were responsible for her weight gain, she said, because 
they store energy as fat cells. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1992, she has followed a system of eating a lot of  
protein, fruits, vegetables and whole grains. ``For the last few 
years, it's been my great secret: How do I eat so much and stay 
thin?'' she said. She now weighs about 116 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Somers started writing down recipes on scraps of paper and  
photocopying them to give to friends. Then, at the urging of 
husband Alan Hamel, she put the recipes in a book. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eat Great, Lose Weight'' was published in 1996. Somers' new  
book, ``Get Skinny on Fabulous Food,'' was just published (Crown, 
$24). Both books are best sellers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Get Skinny'' contains recipes for Moroccan Chicken with  
Preserved Lemon Rinds, Marinated Grilled Butterflied Leg of Lamb, 
and Chocolate Souffle with Whipped Cream and Hot Chocolate Sauce. 
(She does not include nutritional information with her recipes.) 
</P>
<P>
	She believes in ``food combining,'' which she defines as eating  
certain foods together and keeping others separate to aid 
digestion. She also believes in eliminating sugar and high-starch 
foods. 
</P>
<P>
	And she has a simple message for scientists who might discount  
her methods: ``science schmience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her system works, and that's what matters, she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Somers follows a regular exercise routine, meeting with a  
trainer for about 35 minutes three times a week and throwing her 
ThighMaster into her suitcase when she travels. 
</P>
<P>
	Her life is busy. In addition to writing books and running her  
fitness business, she also appears on ``Candid Camera,'' which airs 
on CBS. Somers said she uses cooking as ``a kind of Zen'' that 
allows her to be focused and creative, yet relaxed. 
</P>
<P>
	She traces her love of cooking to her childhood, when she made  
her first beef stroganoff at 9. She enjoys preparing meals for 
guests and has fed 40 people at a party. 
</P>
<P>
	Does she consider herself an actress first, an author, even a  
chef? 
</P>
<P>
	``No one has a career like mine,'' she said. ``I'm a  
hyphenate.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
