<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swapping Real Estate May Save Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Here's a problem you may share. You have  
accumulated rental property in a distant state that has increased 
substantially in value, but as you head into retirement you would 
rather own rental property closer to home. 
</P>
<P>
	Or you want to sell farmland in the Midwest so you can buy an  
apartment building in New York City. Or you own an office building 
you want to sell so you can buy a vacation home in the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	In all of these cases, assuming the property you own has  
increased in value, you normally would have to pay taxes on the 
gain made from the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer to your tax problem may lie in a less-than-familiar  
tax strategy known as a 1031 like-kind exchange, according to 
Michelle Augustine, an academic associate at the College for 
Financial Planning. 
</P>
<P>
	``The benefit of a 1031 exchange is you can swap a piece of  
property for another and avoid the capital-gains taxes. You also 
can use it to consolidate several pieces of property into a single 
property, or swap raw land that doesn't produce much income for 
income-producing property such as rental homes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Augustine cautions, this is a tax strategy you will  
want professional advice for. If it isn't done right, it can end up 
costing you money instead of saving money. 
</P>
<P>
	First, understand that you can exchange only investment-type  
property for other investment-type property: farms, ranches, 
commercial property, rental homes or apartments, raw land. 
</P>
<P>
	You can't swap the property for a new personal residence, or  
swap your current residence for another residence. The latter isn't 
much of problem anymore for most people, Augustine notes, because 
homeowners can protect up to $500,000 in home-sale profits from 
capital-gains taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	But retirees or people heading into retirement may well have  
accumulated investment property, such as the family farm or rental 
property. Its sale could trigger substantial capital-gains taxes. 
By exchanging the investment property for other investment 
property, you can delay or even avoid the taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, suppose you want to sell an office building and use  
the proceeds to buy a vacation home. First, consult with your tax 
or financial adviser to determine whether both properties are 
suitable for a 1031 exchange (1031, incidentally, refers to a 
section of the tax code). 
</P>
<P>
	Augustine especially cautions about the adjusted cost basis of  
the property -- the price you paid for the property plus capital 
improvements, minus depreciation. Significant depreciation of the 
property over the years could prove less favorable in this type of 
transaction, she says, and could even result in an exchange 
becoming taxable. The tax bracket you are in also is a factor, she 
adds. The higher your tax bracket, generally the more beneficial a 
like-kind exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	If an exchange makes financial sense, the next step is to find  
an intermediary -- technically referred to as an accommodator -- who 
handles the exchange, for a fee. Like-kind exchanges can be done 
directly between two parties, but typically it's tough to find 
someone who wants to swap straight across. Whoever owns the 
vacation home you want probably doesn't want your office building. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, you sell your office building and the cash from the  
sale goes to the intermediary, who holds it in escrow and 
eventually uses it to purchase the vacation home you want, which 
you must rent out so it is treated as investment property. 
</P>
<P>
	Augustine says you must identify the property you want to swap  
for (called replacement property) within 45 days from the close of 
escrow of the property you sold (relinquished property). You have 
180 days from closing to acquire the replacement property. If you 
don't meet these deadlines, the transaction will be treated as a 
sale and you'll end up paying capital-gains taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with a successful like-kind exchange, you may end up paying  
some capital-gains taxes. For example, your office building might 
be worth more than the vacation home you want to swap for. The 
leftover cash from the sale that wasn't used to buy the vacation 
home is distributed to you, and you must pay capital-gains tax on 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	If you eventually sell the vacation home you swapped your office  
building for, you'll have to pay capital gains taxes, though you've 
received the financial benefit of postponing taxes. However, you 
might be able to avoid the taxes entirely, Augustine says. 
</P>
<P>
	One solution: you could leave the home in your estate and pass  
it on to your heirs. They in turn could sell it potentially free of 
tax. Or you could move into the vacation home you've been renting 
out, make it your principal residence for at least two years and 
then sell the home. You then could protect gains up to $500,000 
from taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``People need to be cautious about doing like-kind exchanges,  
and they need good consultation,'' Augustine says. ``But they also 
need to look seriously at doing this. So often people miss 
opportunities to do something with their property that might 
provide tax benefits.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
