<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airline Bomb-Screening Lapses Cited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Bomb detection machines installed at the nation's  
major airports are being underutilized by many airlines, according 
to a published report. 
</P>
<P>
	The CTX 5000 machines are intended to scan the baggage of people  
identified as high security risks by a passenger-screening process. 
</P>
<P>
	The CTX 5000 is being installed in 100 airports nationwide.  
</P>
<P>
	It can process 225 bags an hour, but a government audit found  
some airlines run as few as four bags an hour through the $1 
million machines, the Chicago Tribune reported in today's editions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The utilization is starting to increase, but not at the rate  
that we and the inspector general's office would like to see,'' 
said Monte Belger, the acting deputy director of the Federal 
Aviation Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA's immediate goal is for the airlines to run 2 percent to  
20 percent of all checked baggage -- depending on perceived security 
risk. 
</P>
<P>
	But nationally, the CTX 5000s now screen less than 1 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Airlines complain that widespread use of the scanners will  
disrupt flight timetables because of the additional time it takes 
to complete the screening process. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA says scanning takes 15 seconds or less per bag on  
average -- longer if possible contraband is detected or if the unit 
gives off a false alarm. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of the Air Transport Association, which  
represents the carriers, declined to give interviews about the CTX 
5000, citing security concerns, the Tribune reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are issues that we believe are not beneficially aired in  
public,'' said John Meenan, the association's senior vice president 
for industry policy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
