<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates Say Goodbye to Garcia, Ward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Freddy Garcia and Turner Ward may have played  
their final games for the Pittsburgh Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, a power-hitting infielder-outfielder who began the 1998  
season as the Pirates' starting third baseman, was designated for 
assignment Wednesday to clear a roster spot for shortstop Mike 
Benjamin. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin broke his left index finger July 22 against the Cubs.  
</P>
<P>
	Garcia, 27, must clear options before he can join a Pirates farm  
club. If he is not claimed, the Pirates have 10 days to trade him, 
release him or reassign him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't get to play much over here,'' he said. ``It was tough  
because I wasn't playing very much. I would like to go to another 
team where maybe I could play more. They just have a lot of guys 
over her and they can't play everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia was batting .233 with six homers and 23 RBIs as a  
part-time third baseman and outfielder and was in a 2-for-18 slump. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-handed hitting Garcia showed flashes of power -- he hit  
a combined 31 homers with the Pirates (9) and Nashville (22) -- last 
season -- but had trouble hitting for average in the majors and was 
below-average defensively. 
</P>
<P>
	He has never been able to channel his considerable power into a  
fulltime job. He would often hit a 420-foot homer, then go into a 
slide. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got upper-deck power, and you don't like to give up on a  
player with that kind of power,'' manager Gene Lamont said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward, the 34-year-old outfielder who has been on the disabled  
list most of the season, cleaned out his Three Rivers Stadium 
locker after ending his rehabilitation assignment at Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	He has used up all of his rehabilitation time, and the Pirates  
have no plans to activate him soon, even though he told trainer 
Kent Biggerstaff that his sore right knee feels better than it has 
in months. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Cam Bonifay said Ward will continue his  
rehabilitation at his home in Saraland, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward hit .209 in 91 at-bats earlier this season and, despite  
having more walks (13) than strikeouts (nine), scored only two 
runs. He was 1-for-15 as the Pirates' chief pinch-hitter in April 
and early May. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward's situation would seem to be much like that of infielder  
Doug Strange, who cleaned out his locker in spring training before 
undergoing season-ending right elbow surgery. There is almost no 
chance he will play for the Pirates again. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward played previously for Cleveland, Toronto and Milwaukee. He  
was out of baseball, except for coaching his son's T-ball team, 
when the Pirates offered him a minor league contract in April 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The outfielder was called up later this season and was one of  
the pleasant surprises on a team that stayed in the division race 
until the final week of September, batting .353 in 167 at-bats with 
seven homers and 33 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward's average slipped to .262 with nine homers and 46 RBIs in  
282 at-bats as the Pirates' fourth outfielder last season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
